irus pandemic in the United States by state|Maryland]]\n[[Category:2020 in Maryland|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Maryland]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Maryland]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMarch 30:Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Maryland"}
{"title_page": "Samuel Merrill (Indiana)", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Samuel Merrill\n| image = Samuel Merrill (1792-1855).jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| constituency_AM = [[Switzerland County, Indiana|Switzerland County]]\n| assembly = Indiana General\n| term_start = December 6, 1819 \n| term_end = December 2, 1822 \n| predecessor =\tRalph Cotton<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitolandwashington.com/offices/all-offices/|title=State Representatives from Switzerland County\u2013All Holders|date=5 March 2015|website=capitolandwashington.com|accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref> \n| successor = William B. Chamberlain \n| office2 = [[Indiana State Treasurer]]\n| term_start2 = 1822\n| term_end2 = February 10, 1834\n| predecessor2 = [[Daniel Crosby Lane]]\n| successor2 = [[Nathan B. Palmer]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1792|10|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Peacham, Vermont]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1855|8|24|1792|10|29}}\n| death_place = [[Indianapolis, Indiana]], U.S.\n| spouse=Lydia Jane Anderson (m. 1818\u201347);<br>Elizabeth Young (m. 1849\u2013 ) \n| children =ten, including [[Catharine Merrill]]\n}}\n\n'''Samuel Merrill''' (October 29, 1792 &ndash; August 24, 1855), a native of [[Peacham, Vermont]], was an early lawyer and leading citizen of [[Indiana]], who served as [[Indiana State Treasurer|state treasurer]] from 1822 to 1834. Merrill attended [[Dartmouth College]], and in 1816 settled in [[Vevay, Indiana]], where he established a law practice and served in the [[Indiana General Assembly]] as a representative from [[Switzerland County, Indiana|Switzerland County]] (1821\u201322). Merrill resigned his position as state treasurer in 1834 to become the president of the State Bank of Indiana (1834\u201344); he also served as the president of the [[Jeffersonville, Madison and Indianapolis Railroad|Madison and Indianapolis Railroad Company]] (1844\u201348) and head of the Merrill Publishing Company, which later became the [[Bobbs-Merrill Company]]. In addition to his government service and business ventures, Merrill was the second president of the [[Indiana Historical Society]] (1835\u201348), a founder and trustee of [[Wabash College]], and an elder in the [[Second Presbyterian Church (Indianapolis, Indiana)|Second Presbyterian]] and Fourth Presbyterian churches in [[Indianapolis]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMerrill was born on October 29, 1792, in [[Peacham, Vermont]], the second son of Jesse and Priscilla (Kimball) Merrill.<ref name=IMH53-54>{{cite journal|author=Catharine Merrill |title=Samuel Merrill, Indiana's Second State Treasurer (1792-1855) | journal =Indiana Magazine of History | volume =12 | issue =1 | pages =53\u201354|publisher=[[Indiana University]]| location =Bloomington | date=March 1916 |url= https://scholarworks.iu.edu/journals/index.php/imh/article/view/5961/5642| accessdate =}}</ref> Jesse Merrill was a farmer and town officer who also served for years as a member of the Vermont legislature; his wife, Priscilla, was a homemaker and the mother of seven children (six boys and one girl).<ref name=IMH53-54/>\n\nMerrill received his early education at Peacham Academy and attended [[Dartmouth College]], but left before graduating.<ref name=IHS-Bio>\"Biographical Sketch\" in {{cite web| author= | title =Samuel Merrill Papers, 1818\u20131934 | work = | publisher =Indiana Historical Society | date =January 2, 2002 | url = http://www.indianahistory.org/our-collections/collection-guides/samuel-merrill-papers-1812-1934.pdf | format =pdf | accessdate =November 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Sulgrove58>{{cite book|author=Berry R. Sulgrove|title=History of Indianapolis and Marion County Indiana |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofindiana00sulgrich| publisher = L. H. Everts and Company |location= Philadelphia | year = 1884| page=[https://archive.org/details/historyofindiana00sulgrich/page/58 58]  | isbn= }}</ref> In 1813 Merrill followed his older brother, James, to [[York, Pennsylvania]], where he spent three years [[reading law|studying law]] and teaching school. In 1816, at the age of twenty-four, Merrill settled in [[Vevay, Indiana|Vevay]], [[Switzerland County, Indiana]]. After his [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admission to the bar]] in 1817, Merrell established a law practice in Vevay.<ref name=IHS-Bio/><ref>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\", p. 55.</ref>\n\n==Marriage and family==\nIn 1818 Merrill married Lydia Jane Anderson, the daughter of Robert and Catherine (Dumont) Anderson of Vevay. Samuel and Lydia Jane Merrill had ten children: Jane (1819\u20131911), Pricilla, [[Catharine Merrill|Catharine]] \"Kate\" (1824\u20131900), Julia Dumont, Samuel Jr., Mary, Anna Maria \"Mina\", and three others (Sophia, \"Jimmie,\" and Elizabeth) who died young. Merrill's wife, Lydia Jane, died in 1847.<ref>{{cite book | authors=Catharine Merrill and Katharine Merrill Graydon| title =Catharine Merrill, Life and Letters: Collected and Arranged | publisher =The Mitchell Company | series = | volume = | edition = | year =1934 | location =Greenfield, IN | page=31 | url =  | OCLC=7102104}}</ref><ref name=Stoler>{{cite journal| author=Mildred C. Stoler| title =The Removal of the State Capital to Indianapolis | journal =Indiana Magazine of History | volume =27 | issue =3 | pages =240\u201343 | publisher =Indiana University | location =Bloomington | date =September 1931| url = https://scholarworks.iu.edu/journals/index.php/imh/article/view/6614/6949| accessdate =November 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author=| title =In Memoriam: Jane Merrill Ketcham, February 2, 1819 \u2013September 21, 1911 | publisher =| year =1911 | location = | pages = | url = | OCLC=23162975}} (Collections of the Indiana Historical Society.)</ref>\n\nIn 1849 he married Elizabeth Young of [[Madison, Indiana]], two years after the death of his first wife.<ref name=IMH56>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" p. 56.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMerrill's career included government service as a representative in the [[Indiana General Assembly]] (1821\u201322) and as the [[Indiana State Treasurer]] (1822\u201334). He was also involved in banking and other business ventures. Merrill was president of [[Bank of Indiana|State Bank of Indiana]] (1834\u201344) and the [[Jeffersonville, Madison and Indianapolis Railroad|Madison and Indianapolis Railroad Company]] (1844\u201348). He also owned an Indianapolis bookstore and publishing company that later became the [[Bobbs-Merrill Company]].\n\n===State legislator and treasurer===\nMerrill moved to [[Vevay, Indiana]], in 1816, and was elected to the [[Indiana General Assembly]] in 1821 as the representative of [[Switzerland County, Indiana|Switzerland County]].<ref>Dunn, v. I, p. 368.</ref> While serving in the state legislature, Merrill was elected as [[Indiana State Treasurer]].<ref name=Sulgrove58/> He succeeded Daniel Crosby Lane as state treasurer on December 28, 1822. Merrill moved to [[Corydon, Indiana]], and was reelected for three more consecutive terms, serving until February 10, 1834, when [[Nathan B. Palmer]] succeeded him.<ref name =IMH56/><ref>{{cite book | author=Arville Funk| title =A Sketchbook of Indiana History | publisher =Christian Book Press | series = | volume = | edition = | year =1969 | location =Rochester, Indiana | page=210  | OCLC=49694}}</ref>\n\nAfter the decision was made to relocate the seat of state government on January 20, 1824, Merrill had a role in helping to the name the new state capital. He seconded the motion to adopt the name of [[Indianapolis]] for the state capital of Indiana.<ref name=Dunn364>{{cite book |author=[[Jacob Piatt Dunn]] |title=Indiana and Indianans: A History of the Aboriginal and Territorial Indiana and the Century of Statehood |publisher=American Historical Society |location=Chicago and New York |year=1919 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s8wtRblsXksC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Indiana+and+Indianans.+American+Historical+Society.&source=gbs_summary_r&cad=0| series = | volume =I | edition =| page=364| OCLC=2470354}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author=William Wesley Woollen | title =Biographical and Historical Sketches of Early Indiana | publisher =Arno Press | series =Mid-American Frontier | volume = | edition =reprint | year =1975 | location =New York | pages =367 | OCLC=1218324}}</ref> Merrill also oversaw the transfer of the state treasury and state government's records to [[Indianapolis]] from [[Corydon, Indiana|Corydon]]. The arduous task included Merrill's and his young family's eleven-day journey of about {{convert|160|mile|km}} by horseback and wagon caravan from Corydon to the new state capital in November 1824.<ref name=\"IMH56\" /><ref name=\"Stoler\" /> To complicate matters, no paved road existed along the caravan's path at that time and in some places a trail had to be cut through the dense forests in order to move northward.<ref>Dunn, v. I, pp. 367\u201371.</ref>\n\nMerrill's caravan of four, four-horse wagons and two or three saddle horses brought the state treasury, governmental records, a printing press, and furniture for the Indiana General Assembly, the Indiana Supreme Court, and the state's executive offices, as well as two families, including his own, their personal goods, and implements and supplies for the caravan. He also arranged for the transfer of the state archives and state library to Indianapolis.<ref>Merrill's bill for the move was $65.35, plus a separate bill of $9.50 to move the state library to Indianapolis. The Indiana General Assembly allocated Merrill $100 for his personal services in arranging the move. See Dunn, v. I, pp. 367\u201371.</ref> After relocating to Indianapolis, Merrill and his family lived in a two-story brick building, later demolished, that the state government had constructed at the southwest corner of Washington Street and present-day Capitol Avenue to house the state treasurer's office and residence, as well as the state auditor's office.<ref>Dunn, v. I, p. 370.</ref>\n\nMerrill continued to serve as state treasurer until 1834, when he was named president of the [[Bank of Indiana|State Bank of Indiana]]. He was also a partner in the trading firm of Yandes and Merrill and was active in other business ventures and civic affairs.<ref name=IHS-Bio/>\n\n===Bank president===\n[[File:Onedollarbanknotefrombankofindiana(1834).JPG|thumb|left|A one dollar bank note from the [[Bank of Indiana]] featuring a portrait engraving of Merrill (left)]]\n\nWhen the State Bank of Indiana was founded in 1834, the Indiana General Assembly choose Samuel Merrill as the bank's first president. Following his appointment, Merrill resigned his position of state treasurer. The ''[[Indianapolis News]]'' reported on July 15, 1911: \"His honesty and splendid record made him a man to inspire confidence in the bank.\" Merrill visited all thirteen of the bank's branches twice each year, traveling on horseback to personally examine their accounts and ledgers. It was said that he was able to review columns of figures with machine-like rapidity and accuracy.<ref name=IMH56-57>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" pp. 56\u201357.</ref>\n\n===Railroad company president===\nMerrill served as president of the Madison and Indianapolis Railroad Company from 1844 to 1848.<ref name =IMH56-57/> The state legislature initially established it as a state-owned railroad on January 27, 1836, as one of the first rail lines in the state. The railroad was salvaged following the collapse of the state's [[Indiana Mammoth Internal Improvement Act|internal improvement programs]] and transferred to private ownership on June 20, 1842.<ref name=Netzlof>{{cite web | author=Robert T. Netzlof | title=Corporate Genealogy: Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway, The Panhandle  | work = | publisher =  | date =August 23, 1999 | url=http://rnetzlof.pennsyrr.com/corphist/pcc_stl.html  | accessdate=November 30, 2017}} (Rev. April 29, 2002.) From data originally published in: {{cite book | author=  | title = Valuation Reports | publisher =Interstate Commerce Commission | series = | volume =24 | edition = | year =1929 | location =Washington, D. C.  | pages = | url =  | isbn =}}</ref>\n\nWith additional funding from investors in the [[eastern United States|East]], Merrill expanded the railroad to complete the line, which extended from [[Madison, Indiana]], to Indianapolis. More track was laid during his first two years as president than had been done in the previous ten years of its state-owned management. Merrill resigned from the railroad in 1848 after disagreements with H. R. Hall, the rail line's superintendent.<ref name=IHS-Bio/><ref name =IMH56-57/>\n\n===Publisher===\nIn 1840 Merrill authored and published ''Chamberlain's Gazetteer of Indiana''.<ref>Dunn, v. I, p. 364.</ref> The following year he bought Hood and Noble's bookstore, one of four bookstores located in Indianapolis at that time, and oversaw its merger with his publishing business.<ref name =IMH56-57/>\n\nAfter Merrill's death in 1855, ownership of the Merrill Publishing Company passed to his son, Samuel Merrill Jr. After a merger with Bowen Stewart and Company in 1885, it became known as the Bowen-Merrill Company; in 1903 the firm was renamed the [[Bobbs-Merrill Company]].<ref name=GS56>{{cite book | author= Linda C. Gugin and James E. St. Clair, eds. | title =Indiana's 200: The People Who Shaped the Hoosier State | publisher =Indiana Historical Society Press| year =2015 | location =Indianapolis | page =56  | url = | isbn =978-0-87195-387-2}}</ref>\n\n==Other interests==\nIn addition to his banking and business ventures, Merrill, a temperance and abolitionist, was interested in education and religious work.<ref name=IHS-Bio/>\n\nMerrill was an early president of the Temperance Society of Indianapolis and a leader of the State Colonization Society.<ref name=IMH59>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" p. 59.</ref> He was also an outspoken [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]]. On one occasion, a pro-slavery man entered the Indianapolis branch of the State Bank of Indiana and challenged Merrill to a fist-fight, which Merrill won.<ref>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" p. 58.</ref>\n\nBecause of his interest in education, Merrill helped to establish [[Wabash College]] in 1833 and served as a trustee. Merrill also taught school in York, Pennsylvania, and on occasion in Vevay, Indiana, and served as the superintendent of Sunday Schools for Indianapolis's [[Second Presbyterian Church (Indianapolis, Indiana)|Second Presbyterian]] and Fourth Presbyterian churches. Merrill was also an elder in the Second and Fourth Presbyterian churches, the latter of which he helped establish in 1851. In addition, Merrill served as the second president of the [[Indiana Historical Society]] (1835\u201348).<ref name=IHS-Bio/><ref name=IMH59/>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nMerrill died on August 24, 1855, in Indianapolis at the age of sixty-two.<ref name =IMH57>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\", p. 57.</ref>\n\nMerrill was known among his contemporaries as an able businessman and for his sound judgment and attention to detail. Although Merrill was not a skilled orator, he was an avid storyteller and a valued counselor to his peers. Merrill was a modest individual, but he could also be impulsive in his actions and outspoken in expressing his opinions.<ref>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" pp. 57\u201359; Dunn, v. I, pp. 380\u201381.</ref>\n\nAs a public servant, Merrill oversaw the successful transfer in 1824 of the state treasury, state library, and state archives, which remain at [[Indianapolis]], the permanent seat of [[Indiana]]'s state government. He was also successful in banking, the railroad industry, and publishing. Merrill became the first president of the State [[Bank of Indiana]], which continued to operate until 1859, and a president of the [[Jeffersonville, Madison and Indianapolis Railroad|Madison and Indianapolis Railroad Company]], provider of an early rail transportation link to Indianapolis. He also founded the Merrill Publishing Company, which later became known as the [[Bobbs-Merrill Company]]. The publishing company's backlist of titles and publishing rights were sold to [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan Company]] in 1985.<ref name=Netzlof/><ref name=GS56/><ref>Dunn, v. I, pp. 367\u201371, 418; Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" pp. 56\u201359.</ref>\n\nMerrill was also an early civic leader, serving as the second president of the [[Indiana Historical Society]], whose headquarters remain in Indianapolis. He was also a founder and trustee of [[Wabash College]], which continues to operate in [[Crawfordsville, Indiana]]; and served as an elder in two of Indianapolis's  Presbyterian congregations. The [[Second Presbyterian Church (Indianapolis, Indiana)|Second Presbyterian Church]] is located on North Meridian Street;<ref>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" pp. 56\u201359; \"Biographical Sketch\" in {{cite web| author= | title =Samuel Merrill Papers, 1818\u20131934 | work = | publisher =Indiana Historical Society | date =January 2, 2002 | url = http://www.indianahistory.org/our-collections/collection-guides/samuel-merrill-papers-1812-1934.pdf | format =pdf | accessdate =November 29, 2017}} See also: {{cite book | author =George W. Geib | title =Lives Touched by Faith: Second Presbyterian Church, 150 Years | publisher =Mallory Lithography, Inc. | year =1987 | location =Indianapolis, Indiana | pages = | url = | isbn =0961935103}}</ref> the Fourth Presbyterian Church later merged with other congregations.<ref>Sulgrove, p. 396. See also: {{cite book | author =David J. Bodenhamer and Robert G. Barrows, eds.|title =The Encyclopedia of Indianapolis  | publisher =Indiana University Press | series = | volume = | edition = | year =1994 | location =Bloomington and Indianapolis | pages =1132\u201333| url =  | isbn =0-253-31222-1}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and tributes==\nThe [[Bank of Indiana|State Bank of Indiana]] featured an engraved image of Merrill on the front of its one dollar bank note in the late 1850s.<ref>Dunn, v. I, p. 412.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Indiana}}\n*[[History of Indiana]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* \"Biographical Sketch\" in {{cite web| author= | title =Samuel Merrill Papers, 1818\u20131934 | work = | publisher =Indiana Historical Society | date =January 2, 2002 | url = http://www.indianahistory.org/our-collections/collection-guides/samuel-merrill-papers-1812-1934.pdf | format =pdf | accessdate =November 29, 2017}}\n* {{cite book | author =Bodenhamer, David J., and Robert G. Barrows, eds.|title =The Encyclopedia of Indianapolis  | publisher =Indiana University Press | series = | volume = | edition = | year =1994 | location =Bloomington and Indianapolis | page =| url =  | isbn =0-253-31222-1}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s8wtRblsXksC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Indiana+and+Indianans.+American+Historical+Society.&source=gbs_summary_r&cad=0|title=Indiana and Indianans: A History of the Aboriginal and Territorial Indiana and the Century of Statehood |author=[[Jacob Piatt Dunn|Dunn, Jacob Piatt]]|publisher=American Historical Society|location=Chicago and New York |year=1919| volume =I | edition =| pages =| OCLC=2470354}}\n*{{cite book|title=A Sketchbook of Indiana History| author=Funk, Arville L|origyear=1969|year=1983|publisher=Christian Book Press|location=[[Rochester, Indiana]]|OCLC=49694}}\n* {{cite book | author =Geib, George W.  | title =Lives Touched by Faith: Second Presbyterian Church, 150 Years | publisher =Mallory Lithography, Inc. | year =1987 | location =Indianapolis, Indiana | pages = | url = | isbn =0961935103}}\n* {{cite book | author=Gugin, Linda C., and James E. St. Clair, eds. | title =Indiana's 200: The People Who Shaped the Hoosier State | publisher =Indiana Historical Society Press| year =2015 | location =Indianapolis | page=  | url = | isbn =978-0-87195-387-2}}\n* {{cite book | author=| title =In Memoriam: Jane Merrill Ketcham, February 2, 1819 \u2013September 21, 1911 | publisher =| year =1911 | location = | pages = | url = | OCLC=23162975}} (Collections of the Indiana Historical Society.)\n*{{cite journal|author=Merrill, Catharine |title=Samuel Merrill, Indiana\u2019s Second State Treasurer (1792-1855) |journal=Indiana Magazine of History | volume =12 | issue =1| location =Bloomington | date=March 1916 | pages =53\u201359|url=https://scholarworks.iu.edu/journals/index.php/imh/article/view/5961/5642| accessdate =December 4, 2017}}\n* {{cite book | authors=Merrill, Catharine, and Katharine Merrill Graydon| title =Catharine Merrill, Life and Letters: Collected and Arranged | publisher =The Mitchell Company | series = | volume = | edition = | year =1934 | location =Greenfield, IN | page= | url =  | OCLC=7102104}}\n* {{cite web | author=Netzlof, Robert T.| title=Corporate Genealogy: Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway, The Panhandle | work = | publisher =  | date =August 23, 1999 | url=http://rnetzlof.pennsyrr.com/corphist/pcc_stl.html  | accessdate=November 30, 2017}} (Rev. April 29, 2002.) \n* {{cite journal| author=Stoler, Mildred C. | title =The Removal of the State Capital to Indianapolis | journal =Indiana Magazine of History | volume =27 | issue =3 | pages =240\u201343 | publisher =Indiana University | location =Bloomington | date =September 1931| url = https://scholarworks.iu.edu/journals/index.php/imh/article/view/6614/6949\n| accessdate =November 28, 2017}}\n* {{cite book|author=Sulgrove, Berry R. |title=History of Indianapolis and Marion County Indiana |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofindiana00sulgrich | publisher = L. H. Everts and Company |location= Philadelphia | year = 1884| page=[https://archive.org/details/historyofindiana00sulgrich/page/58 58]  | isbn= }}\n* {{cite book | author=Woollen, William Wesley | title =Biographical and Historical Sketches of Early Indiana | publisher =Arno Press | series =Mid-American Frontier | volume = | edition =reprint | year =1975 | location =New York | pages = | OCLC=1218324}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archives.isl.lib.in.us/repositories/2/resources/206 Samuel Merrill collection, Rare Books and Manuscripts, Indiana State Library]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Daniel Crosby Lane]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Indiana State Treasurer|Treasurer of Indiana]]|years=1822\u20131834}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nathan B. Palmer]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Merrill, Samuel}}\n[[Category:1792 births]]\n[[Category:1855 deaths]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Wabash College]]\n[[Category:State treasurers of Indiana]]\n[[Category:People from Caledonia County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Members of the Indiana House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Indiana Historical Society]]\n[[Category:People from Vevay, Indiana]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Samuel Merrill\n| image = Samuel Merrill (1792-1855).jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| constituency_AM = [[Switzerland County, Indiana|Switzerland County]]\n| assembly = Indiana General\n| term_start = December 6, 1819 \n| term_end = December 2, 1822 \n| predecessor =\tRalph Cotton<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitolandwashington.com/offices/all-offices/|title=State Representatives from Switzerland County\u2013All Holders|date=5 March 2015|website=capitolandwashington.com|accessdate=24 March 2019}}</ref> \n| successor = William B. Chamberlain \n| office2 = [[Indiana State Treasurer]]\n| term_start2 = 1822\n| term_end2 = February 10, 1834\n| predecessor2 = [[Daniel Crosby Lane]]\n| successor2 = [[Nathan B. Palmer]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1792|10|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Peacham, Vermont]], U.S.\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1855|8|24|1792|10|29}}\n| death_place = [[Indianapolis, Indiana]], U.S.\n| spouse=Lydia Jane Anderson (m. 1818\u201347);<br>Elizabeth Young (m. 1849\u2013 ) \n| children =ten, including [[Catharine Merrill]]\n}}\n\n'''Samuel Merrill''' (October 29, 1792 &ndash; August 24, 1855), a native of [[Peacham, Vermont]], was an early lawyer and leading citizen of [[Indiana]], who served as [[Indiana State Treasurer|state treasurer]] from 1822 to 1834. Merrill attended [[Dartmouth College]], and in 1816 settled in [[Vevay, Indiana]], where he established a law practice and served in the [[Indiana General Assembly]] as a representative from [[Switzerland County, Indiana|Switzerland County]] (1821\u201322). Merrill resigned his position as state treasurer in 1834 to become the president of the State Bank of Indiana (1834\u201344); he also served as the president of the [[Jeffersonville, Madison and Indianapolis Railroad|Madison and Indianapolis Railroad Company]] (1844\u201348) and head of the Merrill Publishing Company, which later became the [[Bobbs-Merrill Company]]. In addition to his government service and business ventures, Merrill was the second president of the [[Indiana Historical Society]] (1835\u201348), a founder and trustee of [[Wabash College]], and an elder in the [[Second Presbyterian Church (Indianapolis, Indiana)|Second Presbyterian]] and Fourth Presbyterian churches in [[Indianapolis]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMerrill was born on October 29, 1792, in [[Peacham, Vermont]], the second son of Jesse and Priscilla (Kimball) Merrill.<ref name=IMH53-54>{{cite journal|author=Catharine Merrill |title=Samuel Merrill, Indiana's Second State Treasurer (1792-1855) | journal =Indiana Magazine of History | volume =12 | issue =1 | pages =53\u201354|publisher=[[Indiana University]]| location =Bloomington | date=March 1916 |url= https://scholarworks.iu.edu/journals/index.php/imh/article/view/5961/5642| accessdate =}}</ref> Jesse Merrill was a farmer and town officer who also served for years as a member of the Vermont legislature; his wife, Priscilla, was a homemaker and the mother of seven children (six boys and one girl).<ref name=IMH53-54/>\n\nMerrill received his early education at Peacham Academy before attending [[Dartmouth College]], but he did not graduate from the college.<ref name=IHS-Bio>\"Biographical Sketch\" in {{cite web| author= | title =Samuel Merrill Papers, 1818\u20131934 | work = | publisher =Indiana Historical Society | date =January 2, 2002 | url = http://www.indianahistory.org/our-collections/collection-guides/samuel-merrill-papers-1812-1934.pdf | format =pdf | accessdate =November 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Sulgrove58>{{cite book|author=Berry R. Sulgrove|title=History of Indianapolis and Marion County Indiana |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofindiana00sulgrich| publisher = L. H. Everts and Company |location= Philadelphia | year = 1884| page=[https://archive.org/details/historyofindiana00sulgrich/page/58 58]  | isbn= }}</ref> In 1813 Merrill followed his older brother, James, to [[York, Pennsylvania]], where he spent three years studying law and teaching school. In 1816, at the age of twenty-four, Merrill settled in [[Vevay, Indiana|Vevay]], [[Switzerland County, Indiana]]. After his admission to the Indiana bar in 1817, Merrell established a law practice in Vevay.<ref name=IHS-Bio/><ref>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\", p. 55.</ref>\n\n==Marriage and family==\nIn 1818 Merrill married Lydia Jane Anderson, the daughter of Robert and Catherine (Dumont) Anderson of Vevay. Samuel and Lydia Jane Merrill had ten children: Jane (1819\u20131911), Pricilla, [[Catharine Merrill|Catharine]] \"Kate\" (1824\u20131900), Julia Dumont, Samuel Jr., Mary, Anna Maria \"Mina\", and three others (Sophia, \"Jimmie,\" and Elizabeth) who died young. Merrill's wife, Lydia Jane, died in 1847.<ref>{{cite book | authors=Catharine Merrill and Katharine Merrill Graydon| title =Catharine Merrill, Life and Letters: Collected and Arranged | publisher =The Mitchell Company | series = | volume = | edition = | year =1934 | location =Greenfield, IN | page=31 | url =  | OCLC=7102104}}</ref><ref name=Stoler>{{cite journal| author=Mildred C. Stoler| title =The Removal of the State Capital to Indianapolis | journal =Indiana Magazine of History | volume =27 | issue =3 | pages =240\u201343 | publisher =Indiana University | location =Bloomington | date =September 1931| url = https://scholarworks.iu.edu/journals/index.php/imh/article/view/6614/6949| accessdate =November 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author=| title =In Memoriam: Jane Merrill Ketcham, February 2, 1819 \u2013September 21, 1911 | publisher =| year =1911 | location = | pages = | url = | OCLC=23162975}} (Collections of the Indiana Historical Society.)</ref>\n\nIn 1849 he married Elizabeth Young of [[Madison, Indiana]], two years after the death of his first wife.<ref name=IMH56>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" p. 56.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMerrill's career included government service as a representative in the [[Indiana General Assembly]] (1821\u201322) and as the [[Indiana State Treasurer]] (1822\u201334). He was also involved in banking and other business ventures. Merrill was president of [[Bank of Indiana|State Bank of Indiana]] (1834\u201344) and the [[Jeffersonville, Madison and Indianapolis Railroad|Madison and Indianapolis Railroad Company]] (1844\u201348). He also owned an Indianapolis bookstore and publishing company that later became the [[Bobbs-Merrill Company]].\n\n===State legislator and treasurer===\nMerrill moved to [[Vevay, Indiana]], in 1816, and was elected to the [[Indiana General Assembly]] in 1821 as the representative of [[Switzerland County, Indiana|Switzerland County]].<ref>Dunn, v. I, p. 368.</ref> While serving in the state legislature, Merrill was elected as [[Indiana State Treasurer]].<ref name=Sulgrove58/> He succeeded Daniel Crosby Lane as state treasurer on December 28, 1822. Merrill moved to [[Corydon, Indiana]], and was reelected for three more consecutive terms, serving until February 10, 1834, when [[Nathan B. Palmer]] succeeded him.<ref name =IMH56/><ref>{{cite book | author=Arville Funk| title =A Sketchbook of Indiana History | publisher =Christian Book Press | series = | volume = | edition = | year =1969 | location =Rochester, Indiana | page=210  | OCLC=49694}}</ref>\n\nAfter the decision was made to relocate the seat of state government on January 20, 1824, Merrill had a role in helping to the name the new state capital. He seconded the motion to adopt the name of [[Indianapolis]] for the state capital of Indiana.<ref name=Dunn364>{{cite book |author=[[Jacob Piatt Dunn]] |title=Indiana and Indianans: A History of the Aboriginal and Territorial Indiana and the Century of Statehood |publisher=American Historical Society |location=Chicago and New York |year=1919 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s8wtRblsXksC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Indiana+and+Indianans.+American+Historical+Society.&source=gbs_summary_r&cad=0| series = | volume =I | edition =| page=364| OCLC=2470354}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author=William Wesley Woollen | title =Biographical and Historical Sketches of Early Indiana | publisher =Arno Press | series =Mid-American Frontier | volume = | edition =reprint | year =1975 | location =New York | pages =367 | OCLC=1218324}}</ref> Merrill also oversaw the transfer of the state treasury and state government's records to [[Indianapolis]] from [[Corydon, Indiana|Corydon]]. The arduous task included Merrill's and his young family's eleven-day journey of about {{convert|160|mile|km}} by horseback and wagon caravan from Corydon to the new state capital in November 1824.<ref name=\"IMH56\" /><ref name=\"Stoler\" /> To complicate matters, no paved road existed along the caravan's path at that time and in some places a trail had to be cut through the dense forests in order to move northward.<ref>Dunn, v. I, pp. 367\u201371.</ref>\n\nMerrill's caravan of four, four-horse wagons and two or three saddle horses brought the state treasury, governmental records, a printing press, and furniture for the Indiana General Assembly, the Indiana Supreme Court, and the state's executive offices, as well as two families, including his own, their personal goods, and implements and supplies for the caravan. He also arranged for the transfer of the state archives and state library to Indianapolis.<ref>Merrill's bill for the move was $65.35, plus a separate bill of $9.50 to move the state library to Indianapolis. The Indiana General Assembly allocated Merrill $100 for his personal services in arranging the move. See Dunn, v. I, pp. 367\u201371.</ref> After relocating to Indianapolis, Merrill and his family lived in a two-story brick building, later demolished, that the state government had constructed at the southwest corner of Washington Street and present-day Capitol Avenue to house the state treasurer's office and residence, as well as the state auditor's office.<ref>Dunn, v. I, p. 370.</ref>\n\nMerrill continued to serve as state treasurer until 1834, when he was named president of the [[Bank of Indiana|State Bank of Indiana]]. He was also a partner in the trading firm of Yandes and Merrill and was active in other business ventures and civic affairs.<ref name=IHS-Bio/>\n\n===Bank president===\n[[File:Onedollarbanknotefrombankofindiana(1834).JPG|thumb|left|A one dollar bank note from the [[Bank of Indiana]] featuring a portrait engraving of Merrill (left)]]\n\nWhen the State Bank of Indiana was founded in 1834, the Indiana General Assembly choose Samuel Merrill as the bank's first president. Following his appointment, Merrill resigned his position of state treasurer. The ''[[Indianapolis News]]'' reported on July 15, 1911: \"His honesty and splendid record made him a man to inspire confidence in the bank.\" Merrill visited all thirteen of the bank's branches twice each year, traveling on horseback to personally examine their accounts and ledgers. It was said that he was able to review columns of figures with machine-like rapidity and accuracy.<ref name=IMH56-57>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" pp. 56\u201357.</ref>\n\n===Railroad company president===\nMerrill served as president of the Madison and Indianapolis Railroad Company from 1844 to 1848.<ref name =IMH56-57/> The state legislature initially established it as a state-owned railroad on January 27, 1836, as one of the first rail lines in the state. The railroad was salvaged following the collapse of the state's [[Indiana Mammoth Internal Improvement Act|internal improvement programs]] and transferred to private ownership on June 20, 1842.<ref name=Netzlof>{{cite web | author=Robert T. Netzlof | title=Corporate Genealogy: Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway, The Panhandle  | work = | publisher =  | date =August 23, 1999 | url=http://rnetzlof.pennsyrr.com/corphist/pcc_stl.html  | accessdate=November 30, 2017}} (Rev. April 29, 2002.) From data originally published in: {{cite book | author=  | title = Valuation Reports | publisher =Interstate Commerce Commission | series = | volume =24 | edition = | year =1929 | location =Washington, D. C.  | pages = | url =  | isbn =}}</ref>\n\nWith additional funding from investors in the [[eastern United States|East]], Merrill expanded the railroad to complete the line, which extended from [[Madison, Indiana]], to Indianapolis. More track was laid during his first two years as president than had been done in the previous ten years of its state-owned management. Merrill resigned from the railroad in 1848 after disagreements with H. R. Hall, the rail line's superintendent.<ref name=IHS-Bio/><ref name =IMH56-57/>\n\n===Publisher===\nIn 1840 Merrill authored and published ''Chamberlain's Gazetteer of Indiana''.<ref>Dunn, v. I, p. 364.</ref> The following year he bought Hood and Noble's bookstore, one of four bookstores located in Indianapolis at that time, and oversaw its merger with his publishing business.<ref name =IMH56-57/>\n\nAfter Merrill's death in 1855, ownership of the Merrill Publishing Company passed to his son, Samuel Merrill Jr. After a merger with Bowen Stewart and Company in 1885, it became known as the Bowen-Merrill Company; in 1903 the firm was renamed the [[Bobbs-Merrill Company]].<ref name=GS56>{{cite book | author= Linda C. Gugin and James E. St. Clair, eds. | title =Indiana's 200: The People Who Shaped the Hoosier State | publisher =Indiana Historical Society Press| year =2015 | location =Indianapolis | page =56  | url = | isbn =978-0-87195-387-2}}</ref>\n\n==Other interests==\nIn addition to his banking and business ventures, Merrill, a temperance and abolitionist, was interested in education and religious work.<ref name=IHS-Bio/>\n\nMerrill was an early president of the Temperance Society of Indianapolis and a leader of the State Colonization Society.<ref name=IMH59>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" p. 59.</ref> He was also an outspoken [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]]. On one occasion, a pro-slavery man entered the Indianapolis branch of the State Bank of Indiana and challenged Merrill to a fist-fight, which Merrill won.<ref>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" p. 58.</ref>\n\nBecause of his interest in education, Merrill helped to establish [[Wabash College]] in 1833 and served as a trustee. Merrill also taught school in York, Pennsylvania, and on occasion in Vevay, Indiana, and served as the superintendent of Sunday Schools for Indianapolis's [[Second Presbyterian Church (Indianapolis, Indiana)|Second Presbyterian]] and Fourth Presbyterian churches. Merrill was also an elder in the Second and Fourth Presbyterian churches, the latter of which he helped establish in 1851. In addition, Merrill served as the second president of the [[Indiana Historical Society]] (1835\u201348).<ref name=IHS-Bio/><ref name=IMH59/>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nMerrill died on August 24, 1855, in Indianapolis at the age of sixty-two.<ref name =IMH57>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\", p. 57.</ref>\n\nMerrill was known among his contemporaries as an able businessman and for his sound judgment and attention to detail. Although Merrill was not a skilled orator, he was an avid storyteller and a valued counselor to his peers. Merrill was a modest individual, but he could also be impulsive in his actions and outspoken in expressing his opinions.<ref>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" pp. 57\u201359; Dunn, v. I, pp. 380\u201381.</ref>\n\nAs a public servant, Merrill oversaw the successful transfer in 1824 of the state treasury, state library, and state archives, which remain at [[Indianapolis]], the permanent seat of [[Indiana]]'s state government. He was also successful in banking, the railroad industry, and publishing. Merrill became the first president of the State [[Bank of Indiana]], which continued to operate until 1859, and a president of the [[Jeffersonville, Madison and Indianapolis Railroad|Madison and Indianapolis Railroad Company]], provider of an early rail transportation link to Indianapolis. He also founded the Merrill Publishing Company, which later became known as the [[Bobbs-Merrill Company]]. The publishing company's backlist of titles and publishing rights were sold to [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan Company]] in 1985.<ref name=Netzlof/><ref name=GS56/><ref>Dunn, v. I, pp. 367\u201371, 418; Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" pp. 56\u201359.</ref>\n\nMerrill was also an early civic leader, serving as the second president of the [[Indiana Historical Society]], whose headquarters remain in Indianapolis. He was also a founder and trustee of [[Wabash College]], which continues to operate in [[Crawfordsville, Indiana]]; and served as an elder in two of Indianapolis's  Presbyterian congregations. The [[Second Presbyterian Church (Indianapolis, Indiana)|Second Presbyterian Church]] is located on North Meridian Street;<ref>Merrill, \"Samuel Merrill,\" pp. 56\u201359; \"Biographical Sketch\" in {{cite web| author= | title =Samuel Merrill Papers, 1818\u20131934 | work = | publisher =Indiana Historical Society | date =January 2, 2002 | url = http://www.indianahistory.org/our-collections/collection-guides/samuel-merrill-papers-1812-1934.pdf | format =pdf | accessdate =November 29, 2017}} See also: {{cite book | author =George W. Geib | title =Lives Touched by Faith: Second Presbyterian Church, 150 Years | publisher =Mallory Lithography, Inc. | year =1987 | location =Indianapolis, Indiana | pages = | url = | isbn =0961935103}}</ref> the Fourth Presbyterian Church later merged with other congregations.<ref>Sulgrove, p. 396. See also: {{cite book | author =David J. Bodenhamer and Robert G. Barrows, eds.|title =The Encyclopedia of Indianapolis  | publisher =Indiana University Press | series = | volume = | edition = | year =1994 | location =Bloomington and Indianapolis | pages =1132\u201333| url =  | isbn =0-253-31222-1}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and tributes==\nThe [[Bank of Indiana|State Bank of Indiana]] featured an engraved image of Merrill on the front of its one dollar bank note in the late 1850s.<ref>Dunn, v. I, p. 412.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Indiana}}\n*[[History of Indiana]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* \"Biographical Sketch\" in {{cite web| author= | title =Samuel Merrill Papers, 1818\u20131934 | work = | publisher =Indiana Historical Society | date =January 2, 2002 | url = http://www.indianahistory.org/our-collections/collection-guides/samuel-merrill-papers-1812-1934.pdf | format =pdf | accessdate =November 29, 2017}}\n* {{cite book | author =Bodenhamer, David J., and Robert G. Barrows, eds.|title =The Encyclopedia of Indianapolis  | publisher =Indiana University Press | series = | volume = | edition = | year =1994 | location =Bloomington and Indianapolis | page =| url =  | isbn =0-253-31222-1}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s8wtRblsXksC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Indiana+and+Indianans.+American+Historical+Society.&source=gbs_summary_r&cad=0|title=Indiana and Indianans: A History of the Aboriginal and Territorial Indiana and the Century of Statehood |author=[[Jacob Piatt Dunn|Dunn, Jacob Piatt]]|publisher=American Historical Society|location=Chicago and New York |year=1919| volume =I | edition =| pages =| OCLC=2470354}}\n*{{cite book|title=A Sketchbook of Indiana History| author=Funk, Arville L|origyear=1969|year=1983|publisher=Christian Book Press|location=[[Rochester, Indiana]]|OCLC=49694}}\n* {{cite book | author =Geib, George W.  | title =Lives Touched by Faith: Second Presbyterian Church, 150 Years | publisher =Mallory Lithography, Inc. | year =1987 | location =Indianapolis, Indiana | pages = | url = | isbn =0961935103}}\n* {{cite book | author=Gugin, Linda C., and James E. St. Clair, eds. | title =Indiana's 200: The People Who Shaped the Hoosier State | publisher =Indiana Historical Society Press| year =2015 | location =Indianapolis | page=  | url = | isbn =978-0-87195-387-2}}\n* {{cite book | author=| title =In Memoriam: Jane Merrill Ketcham, February 2, 1819 \u2013September 21, 1911 | publisher =| year =1911 | location = | pages = | url = | OCLC=23162975}} (Collections of the Indiana Historical Society.)\n*{{cite journal|author=Merrill, Catharine |title=Samuel Merrill, Indiana\u2019s Second State Treasurer (1792-1855) |journal=Indiana Magazine of History | volume =12 | issue =1| location =Bloomington | date=March 1916 | pages =53\u201359|url=https://scholarworks.iu.edu/journals/index.php/imh/article/view/5961/5642| accessdate =December 4, 2017}}\n* {{cite book | authors=Merrill, Catharine, and Katharine Merrill Graydon| title =Catharine Merrill, Life and Letters: Collected and Arranged | publisher =The Mitchell Company | series = | volume = | edition = | year =1934 | location =Greenfield, IN | page= | url =  | OCLC=7102104}}\n* {{cite web | author=Netzlof, Robert T.| title=Corporate Genealogy: Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Chicago and St. Louis Railway, The Panhandle | work = | publisher =  | date =August 23, 1999 | url=http://rnetzlof.pennsyrr.com/corphist/pcc_stl.html  | accessdate=November 30, 2017}} (Rev. April 29, 2002.) \n* {{cite journal| author=Stoler, Mildred C. | title =The Removal of the State Capital to Indianapolis | journal =Indiana Magazine of History | volume =27 | issue =3 | pages =240\u201343 | publisher =Indiana University | location =Bloomington | date =September 1931| url = https://scholarworks.iu.edu/journals/index.php/imh/article/view/6614/6949\n| accessdate =November 28, 2017}}\n* {{cite book|author=Sulgrove, Berry R. |title=History of Indianapolis and Marion County Indiana |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofindiana00sulgrich | publisher = L. H. Everts and Company |location= Philadelphia | year = 1884| page=[https://archive.org/details/historyofindiana00sulgrich/page/58 58]  | isbn= }}\n* {{cite book | author=Woollen, William Wesley | title =Biographical and Historical Sketches of Early Indiana | publisher =Arno Press | series =Mid-American Frontier | volume = | edition =reprint | year =1975 | location =New York | pages = | OCLC=1218324}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archives.isl.lib.in.us/repositories/2/resources/206 Samuel Merrill collection, Rare Books and Manuscripts, Indiana State Library]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Daniel Crosby Lane]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Indiana State Treasurer|Treasurer of Indiana]]|years=1822\u20131834}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nathan B. Palmer]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Merrill, Samuel}}\n[[Category:1792 births]]\n[[Category:1855 deaths]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Wabash College]]\n[[Category:State treasurers of Indiana]]\n[[Category:People from Caledonia County, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Members of the Indiana House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Indiana Historical Society]]\n[[Category:People from Vevay, Indiana]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Billmckern", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Merrill_(Indiana)"}
{"title_page": "After the Gold Rush", "text_new": "{{short description|1970 studio album by Neil Young}}\n{{about|the album|the song|After the Gold Rush (song)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = After the Gold Rush\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Neil Young]]\n| cover      = After the Gold Rush.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 19, 1970<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilyoung.com/archives/discography/items/ny-atg.html |title=  NY-ATG|accessdate=2013-07-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130629144508/http://www.neilyoung.com/archives/discography/items/ny-atg.html |archivedate=June 29, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| recorded   = Winter 1969&nbsp;\u2013 June 1970\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Sunset Sound]], Hollywood, CA <br />[[Sound City Studios|Sound City]], Van Nuys, Los Angeles<br />Redwood Studios, Topanga, CA\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Folk rock]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Richie Unterberger|title=Jingle Jangle Morning: Folk-Rock in the 1960s|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DihcDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT1089|date=February 20, 2014|publisher=BookBaby|isbn=978-0-9915892-1-0|page=1089}}</ref>|[[country rock]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Christgau|title=Grown Up All Wrong: 75 Great Rock and Pop Artists from Vaudeville to Techno|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EdN8VLiEZtcC&pg=PA470|date=November 15, 1998|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-44318-1|page=470}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 34:52\n| label      = [[Reprise Records|Reprise]]\n| producer   = Neil Young, [[David Briggs (record producer)|David Briggs]] with Kendall Pacios\n| prev_title = [[Everybody Knows This Is Nowhere]]\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = [[Harvest (Neil Young album)|Harvest]]\n| next_year  = 1972\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = After the Gold Rush\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Only Love Can Break Your Heart]]\n | single1date = October 19, 1970<ref name=\"B1\">{{cite book |title=Billboard |date=1970 |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_gSkEAAAAMBAJ/page/n71 72] |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_gSkEAAAAMBAJ |language=en |chapter=Billboard Hot 100}}</ref>\n | single2     = [[When You Dance I Can Really Love]]\n | single2date = March 1971<ref name=\"B2\">{{cite book |title=Billboard |date=1971 |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |page=58 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5AgEAAAAMBAJ |language=en |chapter=Spotlight Singles}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n'''''After the Gold Rush''''' is the third studio album by Canadian / American musician [[Neil Young]], released in September 1970 on [[Reprise Records]]. It is one of four high-profile albums released by each member of [[folk rock]] collective [[Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young]] in the wake of their chart-topping 1970 album ''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu (Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young album)|D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]''. ''Gold Rush'' consists mainly of [[country folk]] music, along with the rocking \"[[Southern Man (song)|Southern Man]]\",<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{Allmusic |class=album |id=r22502 |label=''After the Gold Rush'' |first=Ruhlmann |last=William |accessdate=November 30, 2011 }}</ref>  inspired by the [[Dean Stockwell]]-[[Herb Bermann]] screenplay ''After the Gold Rush''.\n\n''After the Gold Rush'' peaked at number eight on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Top Pop Albums chart; the two singles taken from the album, \"[[Only Love Can Break Your Heart]]\" and \"[[When You Dance I Can Really Love]]\", made it to number 33 and number 93 respectively on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. Despite a mixed initial reaction, it has since appeared on a number of \"greatest albums\" lists.\n\n==Production==\nInitial sessions were conducted with backing band [[Crazy Horse (band)|Crazy Horse]] at [[Sunset Sound Studios]] in Los Angeles amid a short winter 1970 tour that included a well-received engagement with [[Steve Miller (musician)|Steve Miller]] and [[Miles Davis]] at the [[Fillmore East]]. Despite the deteriorating health of rhythm guitarist [[Danny Whitten]], the sessions yielded two released tracks, \"[[I Believe in You (Neil Young song)|I Believe In You]]\" and \"Oh, Lonesome Me.\"\n\nMost of the album was recorded at a makeshift basement studio in Young's [[Topanga Canyon]] home during the spring with [[Crosby, Stills, Nash, & Young]] bassist [[Greg Reeves]], Crazy Horse drummer [[Ralph Molina]] and burgeoning eighteen-year-old musical prodigy [[Nils Lofgren]] of the [[Washington, D.C.]]-based band [[Grin (band)|Grin]] on piano. The incorporation of Lofgren was a characteristically idiosyncratic decision by Young: Lofgren had not played keyboards on a regular basis prior to the sessions.<ref>{{cite news |first = J. Freedom | last = du Lac | date = October 8, 2008 | title= Six Questions (And Then Some) For ... Nils Lofgren |work=The Washington Post | url =\nhttp://voices.washingtonpost.com/postrock/2008/10/six_questions_and_then_some_fo_2.html | accessdate =March 24, 2009}}</ref> Along with [[Jack Nitzsche]], Lofgren would join an augmented Crazy Horse sans Young before enjoying success with his own group, solo cult success and a 25-year membership in [[Bruce Springsteen]]'s [[E Street Band]]). The Young biography ''Shakey''<ref>[[McDonough, Jimmy]]. ''Shakey: Neil Young's Biography''. New York: Random House Inc., 2002</ref> claims Young was intentionally trying to combine Crazy Horse and CSNY on this release, with members of the former band appearing alongside [[Stephen Stills]] (who contributed backing vocals to \"Only Love Can Break Your Heart\") and Reeves. The cover art is a [[solarization|solarized]] image of Young, walking past the [[New York University School of Law]] campus, passing an old woman. The picture was taken by photographer [[Joel Bernstein]] and was reportedly out of focus. It was because of this he decided to mask the blurred face by solarizing the image.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popspotsnyc.com/afterthegoldrush/|title=After the Gold Rush - Album Cover Location|website=Popspotsnyc.com}}</ref>  The photo is cropped; the original image included Young's friend and CSNY bandmate [[Graham Nash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://alancook.files.wordpress.com/2014/02/after-the-gold-rush-outtake.jpg|format=JPG|title=Photographic image|website=Alancook.files.wordpress.com|accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nSongs on the album were inspired by the [[Dean Stockwell]]-[[Herb Bermann]] screenplay for the unmade film ''After the Gold Rush''. Young had read the screenplay and asked Stockwell if he could produce the soundtrack. Tracks that Young recalls as being written specifically for the film are \"After the Gold Rush\" and \"Cripple Creek Ferry.\"<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=N__84GtwaUUC&q=Cripple+Creek+Ferry+Gold+Rush&dq=Cripple+Creek+Ferry+Gold+Rush&hl=en&ei=CwTWTobXDIOY8gOv0LygAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CFEQ6AEwBQ |title=Shakey: Neil Young's Biography |first=Jimmy  |last=McDonough |page=332|publisher=Anchor Books |year= 2003 |accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> The script has since been lost, though has been described as \"sort of an end-of-the-world movie.\"<ref name=Shakey>{{cite book |url= https://www.google.com/search?tbm=bks&tbo=1&q=A+sort+of+an+end-of-the-world+movie&btnG=#sclient=psy-ab&hl=en&safe=off&tbo=1&tbm=bks&source=hp&q=A+sort+of+an+end-of-the-world+movie+Gold+Rush |title=Shakey: Neil Young's Biography |first=Jimmy |last= McDonough |page=331|publisher=Anchor Books |year= 2003 |accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> Stockwell said of it, \"I was gonna write a movie that was personal, a [[Jungian]] self-discovery of the [[gnosis]]... it involved the [[Kabbalah|Kabala]] ''(sic)'', it involved a lot of arcane stuff.\"<ref name=Shakey /> Graham Nash claims that \"Only Love Can Break Your Heart\" was written for him about the pains he was going through with his break up from [[Joni Mitchell]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/what-pushed-graham-nash-the-quiet-one-to-record-his-solo-masterpiece/2019/09/17/57f52720-ce4d-11e9-b29b-a528dc82154a_story.html|title=Graham Nash - Washington Post|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Neil Young Archives]]'', ''After the Gold Rush'' was released on September 19, 1970. One month later, on October 24, the lead single \"Only Love Can Break Your Heart\" entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart.<ref name=\"B1\" />\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|title = Retrospective professional reviews\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\" />\n| rev2 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n| rev2Score = A+<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: Y|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=Y&bk=70|accessdate=March 23, 2019|via=robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin|title=Encyclopedia of Popular Music|year=2007|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|edition=5th|isbn=978-0857125958|title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music}}</ref>\n|rev4 = [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']]\n|rev4score = 10/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Richardson |first=Mark |title=Review: ''After the Gold Rush'' |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/13771-neil-young-everybody-knows-this-is-nowhere-after-the-gold-rush-harvest/ |date=December 11, 2009 |accessdate=April 12, 2012 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] }}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev5score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lRgtYCC6OUwC&lpg=PP1&dq=rolling+stone+record+guide&pg=PA899#v=onepage&q=neil+young&f=false|title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide|first1=Nathan|last1=Brackett|first2=Christian David|last2=Hoard|date=September 13, 2017|publisher=Simon and Schuster|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n}}\nCritics were not immediately impressed; the 1970 review in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine by [[Langdon Winner]] was negative, with Winner feeling that, \"none of the songs here rise above the uniformly dull surface.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/after-the-gold-rush-19701015 |title=After The Gold Rush; Album Reviews; Rolling Stone|journal=Rolling Stone |first=Langdon  |last=Winner |date=October 15, 1970|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Village Voice]]'' critic [[Robert Christgau]] was more enthusiastic, saying: \"While [[David Crosby]] yowls about assassinations, Young divulges darker agonies without even bothering to make them explicit. Here the gaunt pain of ''[[Everybody Knows This Is Nowhere]]'' fills out a little\u2014the voice softer, the jangling guitar muted behind a piano. Young's melodies\u2014every one of them\u2014are impossible to dismiss. He can write 'poetic' lyrics without falling flat on his metaphor even when the subject is ecology or crumbling empire. And despite his acoustic tenor, he rocks plenty. A real rarity: pleasant and hard at the same time.\"<ref name=\"CG\"/>\n\nCritical reaction has improved with time; by 1975, ''Rolling Stone'' was referring to the album as a \"masterpiece\",<ref>{{cite news | first = Dave | last = Marsh | date = August 28, 1975 |  url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/tonights-the-night-19750828 | title = Neil Young: Tonight's the Night | publisher = Rolling Stone | accessdate =July 10, 2011}}</ref> and ''Gold Rush'' is now considered a classic album in Young's recording career.<ref>{{cite news | first = Alex | last = Mar | date = April 4, 2005 | accessdate=October 19, 2008 | url = https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/7234701/young_suffers_aneurysm | publisher = Rolling Stone | title = Young suffers aneurysm}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''After the Gold Rush'' has appeared on a number of greatest albums lists. In 1998 [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' magazine]] readers voted ''After the Gold Rush'' the 89th greatest album of all time. It was ranked 92nd in a 2005 survey held by British television's [[Channel 4]] to determine the 100 greatest albums of all time. In 2003, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' named the album the 71st [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|greatest album of all time]], and 74th in a 2012 revised list, his highest ranking on this list.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/neil-young-after-the-gold-rush-160641/|year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time Rolling Stone\u2019s definitive list of the 500 greatest albums of all time| publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]| accessdate= September 23, 2019}}</ref> [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] listed it 99th on their 2004 list of the \"Top 100 Albums of the 1970s\".<ref>{{cite web |author=Pitchfork Staff |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/5932-top-100-albums-of-the-1970s/ |title=The 100 Best Albums of the 1970s |date=June 23, 2004 |accessdate=February 9, 2019 |publisher=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] }}</ref> In 2006, ''[[Time Magazine]]'' listed it as one of the 'All-TIME 100 Albums'.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/2006/100albums/0,27693,After_the_Gold_Rush,00.html | work=Time | title=The All-TIME 100 Albums: After the Gold Rush by Neil Young \u2013 TIME Magazine \u2013 ALL-TIME 100 Albums | accessdate=April 23, 2010 | date=November 2, 2006}}</ref> It was ranked third in [[Bob Mersereau]]'s 2007 book ''[[The Top 100 Canadian Albums]]''. Its follow-up album, ''[[Harvest (Neil Young album)|Harvest]]'', was named the greatest Canadian album of all time in that book. In 2005, ''Chart Magazine'' readers placed it fifth on a poll of the best Canadian Albums. In 2002, ''[[Blender Magazine]]'' named it the 86th greatest \"American\" album. ''[[New Musical Express]]'' named it the 80th greatest album of all time in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/|title=Acclaimed Music|website=Acclaimedmusic.net}}</ref>  The album was also included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Dimery|author2=Michael Lydon|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition|accessdate= |date=7 February 2006|publisher=Universe|isbn=0-7893-1371-5}}</ref>\n\nIt was voted number 62 in [[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]'s [[All Time Top 1000 Albums]] 3rd Edition (2000).<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=2000|edition=3rd|isbn=0-7535-0493-6|page=62}}</ref> \n\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Country\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! Rank\n|-\n| ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| 100 Best Albums Ever<ref name=\"Guardian 100\">{{cite web |title=The Guardian 100 Best Albums Ever List, 1997 |url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/guardian100.htm |publisher=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=March 13, 2012}}</ref>\n| 1997\n| 47\n|-\n|}\n\n==Releases==\n''After the Gold Rush'' was remastered and released on [[HDCD]]-encoded CD and digital download on July 14, 2009 as part of the [[Neil Young Archives#Original Release Series|Neil Young Archives Original Release Series]]. The remaster has been released on vinyl and a high-resolution digital version on [[Blu-ray disc]] is also planned although a release date for this format has not yet been announced.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = Neil Young, except where noted\n| headline = Side one\n| title1 = [[Tell Me Why (Neil Young song)|Tell Me Why]]\n| note1 = \n| length1 = 2:54\n| title2 = [[After the Gold Rush (song)|After the Gold Rush]]\n| note2 = \n| length2 = 3:45\n| title3 = [[Only Love Can Break Your Heart]]\n| note3 = \n| length3 = 3:05\n| title4 = [[Southern Man (song)|Southern Man]]\n| note4 =\n| length4 = 5:31\n| title5 = Till the Morning Comes\n| note5 =\n| length5 = 1:17\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| title1 = [[Oh Lonesome Me|Oh, Lonesome Me]]\n| writer1 = [[Don Gibson]]\n| length1 = 3:47\n| title2 = [[Don't Let It Bring You Down]]\n| note2 = \n| length2 = 2:56\n| title3 = Birds\n| note3 =\n| length3 = 2:34\n| title4 = [[When You Dance I Can Really Love]]\n| note4 =\n| length4 = 4:05\n| title5 = [[I Believe in You (Neil Young song)|I Believe in You]]\n| note5 = \n| length5 = 3:24\n| title6 = Cripple Creek Ferry\n| note6 = \n| length6 = 1:34\n| total_length = 34:52\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[Neil Young]] \u2013 guitar, piano, harmonica, [[vibraphone|vibes]], lead vocals\n* [[Danny Whitten]] \u2013 guitar, vocals\n* [[Nils Lofgren]] \u2013 guitar, piano, vocals\n* [[Jack Nitzsche]] \u2013 piano\n* [[Billy Talbot]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Greg Reeves]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Ralph Molina]] \u2013 drums, vocals\n* [[Stephen Stills]] \u2013 vocals\n* Bill Peterson \u2013 [[flugelhorn]]\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n!align=\"left\"|Year\n!align=\"left\"|Chart\n!align=\"left\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1970\n|align=\"left\"|[[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] Pop Albums\n|align=\"left\"|8\n|-\n|}\n\n===Single===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n!align=\"left\"|Year\n!align=\"left\"|Single\n!align=\"left\"|Chart\n!align=\"left\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1970\n|align=\"left\"|\"Only Love Can Break Your Heart\"\n|align=\"left\"|''Billboard'' Pop Singles\n|align=\"left\"|33\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1971\n|align=\"left\"|\"When You Dance I Can Really Love\"\n|align=\"left\"|''Billboard'' Pop Singles\n|align=\"left\"|93\n|-\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United Kingdom|artist=Neil Young|title=After the Gold Rush|award=Platinum|number=2|certyear=2004|relyear=1970|accessdate=17 November 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United States|artist=Neil Young|title=After the Gold Rush|award=Platinum|number=2|certyear=1986|relyear=1970|accessdate=17 November 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- *[http://www.radio3net.ro/dbartists/supersearch/QWZ0ZXIgdGhlIEdvbGQgUnVzaA==/After%20the%20Gold%20Rush Album online] on [[Radio3Net]] a radio channel of [[Romanian Radio Broadcasting Company]] -->\n\n{{Neil Young}}\n{{Crazy Horse (band)}}\n\n[[Category:Neil Young albums]]\n[[Category:1970 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by David Briggs (producer)]]\n[[Category:Reprise Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Neil Young]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Sunset Sound Recorders]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded in a home studio]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Sound City Studios]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1970 studio album by Neil Young}}\n{{about|the album|the song|After the Gold Rush (song)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = After the Gold Rush\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Neil Young]]\n| cover      = After the Gold Rush.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 19, 1970<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilyoung.com/archives/discography/items/ny-atg.html |title=  NY-ATG|accessdate=2013-07-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130629144508/http://www.neilyoung.com/archives/discography/items/ny-atg.html |archivedate=June 29, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| recorded   = Winter 1969&nbsp;\u2013 June 1970\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Sunset Sound]], Hollywood, CA <br />[[Sound City Studios|Sound City]], Van Nuys, Los Angeles<br />Redwood Studios, Topanga, CA\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Folk rock]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Richie Unterberger|title=Jingle Jangle Morning: Folk-Rock in the 1960s|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DihcDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT1089|date=February 20, 2014|publisher=BookBaby|isbn=978-0-9915892-1-0|page=1089}}</ref>|[[country rock]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert Christgau|title=Grown Up All Wrong: 75 Great Rock and Pop Artists from Vaudeville to Techno|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EdN8VLiEZtcC&pg=PA470|date=November 15, 1998|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-44318-1|page=470}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 34:52\n| label      = [[Reprise Records|Reprise]]\n| producer   = Neil Young, [[David Briggs (record producer)|David Briggs]] with Kendall Pacios\n| prev_title = [[Everybody Knows This Is Nowhere]]\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = [[Harvest (Neil Young album)|Harvest]]\n| next_year  = 1972\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = After the Gold Rush\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Only Love Can Break Your Heart]]\n | single1date = October 19, 1970<ref name=\"B1\">{{cite book |title=Billboard |date=1970 |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_gSkEAAAAMBAJ/page/n71 72] |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_gSkEAAAAMBAJ |language=en |chapter=Billboard Hot 100}}</ref>\n | single2     = [[When You Dance I Can Really Love]]\n | single2date = March 1971<ref name=\"B2\">{{cite book |title=Billboard |date=1971 |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |page=58 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5AgEAAAAMBAJ |language=en |chapter=Spotlight Singles}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n'''''After the Gold Rush''''' is the third studio album by Canadian / American musician [[Neil Young]], released in September 1970 on [[Reprise Records]]. It is one of four high-profile albums released by each member of [[folk rock]] collective [[Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young]] in the wake of their chart-topping 1970 album ''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu (Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young album)|D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu]]''. ''Gold Rush'' consists mainly of [[country folk]] music, along with the rocking \"[[Southern Man (song)|Southern Man]]\",<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{Allmusic |class=album |id=r22502 |label=''After the Gold Rush'' |first=Ruhlmann |last=William |accessdate=November 30, 2011 }}</ref>  inspired by the [[Dean Stockwell]]-[[Herb Bermann]] screenplay ''After the Gold Rush''.\n\n''After the Gold Rush'' peaked at number eight on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Top Pop Albums chart; the two singles taken from the album, \"[[Only Love Can Break Your Heart]]\" and \"[[When You Dance I Can Really Love]]\", made it to number 33 and number 93 respectively on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. Despite a mixed initial reaction, it has since appeared on a number of \"greatest albums\" lists.\n\n==Production==\nInitial sessions were conducted with backing band [[Crazy Horse (band)|Crazy Horse]] at [[Sunset Sound Studios]] in Los Angeles amid a short winter 1970 tour that included a well-received engagement with [[Steve Miller (musician)|Steve Miller]] and [[Miles Davis]] at the [[Fillmore East]]. Despite the deteriorating health of rhythm guitarist [[Danny Whitten]], the sessions yielded two released tracks, \"[[I Believe in You (Neil Young song)|I Believe In You]]\" and \"Oh, Lonesome Me.\"\n\nMost of the album was recorded at a makeshift basement studio in Young's [[Topanga Canyon]] home during the spring with [[Crosby, Stills, Nash, & Young]] bassist [[Greg Reeves]], Crazy Horse drummer [[Ralph Molina]] and burgeoning eighteen-year-old musical prodigy [[Nils Lofgren]] of the [[Washington, D.C.]]-based band [[Grin (band)|Grin]] on piano. The incorporation of Lofgren was a characteristically idiosyncratic decision by Young: Lofgren had not played keyboards on a regular basis prior to the sessions.<ref>{{cite news |first = J. Freedom | last = du Lac | date = October 8, 2008 | title= Six Questions (And Then Some) For ... Nils Lofgren |work=The Washington Post | url =\nhttp://voices.washingtonpost.com/postrock/2008/10/six_questions_and_then_some_fo_2.html | accessdate =March 24, 2009}}</ref> (Along with [[Jack Nitzsche]], Lofgren would join an augmented Crazy Horse sans Young before enjoying success with his own group, solo cult success and a 25-year membership in [[Bruce Springsteen]]'s [[E Street Band]]). The Young biography ''Shakey''<ref>[[McDonough, Jimmy]]. ''Shakey: Neil Young's Biography''. New York: Random House Inc., 2002</ref> claims Young was intentionally trying to combine Crazy Horse and CSNY on this release, with members of the former band appearing alongside [[Stephen Stills]] (who contributed backing vocals to \"Only Love Can Break Your Heart\") and Reeves. The cover art is a [[solarization|solarized]] image of Young, walking past the [[New York University School of Law]] campus, passing an old woman. The picture was taken by photographer [[Joel Bernstein]] and was reportedly out of focus. It was because of this he decided to mask the blurred face by solarizing the image.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popspotsnyc.com/afterthegoldrush/|title=After the Gold Rush - Album Cover Location|website=Popspotsnyc.com}}</ref>  The photo is cropped; the original image included Young's friend and CSNY bandmate [[Graham Nash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://alancook.files.wordpress.com/2014/02/after-the-gold-rush-outtake.jpg|format=JPG|title=Photographic image|website=Alancook.files.wordpress.com|accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nSongs on the album were inspired by the [[Dean Stockwell]]-[[Herb Bermann]] screenplay for the unmade film ''After the Gold Rush''. Young had read the screenplay and asked Stockwell if he could produce the soundtrack. Tracks that Young recalls as being written specifically for the film are \"After the Gold Rush\" and \"Cripple Creek Ferry.\"<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=N__84GtwaUUC&q=Cripple+Creek+Ferry+Gold+Rush&dq=Cripple+Creek+Ferry+Gold+Rush&hl=en&ei=CwTWTobXDIOY8gOv0LygAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CFEQ6AEwBQ |title=Shakey: Neil Young's Biography |first=Jimmy  |last=McDonough |page=332|publisher=Anchor Books |year= 2003 |accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> The script has since been lost, though has been described as \"sort of an end-of-the-world movie.\"<ref name=Shakey>{{cite book |url= https://www.google.com/search?tbm=bks&tbo=1&q=A+sort+of+an+end-of-the-world+movie&btnG=#sclient=psy-ab&hl=en&safe=off&tbo=1&tbm=bks&source=hp&q=A+sort+of+an+end-of-the-world+movie+Gold+Rush |title=Shakey: Neil Young's Biography |first=Jimmy |last= McDonough |page=331|publisher=Anchor Books |year= 2003 |accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> Stockwell said of it, \"I was gonna write a movie that was personal, a [[Jungian]] self-discovery of the [[gnosis]]... it involved the [[Kabbalah|Kabala]] ''(sic)'', it involved a lot of arcane stuff.\"<ref name=Shakey /> Graham Nash claims that \"Only Love Can Break Your Heart\" was written for him about the pains he was going through with his break up from [[Joni Mitchell]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/what-pushed-graham-nash-the-quiet-one-to-record-his-solo-masterpiece/2019/09/17/57f52720-ce4d-11e9-b29b-a528dc82154a_story.html|title=Graham Nash - Washington Post|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Neil Young Archives]]'', ''After the Gold Rush'' was released on September 19, 1970. One month later, on October 24, the lead single \"Only Love Can Break Your Heart\" entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart.<ref name=\"B1\" />\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|title = Retrospective professional reviews\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\" />\n| rev2 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n| rev2Score = A+<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: Y|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=Y&bk=70|accessdate=March 23, 2019|via=robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin|title=Encyclopedia of Popular Music|year=2007|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|edition=5th|isbn=978-0857125958|title-link=Encyclopedia of Popular Music}}</ref>\n|rev4 = [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']]\n|rev4score = 10/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Richardson |first=Mark |title=Review: ''After the Gold Rush'' |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/13771-neil-young-everybody-knows-this-is-nowhere-after-the-gold-rush-harvest/ |date=December 11, 2009 |accessdate=April 12, 2012 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] }}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev5score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lRgtYCC6OUwC&lpg=PP1&dq=rolling+stone+record+guide&pg=PA899#v=onepage&q=neil+young&f=false|title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide|first1=Nathan|last1=Brackett|first2=Christian David|last2=Hoard|date=September 13, 2017|publisher=Simon and Schuster|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n}}\nCritics were not immediately impressed; the 1970 review in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine by [[Langdon Winner]] was negative, with Winner feeling that, \"none of the songs here rise above the uniformly dull surface.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/after-the-gold-rush-19701015 |title=After The Gold Rush; Album Reviews; Rolling Stone|journal=Rolling Stone |first=Langdon  |last=Winner |date=October 15, 1970|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Village Voice]]'' critic [[Robert Christgau]] was more enthusiastic, saying: \"While [[David Crosby]] yowls about assassinations, Young divulges darker agonies without even bothering to make them explicit. Here the gaunt pain of ''[[Everybody Knows This Is Nowhere]]'' fills out a little\u2014the voice softer, the jangling guitar muted behind a piano. Young's melodies\u2014every one of them\u2014are impossible to dismiss. He can write 'poetic' lyrics without falling flat on his metaphor even when the subject is ecology or crumbling empire. And despite his acoustic tenor, he rocks plenty. A real rarity: pleasant and hard at the same time.\"<ref name=\"CG\"/>\n\nCritical reaction has improved with time; by 1975, ''Rolling Stone'' was referring to the album as a \"masterpiece\",<ref>{{cite news | first = Dave | last = Marsh | date = August 28, 1975 |  url = https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/tonights-the-night-19750828 | title = Neil Young: Tonight's the Night | publisher = Rolling Stone | accessdate =July 10, 2011}}</ref> and ''Gold Rush'' is now considered a classic album in Young's recording career.<ref>{{cite news | first = Alex | last = Mar | date = April 4, 2005 | accessdate=October 19, 2008 | url = https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/7234701/young_suffers_aneurysm | publisher = Rolling Stone | title = Young suffers aneurysm}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n''After the Gold Rush'' has appeared on a number of greatest albums lists. In 1998 [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' magazine]] readers voted ''After the Gold Rush'' the 89th greatest album of all time. It was ranked 92nd in a 2005 survey held by British television's [[Channel 4]] to determine the 100 greatest albums of all time. In 2003, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' named the album the 71st [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|greatest album of all time]], and 74th in a 2012 revised list, his highest ranking on this list.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/neil-young-after-the-gold-rush-160641/|year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time Rolling Stone\u2019s definitive list of the 500 greatest albums of all time| publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]| accessdate= September 23, 2019}}</ref> [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] listed it 99th on their 2004 list of the \"Top 100 Albums of the 1970s\".<ref>{{cite web |author=Pitchfork Staff |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/5932-top-100-albums-of-the-1970s/ |title=The 100 Best Albums of the 1970s |date=June 23, 2004 |accessdate=February 9, 2019 |publisher=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] }}</ref> In 2006, ''[[Time Magazine]]'' listed it as one of the 'All-TIME 100 Albums'.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/2006/100albums/0,27693,After_the_Gold_Rush,00.html | work=Time | title=The All-TIME 100 Albums: After the Gold Rush by Neil Young \u2013 TIME Magazine \u2013 ALL-TIME 100 Albums | accessdate=April 23, 2010 | date=November 2, 2006}}</ref> It was ranked third in [[Bob Mersereau]]'s 2007 book ''[[The Top 100 Canadian Albums]]''. Its follow-up album, ''[[Harvest (Neil Young album)|Harvest]]'', was named the greatest Canadian album of all time in that book. In 2005, ''Chart Magazine'' readers placed it fifth on a poll of the best Canadian Albums. In 2002, ''[[Blender Magazine]]'' named it the 86th greatest \"American\" album. ''[[New Musical Express]]'' named it the 80th greatest album of all time in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/|title=Acclaimed Music|website=Acclaimedmusic.net}}</ref>  The album was also included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Dimery|author2=Michael Lydon|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition|accessdate= |date=7 February 2006|publisher=Universe|isbn=0-7893-1371-5}}</ref>\n\nIt was voted number 62 in [[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]'s [[All Time Top 1000 Albums]] 3rd Edition (2000).<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=2000|edition=3rd|isbn=0-7535-0493-6|page=62}}</ref> \n\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Country\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! Rank\n|-\n| ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| 100 Best Albums Ever<ref name=\"Guardian 100\">{{cite web |title=The Guardian 100 Best Albums Ever List, 1997 |url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/guardian100.htm |publisher=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=March 13, 2012}}</ref>\n| 1997\n| 47\n|-\n|}\n\n==Releases==\n''After the Gold Rush'' was remastered and released on [[HDCD]]-encoded CD and digital download on July 14, 2009 as part of the [[Neil Young Archives#Original Release Series|Neil Young Archives Original Release Series]]. The remaster has been released on vinyl and a high-resolution digital version on [[Blu-ray disc]] is also planned although a release date for this format has not yet been announced.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = Neil Young, except where noted\n| headline = Side one\n| title1 = [[Tell Me Why (Neil Young song)|Tell Me Why]]\n| note1 = \n| length1 = 2:54\n| title2 = [[After the Gold Rush (song)|After the Gold Rush]]\n| note2 = \n| length2 = 3:45\n| title3 = [[Only Love Can Break Your Heart]]\n| note3 = \n| length3 = 3:05\n| title4 = [[Southern Man (song)|Southern Man]]\n| note4 =\n| length4 = 5:31\n| title5 = Till the Morning Comes\n| note5 =\n| length5 = 1:17\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| title1 = [[Oh Lonesome Me|Oh, Lonesome Me]]\n| writer1 = [[Don Gibson]]\n| length1 = 3:47\n| title2 = [[Don't Let It Bring You Down]]\n| note2 = \n| length2 = 2:56\n| title3 = Birds\n| note3 =\n| length3 = 2:34\n| title4 = [[When You Dance I Can Really Love]]\n| note4 =\n| length4 = 4:05\n| title5 = [[I Believe in You (Neil Young song)|I Believe in You]]\n| note5 = \n| length5 = 3:24\n| title6 = Cripple Creek Ferry\n| note6 = \n| length6 = 1:34\n| total_length = 34:52\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[Neil Young]] \u2013 guitar, piano, harmonica, [[vibraphone|vibes]], lead vocals\n* [[Danny Whitten]] \u2013 guitar, vocals\n* [[Nils Lofgren]] \u2013 guitar, piano, vocals\n* [[Jack Nitzsche]] \u2013 piano\n* [[Billy Talbot]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Greg Reeves]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Ralph Molina]] \u2013 drums, vocals\n* [[Stephen Stills]] \u2013 vocals\n* Bill Peterson \u2013 [[flugelhorn]]\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n!align=\"left\"|Year\n!align=\"left\"|Chart\n!align=\"left\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1970\n|align=\"left\"|[[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] Pop Albums\n|align=\"left\"|8\n|-\n|}\n\n===Single===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n!align=\"left\"|Year\n!align=\"left\"|Single\n!align=\"left\"|Chart\n!align=\"left\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1970\n|align=\"left\"|\"Only Love Can Break Your Heart\"\n|align=\"left\"|''Billboard'' Pop Singles\n|align=\"left\"|33\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|1971\n|align=\"left\"|\"When You Dance I Can Really Love\"\n|align=\"left\"|''Billboard'' Pop Singles\n|align=\"left\"|93\n|-\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United Kingdom|artist=Neil Young|title=After the Gold Rush|award=Platinum|number=2|certyear=2004|relyear=1970|accessdate=17 November 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United States|artist=Neil Young|title=After the Gold Rush|award=Platinum|number=2|certyear=1986|relyear=1970|accessdate=17 November 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- *[http://www.radio3net.ro/dbartists/supersearch/QWZ0ZXIgdGhlIEdvbGQgUnVzaA==/After%20the%20Gold%20Rush Album online] on [[Radio3Net]] a radio channel of [[Romanian Radio Broadcasting Company]] -->\n\n{{Neil Young}}\n{{Crazy Horse (band)}}\n\n[[Category:Neil Young albums]]\n[[Category:1970 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by David Briggs (producer)]]\n[[Category:Reprise Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Neil Young]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Sunset Sound Recorders]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded in a home studio]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Sound City Studios]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n", "name_user": "LilJohnAY", "label": "safe", "comment": "Just removed an erroneous ( from the beginning of this sentence.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/After_the_Gold_Rush"}
{"title_page": "William F. Buckley Jr.", "text_new": "{{For|other people with a similar name|William F. Buckley (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American conservative author and commentator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name=William F. Buckley Jr.\n|image=William F. Buckley, Jr. 1985.jpg\n|caption=Buckley at the second inauguration of US President [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1985\n|birth_name=William Francis Buckley\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1925|11|24}}\n|birth_place=[[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|death_date={{death date and age|2008|2|27|1925|11|24}}\n|death_place=[[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]], [[Connecticut]], U.S.\n|occupation={{hlist | Editor | author | political commentator}}\n|alma_mater=[[Yale University]]\n|subject={{hlist | [[Conservatism in the United States|American conservatism]] | politics | [[anti-communism]] | [[espionage]]}}\n|spouse={{marriage|[[Patricia Buckley|Patricia Taylor Buckley]]|1950|2007|end=died}}\n|children=[[Christopher Buckley (novelist)|Christopher Buckley]]\n|relatives={{plainlist|\n*[[James L. Buckley]] (brother)\n*[[Patricia Buckley Bozell]] (sister)\n*[[Reid Buckley]] (brother)\n*[[L. Brent Bozell Jr.]] (brother-in-law)\n*[[L. Brent Bozell III]] (nephew)\n*[[William F.&nbsp;B. O'Reilly]] (nephew)}}\n<!-- Infobox writer no longer supports the fields influences and influenced. See TALK\n [[Talk:William F. Buckley Jr.#Influences/influenced]] -->\n| module = {{Infobox military person |embed=yes\n   |branch       = [[United States Army]]\n   |serviceyears = 1944\u20131946\n   |rank         = [[Second Lieutenant (United States)|Second Lieutenant]]\n   |unit         = \n   |commands     = \n   |battles      = [[World War II]]\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''William Frank Buckley Jr.''' (born '''William Francis Buckley''';<ref>\"William Francis\" in the editorial obituary \"Up From Liberalism\" ''The Wall Street Journal'' February 28, 2008, p. A16; Martin, Douglas, \"William F. Buckley Jr., 82, Dies; Sesquipedalian Spark of Right\", obituary, ''New York Times'', February 28, 2008, which reported that his parents preferred \"Frank\", which would make him a \"Jr.\", but at his christening, the priest \"insisted on a saint's name, so Francis was chosen. When the younger William Buckley was five, he asked to change his middle name to Frank, and his parents agreed. At that point, he became William F. Buckley, Jr.\"</ref> November 24, 1925&nbsp;\u2013 February 27, 2008) was an American [[public intellectual]] and [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] author<ref>Italie, Hillel via ''Associated Press''. [https://archive.today/20121216131901/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2008/02/27/national/a082531S11.DTL&type=politics SFgate.com], ''San Francisco Chronicle'', February 27, 2008. Accessed January 18, 2009.</ref> and commentator. In 1955 Buckley founded ''[[National Review]]'', a magazine that stimulated the conservative movement in the late-20th century United States. Buckley hosted 1,429 episodes of the public affairs television show ''[[Firing Line (TV series)|Firing Line]]'' (1966\u20131999), the longest-running public affairs show in US television history with a single host, where he became known for his distinctive [[Mid-Atlantic accent|Transatlantic]] [[idiolect]] and wide vocabulary.<ref name=WSJ>''The Wall Street Journal'' February 28, 2008, p. A16</ref>\n\nBuckley wrote ''[[God and Man at Yale]]'' (1951) and more than fifty other books on diverse topics, including writing, speaking, history, politics, and sailing. His works include a series of novels featuring fictitious [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agent [[Blackford Oakes]]. He also penned a nationally [[Print syndication|syndicated]] newspaper column.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cumulus.hillsdale.edu/buckley/Standard/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100525170517/http://cumulus.hillsdale.edu/buckley/Standard/index.html|url-status=dead|title=Cumulus.hillsdale.edu|archivedate=May 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTobit\"/>\n\nBuckley called himself either a [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]] or a [[conservativism in the United States|conservative]].<ref>C-SPAN Booknotes October 23, 1993</ref><ref>Buckley, William F. Jr. ''Happy Days Were Here Again: Reflections of a Libertarian Journalist'', Random House, {{ISBN|0-679-40398-1}}, 1993.</ref> [[George H. Nash]], a historian of the modern American conservative movement, said in 2008 that Buckley was \"arguably the most important public intellectual in the United States in the past half century. For an entire generation, he was the preeminent voice of American conservatism and its first great ecumenical figure.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://article.nationalreview.com/print/?q=YmZkMTRmN2MyZjcwYWVhYWI4YjhkNjE5YTA5NmY3ODg|first=George H.|last=Nash|date=February 28, 2008|title=Simply Superlative: Words for Buckley|accessdate=February 29, 2008|publisher=National Review Online|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080303043521/http://article.nationalreview.com/print/?q=YmZkMTRmN2MyZjcwYWVhYWI4YjhkNjE5YTA5NmY3ODg|archivedate=March 3, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Buckley's primary contribution to politics was a [[fusionism (politics)|fusion]] of [[traditionalist conservatism]] and [[classical liberalism]]; it laid the groundwork for the rightward shift in the [[Republican Party United States|Republican Party]] exemplified by [[Barry Goldwater]] and [[Ronald Reagan]].\n\n==Early life==\n{{Conservatism US}}\nBuckley was born November 24, 1925, in [[New York City]], the son of Aloise Josephine Antonia (Steiner) and [[William Frank Buckley Sr.|William Frank Buckley]], a [[Texas]]-born lawyer and oil developer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wargs.com/other/buckley.html|title=Ancestry of William F. Buckley|publisher=}}</ref> His mother, from New Orleans, was of [[Swiss (people)|Swiss-German]], German, and Irish descent, while his paternal grandparents, from [[Hamilton, Ontario]], Canada, were of [[Irish American|Irish]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UBfYAAAAMAAJ|title=The National Cyclopaedia of American Biography: Being the History of the United States as Illustrated in the Lives of the Founders, Builders, and Defenders of the Republic, and of the Men and Women who are Doing the Work and Moulding the Thought of the Present Time|date=January 1, 1967|publisher=University Microfilms|via=Google Books}}</ref> The sixth of ten children, Buckley moved as a boy with his family to Mexico,<ref name=\"Judis2001\">{{cite book|last=Judis|first=John B.|title=William F. Buckley, Jr.: Patron Saint of the Conservatives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aBEpI5h9gAUC&pg=PA29|accessdate=19 June 2016|date=29 January 2001|publisher=Simon and Schuster|location=New York City, NY|isbn=978-0-7432-1797-2|page=29|quote=After leaving Mexico, Will moved his family to New York, where he was raising funds to launch a new oil venture in Venezuela. But he didn't think children should be brought up in the city, and within a year he had bought a 47-acre estate in Sharon, a rustic town of two thousand in the northwestern corner of Connecticut.}}</ref> and then to [[Sharon, Connecticut]], before beginning his formal schooling in Paris, where he attended first grade. By age seven, he received his first formal training in English at a day school in London; his first and second languages were Spanish and French.<ref name=BuckleyJr_2004>{{cite book| first = William F. Jr. | last = Buckley|title=Miles Gone By: A Literary Autobiography|publisher=Regnery Publishing|year=2004}} Early chapters recount his early education and mastery of languages.</ref> As a boy, Buckley developed a love for music, sailing, horses, hunting, and skiing, all interests reflected in his later writings. He was homeschooled through the eighth grade using the Calvert School of Baltimore's Homeschool Curriculum.<ref name=\"Calvert\">{{cite web | url=http://blog.calverteducation.com/calvert/william-f-buckley-jr-calvert-homeschooler/ | title=William F. Buckley Jr. \u2013 Calvert Homeschooler | publisher=Calvert Education | work=Calvert Blog Network \u2013 Alumni | date=January 28, 2014 | accessdate=March 18, 2015}}</ref> Just before World War II, at age 12\u201313, he attended the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] preparatory school [[St John's Beaumont]] in England.\n\nHis father [[William Frank Buckley Sr.]] (1881-1958) was an American oil developer whose wealth was based in Mexico.  He became influential in Mexican politics during the military dictatorship of Victoriano Huerta but was expelled when leftist general [[\u00c1lvaro Obreg\u00f3n]] became president in 1920.  Buckley had nine siblings, including eldest sister Aloise Buckley Heath, a writer and conservative activist;<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{cite news|date=January 21, 1967|title=Aloise Buckley Heath|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2506&dat=19670121&id=VZhJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fAwNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4262,4249647|work=The News and Courier|accessdate=11 Mar 2013}}</ref> sister Maureen Buckley-O'Reilly (1933\u20131964), who married Gerald A. O'Reilly (the CEO of [[Richardson-Vicks]] Drugs); sister Priscilla L. Buckley (author of ''Living It Up With National Review: A Memoir'', for which William wrote the foreword); sister [[Patricia Buckley Bozell]], who was Patricia Taylor's roommate at Vassar before each married; brother [[Reid Buckley]], an author, debate-master, and founder of the Buckley School of Public Speaking; and brother [[James L. Buckley]], who became a U.S. Senator from New York and was later a judge of the [[United States Court of Appeals]] for the [[D.C. Circuit]].<ref>John B. Judis, ''William F. Buckley Jr.'' (2001) pp. 312\u201316, 103</ref>\n\nDuring the war, Buckley's family took in the future British historian [[Alistair Horne]] (son of Sir Allan Horne) as a child war [[Emergency evacuation|evacuee]]. He and Buckley remained lifelong friends. They both attended the [[Millbrook School]] in [[Millbrook, New York]], graduating in 1943. Buckley was a member of the American Boys' Club for the Defense of [[Errol Flynn]] (ABCDEF) during Flynn's trial for statutory rape in 1943. At Millbrook, Buckley founded and edited the school's yearbook, ''The Tamarack''; this was his first experience in publishing. When Buckley was a young man, his father was an acquaintance of libertarian author [[Albert Jay Nock]]. William F. Buckley Sr., encouraged his son to read Nock's works.\n\nAs a youth Buckley developed many musical talents. He played the [[harpsichord]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/embed/evvWbSAZtag|title=Firing Line with William F. Buckley Jr.: William F. Buckley Jr. and the Phoenix Symphony |website=youtube.com|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref> very well, later calling it \"the instrument I love beyond all others\".<ref name=\"Bach\"/> He was an accomplished pianist and appeared once on [[Marian McPartland]]'s [[National Public Radio]] show ''[[Piano Jazz]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/news.php?id=10676 |title=Tanglewood Jazz Festival, September 1\u20133, 2006 in Lenox, Massachusetts |publisher=Allaboutjazz.com |accessdate=2015-05-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120706181429/http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/news.php?id=10676 |archivedate=July 6, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> A great admirer of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]],<ref name=\"Bach\">[https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/07/16/specials/buckley-bach.html Once Again, Buckley Takes On Bach ]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Published October 25, 1992.</ref> Buckley wanted Bach's music played at his funeral.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Charlie Rose|url=http://www.charlierose.com/shows/2006/03/24/1/an-hour-with-editor-william-f-buckleyjr|series=Charlie Rose|network=PBS|airdate=2006-03-24|minutes=50:43|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216202858/http://www.charlierose.com/shows/2006/03/24/1/an-hour-with-editor-william-f-buckleyjr|archivedate=December 16, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Military service, higher education, and the CIA==\nBuckley attended the [[National Autonomous University of Mexico]] (or [[UNAM]]) in 1943. The following year, upon his graduation from the US Army [[Officer Candidate School (U.S. Army)|Officer Candidate School]] (OCS), he was commissioned as a [[Second lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]] in the [[United States Army]]. In his book ''Miles Gone By'', he briefly recounts being a member of [[Franklin Roosevelt]]'s honor guard upon Roosevelt's death. He served stateside throughout the war at [[Fort Benning]], Georgia; [[Fort Gordon]], Georgia; and [[Fort Sam Houston]], Texas.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Judis |first1=John B. |title=William F. Buckley, Jr.: Patron Saint of the Conservatives |date=2001 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |pages=49-50}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of World War II in 1945, Buckley enrolled at [[Yale University]], where he became a member of the secret [[Skull and Bones]] society<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Alexandra Robbins|last=Robbins|first=Alexandra|title=Secrets of the Tomb: Skull and Bones, the Ivy League, and the Hidden Paths of Power|publisher=[[Little, Brown]]|location=Boston|year=2002|isbn=0-316-72091-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/secretsoftombsku00robb/page/41 41]|url=https://archive.org/details/secretsoftombsku00robb/page/41}}</ref><ref name=biographydotcom>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/search/article.do?id=9230494&page=print|title=Buckley, William F(rank) Jr. (1925\u20132008) Biography|accessdate=February 27, 2008}}{{dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref> and was a masterful debater.<ref name=biographydotcom/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.library.yale.edu/madid/oneItem.aspx?id=1809005&q=osterweis&q1=&q2=&qc1=&qc2=&qf1=&qf2=&qn=&qo=&qm=15&qs=1&sid=0&qx=|title=The Manuscripts and Archives Digital Images Database (MADID)|publisher=}}</ref> He was an active member of the [[Yale Political Union#The Conservative Party|Conservative Party]] of the [[Yale Political Union]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digital.library.yale.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/yale-ydn/id/28726/rec/2|title=\"Richard Shapiro Wins PU Debate On Aid To China\", Yale Daily News no. 88 January 22 1948 :: Yale Daily News Historical Archive|last=|first=|date=|website=digital.library.yale.edu|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> and served as Chairman of the ''[[Yale Daily News]]'' and as an informer for the [[FBI]].<ref>{{Cite book |last = Diamond |first = Sigmund |year = 1992 |title = Compromised Campus: The Collaboration of Universities with the Intelligence Community, 1945\u20131955 |location = New York, NY |publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] |isbn = 978-0-195-05382-1 }} Chapter 7 is devoted to Buckley.</ref> Buckley studied political science, history, and economics at Yale, graduating with honors in 1950.<ref name=biographydotcom/> He excelled on the [[Yale Debate Association|Yale Debate Team]]; under the tutelage of Yale professor [[Rollin G. Osterweis]], Buckley honed his acerbic style.<ref>{{cite web |title=History |website=Osterweis Debate Tournament |url=http://www.yaledebate.org/osterweis/history.html |publisher=Yale Debate Association {{!}} Osterweis Tournament |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1951, along with many other Ivy League alumni, Buckley was recruited into the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA); he served for two years, including one year in Mexico City working on political action for [[E. Howard Hunt]],<ref name=LATimes>{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/mar/04/opinion/op-buckley4|newspaper = Los Angeles Times|title = My friend, E. Howard Hunt|first = William F. |last = Buckley Jr.|date = March 4, 2007|accessdate = May 6, 2015|issn = 0458-3035}}</ref> who was later jailed for his part in the Watergate affair. The two officers remained lifelong friends.<ref>Tad Szulc, ''Compulsive Spy: The Strange Career of E. Howard Hunt'' (New York: Viking, 1974)</ref> In a November 1, 2005, column for ''[[National Review]]'', Buckley recounted that while he worked for the CIA, the only CIA employee he knew was Hunt, his immediate boss. While in Mexico, Buckley edited ''The Road to Yenan'', a book by [[Peru]]vian author Eudocio Ravines.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Marriage and family==\nIn 1950, Buckley married [[Patricia Buckley|Patricia Aldyen Austin \"Pat\" Taylor]] (1926\u20132007), daughter of Canadian industrialist [[Austin Cotterell Taylor|Austin C. Taylor]]. He met Taylor, a Protestant from [[Vancouver]], British Columbia, while she was a student at [[Vassar College]]. She later became a prominent fundraiser for such charitable organizations as the [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]], the Institute of Reconstructive [[Plastic Surgery]] at [[New York University]] Medical Center and the Hospital for Special Surgery. She also raised money for Vietnam War veterans and AIDS patients. On April 15, 2007, Pat Buckley died at age 80 of an infection after a long illness.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/02/27/buckley.obit/index.html CNN] February 27, 2008 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605201516/http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/02/27/buckley.obit/index.html |date=June 5, 2008 }}</ref> After her death, Buckley seemed \"dejected and rudderless\", according to friend [[Christopher Little]].<ref name=rbhc>{{cite web|author=Buck, Rinker|url=http://www.courant.com/news/local/hc-buckleyobit0228.artfeb28,0,6920688,print.story|title=William F. Buckley Jr. 1925\u20132008: Icon Of The Right: Entertaining, Erudite Voice Of Conservatism|work=[[The Hartford Courant]]|date=February 28, 2007|access-date=March 1, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080303161159/http://www.courant.com/news/local/hc-buckleyobit0228.artfeb28,0,6920688,print.story|archive-date=March 3, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nWilliam and Patricia Buckley had one son, author [[Christopher Buckley (novelist)|Christopher Buckley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/01/buckleys200901|title=Bob Colacello on Pat and Bill Buckley|first=Cond\u00e9|last=Nast|website=Vanity Fair}}</ref> They lived at 778 Park Avenue in [[Manhattan]].<ref name=\"Park779\">{{cite news |last1=Toy |first1=Vivian S. |title=A Liberal Price Cut |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/21/realestate/21deal1.html |accessdate=5 March 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=March 18, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Religious views==\nBuckley was raised a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] and was a member of the [[Knights of Malta]].<ref>Phelan, Matthew (2011-02-28) [http://www.salon.com/news/politics/war_room/2011/02/28/seymour_hersh_whowhatwhy/index.html Seymour Hersh and the men who want him committed] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110302123501/http://www.salon.com/news/politics/war_room/2011/02/28/seymour_hersh_whowhatwhy/index.html |date=March 2, 2011 }}, ''[[Salon.com]]''</ref> He described his faith by saying, \"I grew up, as reported, in a large family of Catholics without even a decent ration of tentativeness among the lot of us about our religious faith.\"<ref>Buckley, ''Nearer, My God''. p. 241.{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref> When he attended Millbrook School, Buckley was permitted to attend Catholic Mass at a nearby church despite the school's Protestant affiliation. As a youth, he became aware of [[Anti-Catholicism in the United States|anti-Catholic bias]] in the United States through reading ''[[American Freedom and Catholic Power]],'' a [[Paul Blanshard]] book that accused American Catholics of having \"divided loyalties\".{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe release of his first book, ''God and Man at Yale'', in 1951 was met with some specific criticism pertaining to his Catholicism. [[McGeorge Bundy]], dean of Harvard at the time, wrote in ''[[The Atlantic]]'' that \"it seems strange for any Roman Catholic to undertake to speak for the Yale religious tradition\". [[Henry Sloane Coffin]], a Yale trustee, accused Buckley's book of \"being distorted by his Roman Catholic point of view\" and stated that Buckley \"should have attended [[Fordham University|Fordham]] or some similar institution\".<ref>Buckley, ''Nearer, My God''. p. 30.{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn his 1997 book ''Nearer, My God'', Buckley condemned what he viewed as \"the Supreme Court's war against religion in the public school\" and argued that Christian faith was being replaced by \"another God&nbsp;... multiculturalism\".<ref>Buckley, ''Nearer, My God''. p. 37.{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref> As an adult, Buckley regularly attended the [[Tridentine Mass]] in Connecticut.<ref name=\"Ponte\">{{cite news|last=Ponte|first=Lowell|title=Memories of William F. Buckley Jr.|url=http://www.newsmax.com/lowell_ponte/William_Buckley_/2008/02/28/76344.html|work=[[Newsmax]]|date=February 28, 2008|accessdate=February 28, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080302223640/http://www.newsmax.com/lowell_ponte/William_Buckley_/2008/02/28/76344.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archivedate=March 2, 2008}}</ref> He disapproved of the liturgical reforms following the [[Second Vatican Council]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.remnantnewspaper.com/Archives/archive-2008-buckley.htm|title=William F. Buckley on the New Mass|accessdate=July 11, 2008}}</ref> Buckley also revealed an interest in the writings and revelations of the 20th Century Italian writer [[Maria Valtorta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ministryvalues.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1355&Itemid=125|title=William F. Buckley's Fascination with Italian Mystic Maria Valtorta|accessdate=December 25, 2010}}</ref> In his spiritual memoir, Buckley reproduced Valtorta's detailed accounts of Jesus Christ's crucifixion; these accounts were based on Valtorta's visionary experiences of Christ and the mystical revelations she recorded in her book ''[[The Poem of the Man-God]]''.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==First books==\n\n===''God and Man at Yale''===\n[[File:Bozell&Buckley,1954.jpg|thumb|Buckley (right) and [[L. Brent Bozell Jr.]] promote their book ''McCarthy and His Enemies'', 1954]]\n\nBuckley's first book, ''[[God and Man at Yale]]'', was published in 1951. A critique of [[Yale University]], Buckley argued that the school had strayed from its original mission. Critics viewed the work as miscasting the role of [[academic freedom]].<ref>Countryman, Vern (1952). Review of \"William F. Buckley, ''God and Man at Yale''.\" [https://www.jstor.org/stable/793684 ''The Yale Law Journal''], 61.2: 272-83 (\"Once upon a time there was a little boy named William Buckley. Although he was a very little boy, he was much too big for his britches.\").</ref> Buckley himself credited the attention the book received in the media to the \"Introduction\" written by [[John Chamberlain (journalist)|John Chamberlain]], saying that it \"chang[ed] the course of his life\" and that the famous ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine editorial writer had acted out of \"reckless generosity.\"<ref>[[John Chamberlain (journalist)|Chamberlain, John]], ''A Life With the Printed Word'', Chicago: [[Regnery]], 1982, p. 147</ref> William F. Buckley Jr. was referred to in the novel ''[[The Manchurian Candidate]]'' by [[Richard Condon]] in 1959 as \"that fascinating younger fellow who had written about men and God at Yale.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=McCann |first1=David R. |last2=Strauss |first2=Barry S. |title=War and Democracy: A Comparative Study of the Korean War and the Peloponnesian War |date=2015 |publisher=Routledge}}</ref>\n\n===''McCarthy and His Enemies''===\nIn 1954, Buckley and his brother-in-law [[L. Brent Bozell Jr.]] co-authored a book, ''McCarthy and His Enemies''. Bozell worked with Buckley at ''The American Mercury'' in the early 1950s when it was edited by [[William Bradford Huie]].<ref>Judis, ''William F. Buckley Jr.'' (2001) p. 103</ref> The book strongly defended Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] as a patriotic crusader against communism. The book asserted that \"McCarthyism&nbsp;... is a movement around which men of good will and stern morality can close ranks.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Buckley|first=William F.|year=1954|title=McCarthy and His Enemies: The Record and Its Meaning|page=132|publisher=Regnery Publishing|isbn=0-89526-472-2}}</ref> Buckley edited ''[[The American Mercury]]'' in 1951 and 1952, but left after perceiving newly emerging [[Antisemitism|anti-Semitic]] tendencies in the magazine.<ref name=\"IHT-Obit\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.iht.com/bin/printfriendly.php?id=10482667|title=William F. Buckley Jr. is dead at 82|accessdate=February 27, 2008|last=Martin|first=Douglas|date=February 27, 2008|work=International Herald Tribune}}</ref>\n\n==''National Review''==\nBuckley founded ''[[National Review]]'' in 1955 at a time when there were few publications devoted to conservative commentary. He served as the magazine's editor-in-chief until 1990.<ref name=encyc>[http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1P2-1151505.html Encyclopedia.com] June 10, 1990 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090112173159/http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1P2-1151505.html |date=January 12, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=flashback>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/flashback/flashback200511170846.asp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109203640/http://www.nationalreview.com/flashback/flashback200511170846.asp|url-status=dead|title=National Review|archivedate=January 9, 2009}}</ref> During that time, ''National Review'' became the standard-bearer of [[Conservatism in the United States|American conservatism]], promoting the [[fusionism (politics)|fusion]] of traditional conservatives and [[libertarians]]. Examining postwar conservative intellectual history, Kim Phillips-Fein writes:\n\n{{quote|The most influential synthesis of the subject remains [[George H. Nash]]'s ''The Conservative Intellectual Tradition since 1945''&nbsp;... He argued that postwar conservatism brought together three powerful and partially contradictory intellectual currents that previously had largely been independent of each other: libertarianism, traditionalism, and anticommunism. Each particular strain of thought had predecessors earlier in the twentieth (and even nineteenth) centuries, but they were joined in their distinctive postwar formulation through the leadership of William F. Buckley Jr. and ''National Review.'' The fusion of these different, competing, and not easily reconciled schools of thought led to the creation, Nash argued, of a coherent modern Right.<ref>Kim Phillips-Fein, \"Conservatism: A State of the Field,\" ''Journal of American History,'' (Dec. 2011) 98#3 pp. 723\u201343, quote p. 729</ref><ref>George H. Nash, ''The Conservative Intellectual Tradition since 1945'' (1976)</ref>}}\n\nBuckley sought out intellectuals who were ex-Communists or had once worked on the far Left, including [[Whittaker Chambers]], [[Willi Schlamm|William Schlamm]], [[John Dos Passos]], [[Frank Meyer (political philosopher)|Frank Meyer]] and [[James Burnham]],<ref>John P. Diggins, \"Buckley's Comrades: The Ex-Communist as Conservative,\" ''Dissent'' July 1975, Vol. 22 Issue 4, pp. 370\u201386</ref> as editors and writers for ''National Review''. When Burnham became a senior editor, he urged the adoption of a more pragmatic editorial position that would extend the influence of the magazine toward the political center. Smant (1991) finds that Burnham overcame sometimes heated opposition from other members of the editorial board (including Meyer, Schlamm, William Rickenbacker, and the magazine's publisher, [[William A. Rusher]]), and had a significant impact on both the editorial policy of the magazine and on the thinking of Buckley himself.<ref>Kevin Smant, \"Whither Conservatism? James Burnham and 'National Review,' 1955\u20131964,\" ''Continuity,'' 1991, Issue 15, pp. 83\u201397; Smant, ''Principles and Heresies: Frank S. Meyer and the Shaping of the American Conservative Movement'' (2002) pp. 33\u201366</ref>\n\n===Defining the boundaries of conservatism===\n{{see also|Conservatism in the United States}}\nBuckley and his editors used ''National Review'' to define the boundaries of conservatism and to exclude people, ideas or groups they considered unworthy of the conservative title.<ref>Roger Chapman, ''Culture wars: an encyclopedia of issues, viewpoints, and voices'' (2009) vol. 1 p. 58</ref> For example, Buckley denounced Ayn Rand, the John Birch Society, George Wallace, racists, white supremacists, and anti-Semites.\n\nWhen he first met author Ayn Rand, according to Buckley, she greeted him with the following: \"You are much too intelligent to believe in God.\"<ref>\"Ayn Rand, R.I.P.\", ''The National Review'', April 2, 1982.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Baker|first1=Hunter|title=The Devil and Ayn Rand: Extending Christian Charity to Galt's Creator|url=http://thefederalist.com/2014/10/07/the-devil-and-ayn-rand-extending-christian-charity-to-john-galts-creator/|website=The Federalist|accessdate=July 31, 2016|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref> In turn, Buckley felt that \"Rand's style, as well as her message, clashed with the conservative ethos\".<ref>Jennifer Burns, ''Goddess of the market: Ayn Rand and the American Right, 1930\u20131980'' (2010) p. 162</ref> He decided that Rand's hostility to religion made her philosophy unacceptable to his understanding of conservatism. After 1957, he attempted to weed her out of the conservative movement by publishing [[Whittaker Chambers]]'s highly negative review of Rand's ''[[Atlas Shrugged]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chambers|first=Whittaker|authorlink=Whittaker Chambers|title=Big Sister is Watching You|url=http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=ZTFlYjgxMjgzYzkyYjI0NDI4YzM3YzAzYTcyMWQxNGU=|publisher=National Review (online reprint October 12, 2007)|date=December 28, 1957|access-date=October 13, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013171258/http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=ZTFlYjgxMjgzYzkyYjI0NDI4YzM3YzAzYTcyMWQxNGU=|archive-date=October 13, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://whittakerchambers.org/articles/nr/bigsister/|last=Chambers|first=Whittaker|authorlink=Whittaker Chambers|title=Big Sister is Watching You|publisher=WhittakerChambers.org|accessdate=March 18, 2012}}</ref> In 1964, he wrote of \"her desiccated philosophy's conclusive incompatibility with the conservative's emphasis on transcendence, intellectual and moral,\" as well as \"the incongruity of tone, that hard, schematic, implacable, unyielding, dogmatism that is in itself intrinsically objectionable, whether it comes from the mouth of [[Ilya Ehrenburg|Ehrenburg]], [[Girolamo Savonarola|Savonarola]]\u2014or Ayn Rand.\"<ref>William F. Buckley Jr., \"Notes toward an Empirical Definition of Conservatism,\" in Frank S. Meyer, ed., ''What is Conservatism?'' (1964) p. 214</ref> Other attacks on Rand were penned by [[Garry Wills]] and [[M. Stanton Evans]]. Nevertheless, Burns argues, her popularity and her influence on the Right forced Buckley and his circle into a reconsideration of how traditional notions of virtue and Christianity could be integrated with all-out support for capitalism.<ref>Jennifer Burns, \"Godless Capitalism: Ayn Rand and the Conservative Movement,\" ''Modern Intellectual History,'' (2004) 1#3 pp. 359\u201385</ref>\n\nDuring the 1950s, Buckley worked to remove [[anti-Semitism]] from the conservative movement and barred holders of those views from working for ''National Review''.<ref name=stnyt8/>\n\nIn 1962, Buckley denounced [[Robert W. Welch Jr.]] and the [[John Birch Society]] in ''National Review'' as \"far removed from common sense\" and urged the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] to purge itself of Welch's influence.<ref>William F. Buckley Jr., \"Goldwater, the John Birch Society, and Me\". [http://www.commentarymagazine.com/article/goldwater-the-john-birch-society-and-me/ ''Commentary'' (March 2008) online]</ref>\n\n===Views on race and segregation===\nIn the 1950s and early 1960s, Buckley opposed federal civil rights legislation and expressed support for continued racial segregation in the South. In ''Freedom Is Not Enough: The Opening of the American Workplace'', author Nancy MacLean states that ''National Review'' made [[James J. Kilpatrick]]\u2014a prominent supporter of segregation in the South\u2014\"its voice on the [[civil rights movement]] and the Constitution, as Buckley and Kilpatrick united North and South in a shared vision for the nation that included upholding [[white supremacy]]\".<ref>Nancy MacLean, ''Freedom Is Not Enough: The Opening of the American Workplace'' (2008) p. 46</ref> In the August 24, 1957 issue of ''National Review'', Buckley's editorial \"Why the South Must Prevail\" spoke out explicitly in favor of temporary segregation in the South until \"long term equality could be achieved\". It argued that \"the central question that emerges&nbsp;... is whether the White community in the South is entitled to take such measures as are necessary to prevail, politically and culturally, in areas where it does not predominate numerically? The sobering answer is Yes\u2014the White community is so entitled because, for the time being, it is the advanced race.\"<ref>Sean Wilentz, ''The Age of Reagan: A History, 1974\u20132008'' (HarperCollins, 2009) p. 471</ref><ref>John B. Judis, ''William F. Buckley Jr.: Patron Saint of the Conservatives'' (2001) p. 138</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://adamgomez.files.wordpress.com/2012/03/whythesouthmustprevail-1957.pdf|title=Why the South Must Prevail|last=Buckley|first=William F.|date=August 24, 1957|work=National Review|access-date=September 16, 2017|volume=4|pages=148\u201349|type=}}</ref> Buckley opined that temporary segregation in the South was a good idea at the time (in 1957) and the black population lacked the education, economic, and cultural development to make racial equality possible. Buckley claimed that the white South had \"the right to impose superior mores for whatever period it takes to effect a genuine cultural equality between the races\".<ref>Judis, ''William F. Buckley Jr.'' p. 138</ref><ref>Stephen J. Whitfield, ''A death in the Delta: the story of Emmett Till'' (Johns Hopkins U.P. p. 11</ref><ref>Jeremy Lott, ''William F. Buckley Jr.'' (2010) p. 136</ref><ref>Joseph Crespinon, ''In Search of another Country: Mississippi and the Conservative Counterrevolution'' (Princeton U.P., 2007) pp. 81\u201382</ref> Two weeks after that editorial was published, another prominent conservative writer, [[L. Brent Bozell Jr.]] (Buckley's brother-in-law), wrote in the ''National Review'': \"This magazine has expressed views on the racial question that I consider dead wrong, and capable of doing great hurt to the promotion of conservative causes. There is a law involved, and a Constitution, and the editorial gives White Southerners leave to violate them both in order to keep the Negro politically impotent.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/buckleywilliamfb0000bogu|url-access=registration|title=Buckley: William F. Buckley Jr. and the Rise of American Conservatism|first=Carl T.|last=Bogus|date=November 1, 2011|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing USA|via=Internet Archive}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bp15_FjIadgC|title=From the New Deal to the New Right: Race and the Southern Origins of Modern Conservatism|first=Joseph E.|last=Lowndes|date=October 1, 2008|publisher=Yale University Press|via=Google Books|isbn=978-0300148282}}</ref>\n\n''[[Politico]]'' indicates that during the administration of [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], Buckley's writing grew more accommodating toward the civil rights movement. In his columns, he \"ridiculed practices designed to keep African Americans off the voter registration rolls\", \"condemned proprietors of commercial establishments who declined service to African Americans in violation of the recently enacted 1964 Civil Rights Act\", and showed \"little patience\" for \"Southern politicians who incited racial violence and race-baited in their campaigns\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/05/13/william-f-buckley-civil-rights-215129|title=How William F. Buckley, Jr., Changed His Mind on Civil Rights|first=Alvin|last=Felzenberg|website=POLITICO Magazine}}</ref> However, Buckley continued to downplay structural racism and place a large amount of blame for lack of economic growth on the black community itself, most prominently during a highly publicized 1965 debate with African-American writer [[James Baldwin]] at the [[Cambridge Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oFeoS41xe7w|title=James Baldwin Debates William F. Buckley (1965)|last=The Riverbends Channel|date=October 27, 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/?id=hAqdBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT23&dq=buckley+and+mailer#v=onepage&q=baldwin&f=false|title=Buckley and Mailer: The Difficult Friendship That Shaped the Sixties|accessdate=June 7, 2015|isbn=9780393248234|last1=Schultz|first1=Kevin M.|date=June 2015}}</ref> In the late 1960s, Buckley disagreed with segregationist [[George Wallace]] and debated against his segregationist platform on ''[[Firing Line (TV series)|Firing Line]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/cognoscenti/2017/03/06/resisting-trump-the-william-f-buckley-jr-way-rich-barlow|title=Anatomy Of A Takedown: William F. Buckley Jr. Vs. George Wallace|website=[[wbur.org]]}}</ref>\n\nBuckley later said he wished ''National Review'' had been more supportive of civil rights legislation in the 1960s.<ref>{{cite book |last=Felzenberg |first=Alvin S. |date=2017 |title=A Man and His Presidents: The Political Odyssey of William F. Buckley Jr. |url= |location=New Haven & London |publisher=Yale University Press |pages=159\u201360\n|isbn=978-0-300-16384-1 |author-link=Alvin S. Felzenberg |quote=I once believed we could evolve our way up from Jim Crow. I was wrong. Federal intervention was necessary.}}</ref> He grew to admire [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] and supported the creation of a [[Martin Luther King, Jr. Day]] national holiday memorializing him.<ref name=stnyt8>Tanenhaus, Sam, [http://papercuts.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/02/27/qa-with-sam-tanenhaus-on-william-f-buckley/ on William F. Buckley], ''Paper Cuts'' blog at ''The New York Times'' website, February 27, 2008.</ref> In 2004, Buckley told ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', \"'I once believed we could evolve our way up from Jim Crow. I was wrong. Federal intervention was necessary.'\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nBuckley attempted in 2004 to clarify his earlier comments on race, saying: \"[T]he point I made about white cultural supremacy was sociological.\" Buckley also linked his usage of the word ''advancement'' to its usage in the name [[NAACP]], stating that \"[the] call for the 'advancement' of colored people presupposes they are behind. Which they were, in 1958, by any standards of measurement.\"<ref name=nytmds/>\n\n===Democracy and communism===\nBuckley's opposition to Communism extended to support for the overthrow and replacement of leftist governments by nondemocratic forces. Buckley supported Spanish [[authoritarian]] dictator General [[Francisco Franco]], who led the rightist military rebellion in its [[Spanish Civil War|military defeat]] of the [[Second Spanish Republic|Spanish Republic]]. He called Franco \"an authentic national hero,\" applauding his overthrow of Spanish Republican \"visionaries, ideologues, Marxists and nihilists.\"<ref>''National Review'', 10/26/57.{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref> He supported the military dictatorship of General [[Augusto Pinochet]], who led the [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat|1973 coup]] that overthrew [[Chile]]an president [[Salvador Allende]]'s democratically elected [[Marxist]] government; Buckley referred to Allende as \"a president who was defiling the Chilean constitution and waving proudly the banner of his friend and idol, [[Fidel Castro]].\"<ref>''National Review'', November 23, 1998.{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===The Buckley Rule===\n{{quotebox|''National Review'' will support the rightwardmost viable candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/340485/buckley-rule-according-bill-not-karl-neal-b-freeman/page/0/1|title=Buckley Rule \u2013 According to Bill, not Karl|author=Neal B. Freeman|work=National Review Online}}</ref>}}\n\nThe Buckley Rule states that ''National Review'' \"will support the rightwardmost viable candidate\" for a given office. Buckley first stated the Buckley Rule during the 1964 Republican primary election featuring Barry Goldwater and Nelson Rockefeller. The Rule is often misquoted and misapplied as proclaiming support for \"the rightwardmost electable candidate\", or simply the most electable candidate.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murdock |first1=Deroy |title=Follow the Buckley Standard: Vote for Trump |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2016/11/william-f-buckley-donald-trump-republican-conservative-electable-candidate/ |website=nationalreview.com |publisher=National Review |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''National Review''{{'}}s [[Neal B. Freeman]], the Buckley Rule meant that ''National Review'' would support \"somebody who saw the world as we did. Somebody who would bring credit to our cause. Somebody who, win or lose, would conservatize the Republican party and the country. It meant somebody like Barry Goldwater.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/340485/buckley-rule-according-bill-not-karl-neal-b-freeman/page/0/1|title=Buckley Rule \u2013 According to Bill, not Karl |author=Neal B. Freeman|work=National Review Online}}</ref>\n\n==Political commentary and action==\n===Young Americans for Freedom and Barry Goldwater===\nIn 1960, Buckley helped form [[Young Americans for Freedom]] (YAF). The YAF was guided by principles Buckley called \"The [[Sharon Statement]]\". Buckley was proud of the successful campaign of his older brother, [[James L. Buckley|Jim Buckley]], on the Conservative Party ticket to capture the US Senate seat from New York State held by incumbent Republican [[Charles Goodell]] in 1970, giving very generous credit to the activist support of the New York State chapter of Y.A.F. Buckley served one term in the Senate, then was defeated by Democrat [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] in 1976.<ref>Judis, ''William F. Buckley Jr.: Patron Saint of the Conservatives'' pp. 185\u201398, 311</ref>\n\nIn 1963\u201364, Buckley mobilized support for the candidacy of Arizona Senator [[Barry Goldwater]], first for the [[History of the Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nomination against New York Governor [[Nelson Rockefeller]] and then for the Presidency. Buckley used ''National Review'' as a forum for mobilizing support for Goldwater.<ref>Judis, ''William F. Buckley Jr.: Patron Saint of the Conservatives'' ch. 10</ref>\n\n===''On the Right''===\nBuckley's column ''On the Right'' was syndicated by [[Universal Press Syndicate]] beginning in 1962. From the early 1970s, his twice-weekly column was distributed to more than 320 newspapers across the country.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quarles |first1=Philip |title=William F. Buckley Jr., Mayoral Candidate, on Political Rhetoric and Theater,1965 |url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/219301-william-buckley/ |website=wnyc.org |publisher=New York Public Radio |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Edgar Herbert Smith Jr.===\nIn 1962, the convicted murderer [[Edgar Smith (murderer)|Edgar Smith]] began a correspondence with Buckley during which Buckley began to doubt Smith's guilt, later stating that the case was \"inherently implausible\".<ref name=\"multiple\">{{cite web|author=Manning, Lona|url=http://www.crimemagazine.com/great-prevaricator-0|title=Edgar Smith: The Great Prevaricator|work=Crime Magazine|date=October 9, 2009|accessdate=March 10, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103083010/http://crimemagazine.com/great-prevaricator-0|archive-date=January 3, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAn article by Buckley in November 1965, published in ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', drew national media attention:\n\n{{quote|Smith said he told Hommell during their brief conversation&nbsp;... on the night of the murder just where he had discarded his pants. The woman who occupies property across the road from which Smith claimed to have thrown the pants&nbsp;... swore at the trial that she had seen Hommell rummaging there the day after the murder. The pants were later found [by the police] near a well-travelled road&nbsp;... Did Hommell find them, and leave them in the other location, thinking to discredit Smith's story, and make sure they would turn up?<ref name=\"multiple\"/>}}\n\nThis brought renewed media interest in a Don Hommell, who Smith claimed was the real killer.<ref name=\"multiple\"/>\n\nIn 1971, Smith was able to have a retrial. He walked free later that year. In 1976, he attempted another murder and was sentenced to life in prison. He also admitted that he had, in fact, committed the first murder with which he had been charged.<ref>{{cite web|author=Stout, David| work=The New York Times|date=September 24, 2017|title=Edgar Smith, Killer Who Duped William F. Buckley, Dies at 83|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/24/nyregion/edgar-smith-killer-who-duped-william-f-buckley-dies-at-83.html}}</ref>\n\n===Mayoral candidacy===\nIn [[1965 New York City mayoral election|1965]], Buckley ran for [[mayor of New York City]] as the candidate for the new [[Conservative Party of New York State|Conservative Party]]. He ran to restore momentum to the conservative cause in the wake of Goldwater's defeat.<ref>Jonathan Schoenwald, ''A Time for Choosing: The Rise of Modern American Conservatism'' (2002) pp. 162\u201389</ref> He tried to take votes away from the relatively [[Rockefeller Republican|liberal Republican]] candidate and fellow Yale alumnus [[John Lindsay]], who later became a Democrat. Buckley did not expect to win; when asked what he would do if he won the race, he responded, \"Demand a recount.\"<ref name=\"tanenhaus\"/> He used an unusual campaign style. During one televised debate with Lindsay, Buckley declined to use his allotted rebuttal time and instead replied, \"I am satisfied to sit back and contemplate my own former eloquence.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20080228/having-a-beer-with-william-f-buckley-jr|title=Having a beer with William F. Buckley Jr.|date=February 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nTo relieve traffic congestion, Buckley proposed charging drivers a [[congestion pricing|fee to enter the central city]] and creating a network of [[bike lane]]s. He opposed a [[Civilian Complaint Review Board|civilian review board]] for the [[New York Police Department]], which Lindsay had recently introduced to control police corruption and install community policing.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Perlstein|first=Rick|authorlink=Rick Perlstein|title=Nixonland: The Rise of a President and the Fracturing of America|year=2008|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-7432-4302-5|pages=144\u201346|title-link=Nixonland: The Rise of a President and the Fracturing of America}}</ref> Buckley finished third with 13.4% of the vote, possibly having inadvertently aided Lindsay's election by instead taking votes from Democratic candidate [[Abe Beame]].<ref name=\"tanenhaus\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/02/magazine/02buckley.html|title=The Buckley Effect|accessdate=November 12, 2007| last = Tanenhaus | first = Sam | work=The New York Times|date=October 2, 2005|authorlink=Sam Tanenhaus}}</ref>\n\n===Break with the Nixon administration===\nIn July 1971, Buckley assembled a group of conservatives to discuss some of Nixon's domestic and foreign policies that the group opposed. In August 1969, Nixon had proposed and later attempted to enact welfare legislation known as the Family Assistance Plan (FAP), which would establish a national income floor of $1600 per year for a family of four.<ref>Small, Melvin (1999). The Presidency of Richard Nixon. University Press of Kansas. {{ISBN|0-7006-0973-3}}.</ref> On the international front he negotiated arms talks with the Soviet Union and initiated relations with China, which Buckley, as a hawk and anti-communist, opposed. The group, known as the Manhattan Twelve, included National Review's publisher [[William A. Rusher]] and editors [[James Burnham]] and [[Frank Meyer (political philosopher)|Frank Meyer]]. Other organizations represented were the newspaper ''[[Human Events]]'', The Conservative Book Club, [[Young Americans for Freedom]], and the [[American Conservative Union]].<ref>Laurence Jurdem. October 25, 2016. ''When National Review Finally Had Enough of Richard Nixon: A Chorus of Disapproval:''  http://laurencejurdem.com/2016/10/when-national-review-finally-had-enough-of-richard-nixon-a-chorus-of-disapproval/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312144232/http://laurencejurdem.com/2016/10/when-national-review-finally-had-enough-of-richard-nixon-a-chorus-of-disapproval/ |date=March 12, 2018 }}</ref> On July 28, 1971, they published a letter announcing that they would no longer support Nixon.<ref>Tad Szulc. July 29, 1971. ''11 Conservatives criticize Nixon'' New York Times. page 7.  https://www.nytimes.com/1971/07/29/archives/11-conservatives-criticize-nixon-headed-by-william-buckley-they.html</ref> The letter said, \"In consideration of his record, the undersigned, who have heretofore generally supported the Nixon Administration, have resolved to suspend our support of the Administration.\" Buckley would later go on to join the administration as a delegate to the UN.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Redman |first1=Eric |title=William Buckley Reports on a Tour of Duty |url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/00/07/16/specials/buckley-un.html |website=nytimes.com |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''Firing Line''===\n[[File:William F. Buckley, Jr. with President Reagan 1986.jpg|thumb|Buckley with President [[Ronald Reagan]] at Reagan's birthday celebration, 1986]]\n[[File:Reagan with William F. Buckley, Jr 1988.jpg|thumb|right|Buckley with Reagan in the [[Oval Office]], 1988]]\n\nFor many Americans, Buckley's erudition on his weekly [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] show ''[[Firing Line (TV series)|Firing Line]]'' (1966\u20131999) was their primary exposure to him and his manner of speech, often with vocabulary common in academia but unusual on television.<ref>{{cite book|author=Charles R. Kesler and John B. Kienker|title=Life, Liberty, and the Pursuit of Happiness: Ten Years of the Claremont Review of Books|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O4g_WKk1dOoC&pg=PA86|year=2012|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|page=86|isbn=9781442213357}}</ref>\n\nThroughout his career as a media figure, Buckley had received much criticism\u2014largely from the American left, but also from certain factions on the right, such as the [[John Birch Society]] and its second president, [[Larry McDonald]], as well as from [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivists]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capmag.com/article.asp?ID=5128|title=William F. Buckley Jr.: The Witch-Doctor is Dead|publisher=Capmag.com|accessdate=2015-05-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114130355/http://capmag.com/article.asp?ID=5128|archive-date=January 14, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953\u201354, long before he founded ''Firing Line'', Buckley was an occasional panelist on the conservative [[Public affairs (broadcasting)|public affairs]] program ''[[Answers for Americans]]'' broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] and based on material from the [[H. L. Hunt]]\u2013supported publication ''Facts Forum''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jfredmacdonald.com/macfilms/Press%20Release%202.htm |title=MacDonald & Associates: Facts Forum press release |publisher=jfredmacdonald.com |accessdate=June 13, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110112234003/http://www.jfredmacdonald.com/macfilms/Press%20Release%202.htm |archivedate=January 12, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Feud with Gore Vidal===\nWhen asked if there was one person with whom Buckley would not share a stage, Buckley's response was [[Gore Vidal]]. Likewise, Vidal's antagonism toward Buckley was well known, even before 1968.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rosen|first1=James|title=The Long, Hot Summer Of '68|journal=National Review|date=7 September 2015|volume=67|issue=16|pages=37\u201342|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/nrd/articles/422804/long-hot-summer-68|accessdate=28 September 2015}}</ref> Buckley appeared in a series of televised debates with Vidal during the [[1968 Republican National Convention]] in Miami and the [[1968 Democratic National Convention|Democratic National Convention]] in Chicago.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/26/movies/buckley-vs-vidal-when-debate-became-bloodsport.html|title=Buckley vs. Vidal: When Debate Became Bloodsport|first=Michael M.|last=Grynbaum|date=July 24, 2015|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nIn their penultimate debate on August 28 of that year, the two disagreed over the actions of the [[Chicago Police Department]] and the protesters at the ongoing convention. In reference to the response of the police involved in supposedly taking down a Viet Cong flag, moderator [[Howard K. Smith]] asked whether raising a Nazi flag during the Second World War would have elicited a similar response. Vidal responded that people were free to state their political views as they saw fit, whereupon Buckley interrupted and noted that people were free to speak their views but others were also free to ostracize them for holding those views, noting that in the US during the Second World War \"some people were pro-[[Nazi]] and they were well treated by those who ostracized them\u2014and I'm for ostracizing people who egg on other people to shoot American Marines and American soldiers. I know you [Vidal] don't care because you have no sense of identification with\u2014\". Vidal then interjected that \"the only sort of [[Crypto-Nazism|pro- or crypto-Nazi]] I can think of is yourself,\" whereupon Smith interjected, \"Now let's not call names.\" Buckley, visibly angered, rose several inches from his seat and replied, \"Now listen, you [[queer]], stop calling me a crypto-Nazi or I'll sock you in your goddamn face, and you'll stay plastered.\"<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Buckley later apologized in print for having called Vidal a \"queer\" in a burst of anger rather than in a clinical context, but also reiterated his distaste for Vidal as an \"evangelist for [[bisexuality]]\": \"The man who in his essays proclaims the normalcy of his affliction, and in his art the desirability of it, is not to be confused with the man who bears his sorrow quietly. The addict is to be pitied and even respected, not the pusher.\"<ref>''Esquire'' (August 1969), p. 132</ref> The debates are chronicled in the 2015 documentary ''[[Best of Enemies (2015 film)|Best of Enemies]]''.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThis feud continued the following year in the pages of ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', which commissioned essays from both Buckley and Vidal on the television incident. Buckley's essay \"On Experiencing Gore Vidal\" was published in the August 1969 issue. In September, Vidal responded with his own essay, \"A Distasteful Encounter with William F. Buckley\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Gore|last=Vidal|authorlink=Gore Vidal|title=A Distasteful Encounter with William F. Buckley Jr|url=http://www.columbia.edu/~tdk3/vidalesquire69.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050216165523/http://www.columbia.edu/~tdk3/vidalesquire69.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2005-02-16|work=Esquire|pages=140\u201345, 150|date= September 1969|accessdate=February 28, 2008}}</ref> In it Vidal strongly implied that, in 1944, Buckley's unnamed siblings, and possibly Buckley himself, had vandalized a [[Protestantism|Protestant]] church in their [[Sharon, Connecticut]], hometown after the pastor's wife had sold a house to a [[Jewish]] family. He also implied that Buckley was a homosexual<ref name=\"Colacello, 2009\">{{cite news|last1=Colacello|first1=Bob|title=Mr. and Mrs. Right|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/01/buckleys200901|accessdate=22 June 2016|magazine=Vanity Fair|date=January 2009|quote=In follow-up pieces in Esquire, Buckley focused on homosexual themes in Vidal's work, and Vidal responded by implying that Buckley was a homosexual and an anti-Semite, whereupon Buckley sued and Vidal countersued.}}</ref> and a \"racist, antiblack, [[anti-Semite|anti-Semitic]] and a pro-crypto Nazi.\"<ref name=\"NYT_1972\">{{cite news|title=Buckley Drops Vidal Suit, Settles With Esquire|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/03/01/home/vidal-suit.html|accessdate=22 June 2016|newspaper=New York Times|date=September 26, 1972|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124095336/http://www.nytimes.com/books/98/03/01/home/vidal-suit.html|archivedate=January 24, 2016|quote=Mr. Gingrich confirmed that Esquire would publish a statement in its November issue disavowing 'the most vivid statements' of the Vidal article, calling Mr. Buckley 'racist, antiblack, anti-Semitic and a pro-crypto Nazi.'}}</ref> Buckley sued Vidal and ''Esquire'' for libel; Vidal counter-claimed for libel against Buckley, citing Buckley's characterization of Vidal's novel ''[[Myra Breckenridge]]'' as pornography. After Buckley received an out-of-court settlement from ''Esquire'', he also dropped the suit against Vidal. Both cases were dropped,<ref name=NR>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/document/document200412140834.asp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090826230758/http://www.nationalreview.com/document/document200412140834.asp|url-status=dead|title=National Review|archivedate=August 26, 2009}}</ref> with Buckley settling for court costs paid by ''Esquire'' magazine, which had published the piece, while Vidal, who did not sue the magazine, absorbed his own court costs, but neither had paid each other compensation. Buckley also received an editorial apology in the pages of ''Esquire'' as part of the settlement.<ref name=NR/><ref name=\"round\">{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2004/12/20/buckley-and-vidal-one-more-round/ |title=Buckley and Vidal: One More Round |last=Murphy |first=Jarrett |date=December 20, 2004| accessdate=October 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe feud was reopened in 2003 when ''Esquire'' republished the original Vidal essay as part of a collection entitled ''Esquire\u2019s Big Book of Great Writing''. After further litigation, ''Esquire'' agreed to pay $65,000 to Buckley and his attorneys, to destroy every remaining copy of the book that included the Vidal essay, to furnish Buckley's 1969 essay to anyone who asked for it, and to publish an open letter stating that the current management of ''Esquire'' was \"'not aware of the history of this litigation and greatly [regretted] the re-publication of the libels'\" in the 2003 collection.<ref name=round/>\n\nBuckley maintained a philosophical antipathy towards Vidal's other [[wikt:b\u00eate noire|''b\u00eate noire'']], [[Norman Mailer]], calling him \"almost unique in his search for notoriety and absolutely unequalled in his co-existence with it.\"<ref>[http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=YzhhYmYzNjQzM2ViYmMzZmUwNjRiZTQ4YTVmY2I1OTY= National Review]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109170548/http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=YzhhYmYzNjQzM2ViYmMzZmUwNjRiZTQ4YTVmY2I1OTY%3D |date=January 9, 2009 }}</ref> Meanwhile, Mailer summed up Buckley as having a \"second-rate intellect incapable of entertaining two serious thoughts in a row.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/27/business/media/27cnd-buckley.html?_r=1|work=The New York Times|first=Douglas|last=Martin|title=William F. Buckley Jr. Is Dead at 82|date=February 27, 2008}}</ref> After Mailer's 2007 death, however, Buckley wrote warmly about their personal acquaintance.\n\n===Associations with liberal politicians===\nBuckley became close friends with liberal Democratic activist [[Allard K. Lowenstein]]. Buckley featured Lowenstein on numerous ''[[Firing Line (TV series)|Firing Line]]'' programs, publicly endorsed his candidacies for [[United States Congress|US Congress]], and delivered a eulogy at his funeral.<ref>''Firing Line'', [http://hoohila.stanford.edu/firingline/programView2.php?programID=843 \"Allard Lowenstein: A Retrospective\", Episode #415] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104063943/http://hoohila.stanford.edu/firingline/programView2.php?programID=843 |date=November 4, 2013 }}, May 18, 1980</ref><ref>Buckley, William F. Jr., ''On The Firing Line: The Public Life of Our Public Figures'', 1988, pp. 423\u201334</ref>\n\nBuckley was also friends with economist [[John Kenneth Galbraith]]<ref>''The Sydney Morning Herald'', [https://www.smh.com.au/news/obituaries/mordant-wit-perched-atop-manhattan-society/2007/04/27/1177459974997.html?page=2 \"Mordant wit perched atop Manhattan society (Pat Buckley, 1926-2007)\"], Mark McGinness, April 28, 2007</ref><ref>''The Daily Beast'', [http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2008/10/14/sorry-dad-i-was-fired.html \"Buckley Bows Out of National Review\"], Christopher Buckley, October 14, 2008</ref> and former senator and presidential candidate [[George McGovern]],<ref>C-SPAN, [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/80308-1 \"Conservative v. Liberal Ideology\"] (Debate: William F. Buckley v. George S. McGovern), Southeast Missouri State University, April 10, 1997</ref> both of whom he frequently featured or debated on ''[[Firing Line (TV series)|Firing Line]]'' and college campuses. He and Galbraith were also popular for their occasional appearances on ''[[The Today Show]]'', where host [[Frank McGee (journalist)|Frank McGee]] would introduce them and then deftly step aside and defer to the verbal thrust and parry.<ref>Hoover Institute, Stanford University, Library and Archives, [http://hoohila.stanford.edu/firingline The ''Firing Line'' Archive] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150423135750/http://hoohila.stanford.edu/firingline/ |date=April 23, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===United Nations delegate===\nIn 1973, the [[Nixon Administration]] appointed Buckley to serve as a delegate to the United Nations, upon which Buckley would later write a book.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/07/16/specials/buckley-un.html|title=William Buckley Reports on a Tour of Duty|publisher=}}</ref> In 1981, Buckley informed President-elect (and personal friend) [[Ronald Reagan]] that he would decline any official position offered to him. Reagan jokingly replied that was too bad, because he had wanted to make Buckley ambassador to (then [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]-occupied) [[Afghanistan]]. Buckley replied that he was willing to take the job but only if he were to be supplied with \"10 divisions of bodyguards\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-6724737060193073610&q=william+buckley|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106215734/http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-6724737060193073610&q=william+buckley|url-status=dead|title=Google Video|archivedate=January 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Amnesty International===\nIn the late 1960s, Buckley joined the Board of Directors of [[Amnesty International USA]].<ref name=\"newark 1970\">{{cite news|last=Buckley|first=William F.|author-link=William F. Buckley|title=Amnesty International|newspaper=Newark Advocate|page=4|date=April 13, 1970}}</ref> He resigned in January 1978 in protest over the organization's stance against [[capital punishment]] as expressed in its [[Stockholm Declaration]] of 1977, which he said would lead to the \"inevitable sectarianization of the amnesty movement\".<ref name=\"archivaria 1995\">{{cite journal|last=Montgomery|first=Bruce P.|title=Archiving Human Rights: The Records of Amnesty International USA|journal=Archivaria|issue=39|date=Spring 1995|url=http://journals.sfu.ca/archivar/index.php/archivaria/article/view/12073/13055}}</ref>\n\n===Views on HIV/AIDS===\nIn an op-ed piece in ''The New York Times'' on March 18, 1986, Buckley addressed the AIDS epidemic. Calling it \"a fact\" that AIDS is \"the special curse of the homosexual,\" Buckley argued that people infected with the disease should only marry if they agreed to [[sterilization (medicine)|sterilization]] and that universal testing\u2014led by insurance companies, not the government\u2014should be mandatory. Most controversially of all, he wrote: \"Everyone detected with AIDS should be tattooed in the upper forearm, to protect common-needle users, and on the buttocks, to prevent the victimization of other homosexuals.\"<ref>The New York Times, \"Crucial Steps in Combating the Aids Epidemic; Identify All the Carriers,\" March 18, 1986</ref> The piece led to much criticism; some gay activists advocated boycotting Patricia Buckley's fund-raising efforts for AIDS. William Buckley later back-tracked from the piece, but in 2004 he told ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'', \"If the protocol had been accepted, many who caught the infection unguardedly would be alive. Probably over a million.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Interviewed by Deborah Solomon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/11/magazine/way-we-live-now-7-11-04-questions-for-william-f-buckley-conservatively-speaking.html |title=The Way We Live Now, 7/11/04: Questions for William F. Buckley; Conservatively Speaking |publisher=The New York Times Magazine |date=2004-07-11 |accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==Spy novelist==\nIn 1975, Buckley recounted being inspired to write a spy novel by [[Frederick Forsyth]]'s ''[[The Day of the Jackal]]'': \"...&nbsp;If I were to write a book of fiction, I'd like to have a whack at something of that nature.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Interviewed by Sam Vaughan |url=http://www.theparisreview.org/viewinterview.php/prmMID/1395 |title=The Art of Fiction No. 146, William F. Buckley Jr |publisher=Paris Review |date=1925-11-24 |accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref> He went on to explain that he was determined to avoid the moral ambiguity of [[Graham Greene]] and [[John le Carr\u00e9]]. Buckley wrote the 1976 spy novel ''[[Saving the Queen]]'', featuring [[Blackford Oakes]] as a rule-bound CIA agent, based in part on his own CIA experiences. Over the next 30 years, he would write another ten novels featuring Oakes. ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' critic Charlie Rubin wrote that the series \"at its best, evokes [[John O'Hara]] in its precise sense of place amid simmering class hierarchies\".<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/17/books/review/17RUBINL.html?ex=1279339200&en=845293053a63c725&ei=5088 'Last Call for Blackford Oakes': Cocktails With Philby], Charlie Rubin, ''The New York Times'', July 17, 2005</ref> ''[[Stained Glass (novel)|Stained Glass]]'', second in the series, won a 1980 [[National Book Award]] in the [[List of winners of the National Book Award#Miscellaneous 1980 to 1985|one-year category Mystery (paperback)]].<ref name=\"nb a1980\">[https://www.nationalbook.org/awards-prizes/national-book-awards-1980 \"National Book Awards \u2013 1980\"]. [[National Book Foundation]]. Retrieved 2012-02-28. (With essay by Harold Augenbraum from the Awards' 60-year anniversary blog.)</ref><ref group=lower-alpha>From 1980 to 1983 in [[National Book Award#History|National Book Award history]] there were dual awards for hardcover and paperback books in many categories. Most of the paperback award-winners were reprints, including this one.</ref>\n\nBuckley was particularly concerned about the view that what the CIA and the KGB were doing was morally equivalent. He wrote in his memoirs, \"To say that the CIA and the KGB engage in similar practices is the equivalent of saying that the man who pushes an old lady into the path of a hurtling bus is not to be distinguished from the man who pushes an old lady out of the path of a hurtling bus: on the grounds that, after all, in both cases someone is pushing old ladies around.\"<ref>Linda Bridges and John R. Coyne, ''Strictly Right: William F. Buckley Jr. and the American Conservative Movement'' (2007) p. 182</ref>\n\nBuckley began writing on computers in 1982, starting with a [[Zenith Z-89]].<ref name=\"shea19820913\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EDAEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA25&pg=PA26#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Buckley finds word processing on Z-89 'liberating' | work=InfoWorld | date=1982-09-13 | accessdate=9 January 2015 | author=Shea, Tom | page=26}}</ref> According to his son, Buckley developed an almost fanatical loyalty to [[WordStar]], installing it on every new PC he got despite its growing obsolescence over the years. Buckley used it to write his last novel, and when asked why he continued using something so outdated, he answered \"They say there's better software, but they also say there's better alphabets.\"\n\n==Later career==\n[[File:William F. Buckley, Jr. with President Bush 2005.jpg|thumb|Buckley shakes hands with President [[George W. Bush]] on October 6, 2005]]\n\nIn 1988, Buckley helped defeat liberal Republican Senator [[Lowell Weicker]] in Connecticut. Buckley organized a committee to campaign against Weicker and endorsed his Democratic opponent, Connecticut Attorney General [[Joseph Lieberman]].<ref>[http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=NGEwNmYxYjRhZmRkZjA4MmM1YzE5MDIzMzJlYjExNmU= National Review]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109212724/http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=NGEwNmYxYjRhZmRkZjA4MmM1YzE5MDIzMzJlYjExNmU%3D |date=January 9, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, Buckley received the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] from President [[George H. W. Bush]]. Upon turning 65 in 1990, he retired from the day-to-day running of the ''National Review''.<ref name=encyc/><ref name=flashback/> He relinquished his controlling shares of ''National Review'' in June 2004 to a pre-selected board of trustees. The following month, he published the memoir ''Miles Gone By''. Buckley continued to write his syndicated newspaper column, as well as opinion pieces for ''National Review'' magazine and ''National Review Online''. He remained the ultimate source of authority at the magazine and also conducted lectures and gave interviews.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=3387080 |title=A Life on the Right: William F. Buckley |publisher=NPR |date= |accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref>\n\n===Views on modern-day conservatism===\nBuckley criticized certain aspects of policy within the modern conservative movement. Of [[George W. Bush]]'s presidency, he said, \"If you had a European prime minister who experienced what we've experienced it would be expected that he would retire or resign.\"<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/07/22/eveningnews/main1826838.shtml |title=Buckley: Bush Not A True Conservative |publisher=CBS News |date=2006-07-22 |accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref>\n\nRegarding the [[War in Iraq]], Buckley stated, \"The reality of the situation is that missions abroad to effect regime change in countries without a bill of rights or democratic tradition are terribly arduous.\" He added: \"This isn't to say that the Iraq war is wrong, or that history will judge it to be wrong. But it is absolutely to say that conservatism implies a certain submission to reality; and this war has an unrealistic frank and is being conscripted by events.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acuf.org/issues/issue49/051204news.asp|title=Season of Conservative Sloth|accessdate=July 27, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607122729/http://acuf.org/issues/issue49/051204news.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archivedate=June 7, 2007}}</ref> In a February 2006 column published at ''National Review Online'' and distributed by [[Universal Press Syndicate]], Buckley stated unequivocally that, \"One cannot doubt that the American objective in Iraq has failed.\" Buckley has also stated that \"...&nbsp;it's important that we acknowledge in the inner councils of state that it (the war) has failed, so that we should look for opportunities to cope with that failure.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/buckley/buckley200602241451.asp |title=It Didn't Work |accessdate=July 27, 2007 |work=National Review |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702035617/http://www.nationalreview.com/buckley/buckley200602241451.asp |archivedate=July 2, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Jeffrey Hart]], writing in ''[[The American Conservative]]'', Buckley had a \"tragic\" view of the Iraq war: he \"saw it as a disaster and thought that the conservative movement he had created had in effect committed intellectual suicide by failing to maintain critical distance from the Bush administration&nbsp;... At the end of his life, Buckley believed the movement he made had destroyed itself by supporting the war in Iraq.\"<ref>Right at the end, ''[[The American Conservative]], March 24, 2008</ref> Regarding the [[Iraq War troop surge of 2007]], however, it is noted by the editors of ''National Review'' that: \"Buckley initially opposed the surge, but after seeing its early success believed it deserved more time to work.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nrd.nationalreview.com/article/?q=YzllM2IwOGRmODM5YzFhZDEyYjk5MDEwNzBmMTk3MmE=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717033709/http://nrd.nationalreview.com/article/?q=YzllM2IwOGRmODM5YzFhZDEyYjk5MDEwNzBmMTk3MmE%3D|url-status=dead|title=National Review|archivedate=July 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBuckley was an advocate for the legalization of [[marijuana]] and some drug legalization as early as his 1965 candidacy for mayor of New York City.<ref>{{cite journal|date= March 1983|title=Reason Interview: William F. Buckley|journal=Reason |pages=40\u201344|url=http://reason.com/assets/db/159ef03791b35c5bf8537c9cdfd33484.pdf|accessdate=May 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/openmind_ep181|title=The Openmind: Buckley on Drug Legalization|accessdate=July 27, 2007}}</ref> He wrote a pointed pro-marijuana legalization piece for ''National Review'' in 2004 where he calls for conservatives to change their views on legalization, stating, \"We're not going to find someone running for president who advocates reform of those laws. What is required is a genuine republican groundswell. It is happening, but ever so gradually. Two of every five Americans&nbsp;... believe 'the government should treat marijuana more or less the same way it treats alcohol: It should regulate it, control it, tax it, and make it illegal only for children.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://old.nationalreview.com/buckley/buckley200406291207.asp|first=William F. Jr.|last=Buckley|title=Free weed. The marijuana debate|accessdate=October 26, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808091214/http://old.nationalreview.com/buckley/buckley200406291207.asp|archivedate=August 8, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In his December 3, 2007 column, shortly after his wife's death, which he attributed, at least in part, to her smoking, Buckley seemed to advocate banning tobacco use in America.<ref name=\"smokingban\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nysun.com/article/67349|title=My Smoking Confessional| last = Buckley | first = William F. Jr. |date=December 3, 2007|accessdate=February 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAbout [[neoconservative]]s, he said in 2004: \"I think those I know, which is most of them, are bright, informed and idealistic, but that they simply overrate the reach of U.S. power and influence.\"<ref name=nytmds>Sanger, Deborah, [https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/11/magazine/11QUESTIONS.html?ei=5070&en=a78be4479c624bcf&ex=1204952400 \"Questions for William F. Buckley: Conservatively Speaking\"], interview in ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'', July 11, 2004. Retrieved March 6, 2008</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sunsite.berkeley.edu/videodir/asx2/2299.asx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101212011402/http://sunsite.berkeley.edu/videodir/asx2/2299.asx|url-status=dead|title=Video of Buckley debating James Baldwin, October 26, 1965, Cambridge University; digitized by UC Berkeley|archivedate=December 12, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.10zenmonkeys.com/2008/02/28/the-collected-controversies-of-william-f-buckley/ \"The Collected Controversies of William F. Buckley\"], February 28, 2008.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=OWQ4Y2VmNjNmZjhiZTEwOThmNTA3NGY1Y2UwNTE4ZDM= |title=Where does one Start? A Guide to Reading WFB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305130558/http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=OWQ4Y2VmNjNmZjhiZTEwOThmNTA3NGY1Y2UwNTE4ZDM=|archive-date=March 5, 2008|work=National Review|date=February 29, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Johns |first=Michael |url=http://michaeljohnsonfreedomandprosperity.blogspot.com/2008/03/walking-road-that-buckley-built.html |title=Michael Johns: Walking the Road that Buckley Built |publisher=Michaeljohnsonfreedomandprosperity.blogspot.com |date=2008-03-07 |accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref> \n\nVarious organizations have awards and honors named after Buckley.<ref>{{cite web |title=The William F. Buckley Prize Is an Award I\u2019m Unable to Reject |url=https://www.rushlimbaugh.com/daily/2019/10/10/the-william-f-buckley-prize-is-an-award-im-unable-to-reject/ |website=rushlimbaugh.com |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The 8th Annual Buckley Awards |url=https://cei.org/content/8th-annual-buckley-awards |website=cei.org |publisher=Competitive Enterprise Institute |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Intercollegiate Studies Institute]] awards the William F. Buckley Award for Outstanding Campus Journalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legalinsurrection.com/2013/11/oorah-for-the-cornell-review/ |title=Cornell Review &#124; Buckley Award &#124; Collegiate Network |publisher=Legalinsurrection.com |date=2013-11-19 |accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nBuckley died at his home in [[Stamford, Connecticut]], on February 27, 2008 at the age of 82. Initially, it was reported that he was found dead at his desk in his study, a converted garage. \"He died with his boots on\", his son [[Christopher Buckley (novelist)|Christopher Buckley]] said, \"after a lifetime of riding pretty tall in the saddle.\"<ref name=rbhc/> Subsequently, however, in his 2009 book ''Losing Mum and Pup: A Memoir'', Christopher Buckley admitted that this account was an embellishment on his part: his father had actually been found lying on the floor of his study after suffering a fatal heart attack. At the time of his death, he had been suffering from [[emphysema]] and [[diabetes]].<ref name=\"NYTobit\">{{cite news| first = Douglas | last = Martin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/27/business/media/27cnd-buckley.html?hp|title=William F. Buckley Jr. Is Dead at 82|work=The New York Times|date=February 27, 2008|accessdate=February 27, 2008}}</ref> In a December 3, 2007, column, Buckley commented on the cause of his emphysema, citing his lifelong habit of smoking tobacco, despite endorsing a legal ban of it.<ref name=\"smokingban\"/> Buckley's body was buried at the Saint Bernard Cemetery in [[Sharon, Connecticut]], next to his wife Patricia's.<ref>{{findagrave|24915565|William Frank Buckley, Jr}}</ref>\n\nNotable members of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] political establishment paying tribute to Buckley included President [[George W. Bush]],<ref>{{cite press release|title=Statement by the President on Death of William F. Buckley| last = Bush | first = George W. |publisher=Office of the Press Secretary, the White House|date=February 27, 2008|accessdate=February 28, 2008|url= https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2008/02/20080227-4.html}}</ref> former [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]] [[Newt Gingrich]], and former [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Nancy Reagan]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=Nancy Reagan Reacts To Death Of William F. Buckley| last = Reagan | first = Nancy|publisher=The Office of Nancy Reagan|date=February 27, 2008|accessdate=February 28, 2008|url=http://orangecounty.cox.net/cci/newslocal/local?_mode=view&view=LocalNewsArticleView&articleId=3238791&_action=validatearticle}}</ref> Bush said of Buckley, \"[h]e influenced a lot of people, including me. He captured the imagination of a lot of people.\"<ref name=\"AP Buckley dies\">{{cite news|title=Conservative author Buckley dies at 82|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20080227/ap_on_re_us/obit_buckley|date=February 27, 2008|accessdate=February 28, 2008 | agency = Associated Press | publisher = Yahoo! News | last = Italie | first = Hillele | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080301212442/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20080227/ap_on_re_us/obit_buckley <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> | archivedate = March 1, 2008 }}</ref> Gingrich added, \"Bill Buckley became the indispensable intellectual advocate from whose energy, intelligence, wit, and enthusiasm the best of modern conservatism drew its inspiration and encouragement&nbsp;... Buckley began what led to Senator [[Barry Goldwater]] and his ''[[The Conscience of a Conservative|Conscience of a Conservative]]'' that led to the seizing of power by the conservatives from the moderate establishment within the Republican Party. From that emerged [[Ronald Reagan]].\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://newt.org/tabid/102/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/3207/Default.aspx|title=Before there was Goldwater or Reagan, there was Bill Buckley | accessdate = March 4, 2008|publisher=Newt.org| last = Gingrich | first = Newt | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080306012440/http://newt.org/tabid/102/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/3207/Default.aspx <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->| archivedate = March 6, 2008 }}</ref> Reagan's widow, Nancy, commented, \"Ronnie valued Bill's counsel throughout his political life, and after Ronnie died, Bill and Pat were there for me in so many ways.\"<ref name=\"AP Buckley dies\"/>\n\n==Linguistic expertise==\nBuckley was well known for his command of language.<ref>See Schmidt, Julian. (June 6, 2005) ''[[National Review]]'' Notes & asides. (Letter to the Editor) Volume 53; Issue 2. p. 17. (\"Dear Mr. Buckley: You can call off the hunt for the elusive \"encephalophonic\". I have it cornered in ''Webster's Third New International Dictionary'', where the noun \"encephalophone\" is defined as \"an apparatus that emits a continuous hum whose pitch is changed by interference of brain waves transmitted through oscillators from electrodes attached to the scalp and that is used to diagnose abnormal brain functioning.\" I knew right where to look, because you provoked my search for that word a generation ago, when I first (and not last) encountered it in one of your books. If it was used derisively about you, I can only infer that the reviewer's brain was set a-humming by a) his failure to follow your illaqueating (ensnaring) logic, b) his dizzied awe at your manifold talents, and/or c) his inability to distinguish lexiphanicism (the use of pretentious words) from lectio divina. I say, keep it up. We could all do with more brain vibrations.\")</ref> He came late to formal instruction in English, not learning it until he was seven years old and having earlier learned Spanish and French.<ref name=BuckleyJr_2004 /> Michelle Tsai in ''[[Slate.com|Slate]]'' says that he spoke English with an [[idiosyncrasy|idiosyncratic]] accent: something between an old-fashioned, upper class [[Mid-Atlantic English|Mid-Atlantic accent]], and British [[Received Pronunciation]], with a Southern drawl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2185368/|title=Why Did William F. Buckley Jr. talk like that?|last=Tsai|first=Michelle|work=[[Slate.com|Slate]]|date=February 28, 2008|accessdate=February 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Rhetoric===\nEpstein (1972) argues that liberals were especially fascinated by Buckley, and often wanted to debate him, in part because his ideas resembled their own, for Buckley typically formulated his arguments in reaction to left-liberal opinion, rather than being founded on conservative principles that were alien to the liberals.<ref>Joseph Epstein, \"The Politics of William Buckley: Conservative Ideologue as Liberal Celebrity\", ''Dissent'', Oct 1972, Vol. 19 Issue 4, pp. 602\u201361</ref>\n\nAppel (1992) argues from rhetorical theory that Buckley's essays are often written in \"low\" burlesque in the manner of [[Samuel Butler (poet)|Samuel Butler's]] satirical poem \"[[Hudibras]]\". Considered as drama, such discourse features black-and-white disorder, a guilt-mongering logician, distorted clownish opponents, limited scapegoating, and a self-serving redemption.<ref>Edward C. Appel, \"Burlesque drama as a rhetorical genre: The hudibrastic ridicule of William F. Buckley Jr.,\" Western Journal of Communication, Summer 1996, Vol. 60 Issue 3, pp. 269\u201384</ref>\n\nLee (2008) argues that Buckley introduced a new rhetorical style that conservatives often tried to emulate. The \"gladiatorial style\", as Lee calls it, is flashy and combative, filled with sound bites, and leads to an inflammatory drama. As conservatives encountered Buckley's arguments about government, liberalism and markets, the theatrical appeal of Buckley's gladiatorial style inspired conservative imitators, becoming one of the principal templates for conservative rhetoric.<ref>Michael J. Lee, \"WFB: The Gladiatorial Style and the Politics of Provocation,\" ''Rhetoric and Public Affairs,'' Summer 2010, Vol. 13 Issue 2, pp. 43\u201376</ref>\n\n\"Charm, wit, eye-twinkling and rapid deployment of stray [[factoid]]s were among Buckley\u2019s chief rhetorical assets,\" wrote Thomas Meany in the ''New York Times''. \"His main form of reasoning consisted of forced analogies.\"\n\n==Works==\n{{main|William F. Buckley Jr. bibliography}}\n{{see also|List of Blackford Oakes novels}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External references==\n<!---or maybe additional reading--->\n* Appel, Edward C. \"Burlesque drama as a rhetorical genre: The hudibrastic ridicule of William F. Buckley Jr.\", ''Western Journal of Communication,'' Summer 1996, Vol. 60 Issue 3, pp.&nbsp;269\u201384.\n* {{Cite book|first1=Linda|last1=Bridges|first2=John R. Jr.|last2=Coyne|title=Strictly Right: William F. Buckley Jr. and the American Conservative Movement|year=2007|publisher=Wiley|location=Hoboken|isbn=978-0-471-75817-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/strictlyrightwil0000brid}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Reid|last=Buckley|year=1999|title=Strictly Speaking|publisher=McGraw-Hill|location=New York|isbn=0-07-134610-4|url=https://archive.org/details/strictlyspeaking0000buck}}\n* Farber, David. ''The Rise and Fall of Modern American Conservatism: A Short History'' (2010) pp.&nbsp;39\u201376\n* Gottfried, Paul (1993). ''The Conservative Movement''. {{ISBN|0-8057-9749-1}}\n* {{Cite book|first= John B.|last=Judis|authorlink=John Judis|year=1990|title=William F. Buckley Jr.: Patron Saint of the Conservatives|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=978-0-671-45494-4}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Brian|last=Lamb|year=2001|title=Booknotes: Stories from American History|publisher=Penguin|location=New York|isbn=1-58648-083-9|url=https://archive.org/details/booknotesstories00lamb}}\n* Lee, Michael J. \"WFB: The Gladiatorial Style and the Politics of Provocation,\" ''Rhetoric and Public Affairs,'' Summer 2010, Vol. 13 Issue 2, pp.&nbsp;43\u201376\n* [[David Miller (author)|Miller, David]] (1990). ''Chairman Bill: A Biography of William F. Buckley Jr.''. New York\n* Nash, George H. ''The Conservative Intellectual Movement in America Since 1945'' (2006)\n* {{Cite book|first=Mark Royden|last=Winchell|year=1984|title=William F. Buckley Jr.|publisher=Macmillan Publishing Company|location=New York|isbn=0-8057-7431-9|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/williamfbuckleyj0452winc}}\n* Sarchett, Barry W. \"Unreading the Spy Thriller: The Example of William F. Buckley Jr.,\" ''Journal of Popular Culture,'' Fall 1992, Vol. 26 Issue 2, pp.&nbsp;127\u201339, theoretical literary analysis\n* {{Cite book|first=Tamara|last=Straus|year=1997|title=The Literary Almanac: The Best of the Printed Word: 1900 to the Present|publisher=High Tide Press|location=New York|isbn=1-56731-328-0|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/literaryalmanac00mjfb}}\n* {{cite web|title=Writings of Kirk and Buckley|url=http://www.c-span.org/video/?170896-1/writings-kirk-buckley|work=[[American Writers: A Journey Through History]]|publisher=[[C-SPAN]]|accessdate=March 12, 2016}}\n* {{cite web|author=Chris Weinkopf |url=http://www.salon.com/people/feature/1999/09/03/wfb/ |title=William F. Buckley Jr. |publisher=Salon.com |date=1999-09-03 |accessdate=2015-05-06}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.crimemagazine.com/great-prevaricator-0|work=Crime Magazine|date=October 9, 2009|author=Manning, Lona|title=The Great Prevaricator|access-date=November 11, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151008203603/http://www.crimemagazine.com/great-prevaricator-0|archive-date=October 8, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.frontpagemag.com/Articles/ReadArticle.asp?ID=14563 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130123133527/http://www.frontpagemag.com/Articles/ReadArticle.asp?ID=14563 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-23 |title=Miles Gone By |author=Glazov, Jamie |authorlink=Jamie Glazov |publisher=[[FrontPage Magazine]] |accessdate=2015-05-06 }}\n* {{cite web|last=Hickman |first=John |url=http://baltimorechronicle.com/2007/040607Hickman.shtml |title=Happy is the Columnist who has no History |publisher=BaltimoreChronicle.com |date=2007-04-06 |accessdate=2015-05-06}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|commons=Category:William F. Buckley, Jr.|q=William F. Buckley, Jr.|b=no|s=no|n=Journalist William F. Buckley dies at age 82|v=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|118702|William F. Buckley}}\n* [http://cumulus.hillsdale.edu/Buckley/ Buckley Online], a complete guide to the writings William F. Buckley at [[Hillsdale College]]\n* {{C-SPAN|williambuckley}}\n* [http://lccn.loc.gov/n79065205 William F. Buckley] at [[Library of Congress]] Authorities \u2013 with 109 catalog records\n* William F. Buckley's [[FBI]] files, hosted at the [[Internet Archive]]: [https://archive.org/details/foia_Buckley_William_F.-HQ-1 part 1], [https://archive.org/details/foia_Buckley_William_F.-HQ-2 part 2]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ppo}}\n{{S-new|party}}\n{{S-ttl|title= [[Conservative Party of New York|Conservative Party]] nominee for [[Mayor of New York City]]|years=1965}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[John Marchi]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Blackford Oakes|state=expanded}}\n{{Christopher Buckley}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buckley, William F. Jr.}}\n[[Category:William F. Buckley Jr.| ]]\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American anti-communists]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American conservative people]]\n[[Category:American harpsichordists]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American magazine founders]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American people of Canadian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss-German descent]]\n[[Category:American political activists]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholic religious writers]]\n[[Category:American sailors]]\n[[Category:American spies]]\n[[Category:American spy fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American Traditionalist Catholics]]\n[[Category:American travel writers]]\n[[Category:Buckley family]]\n[[Category:Christian libertarians]]\n[[Category:Connecticut Republicans]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party of New York State politicians]]\n[[Category:Critics of Objectivism (Ayn Rand)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from diabetes]]\n[[Category:Deaths from emphysema]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Drug policy reform activists]]\n[[Category:Knights of Malta]]\n[[Category:National Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:National Review people]]\n[[Category:New Right (United States)]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper East Side]]\n[[Category:People of the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Society members]]\n[[Category:Politicians from New York City]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:Traditionalist Catholic writers]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Stamford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Skull and Bones Society]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Manhattan Institute for Policy Research]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other people with a similar name|William F. Buckley (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American conservative author and commentator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|name=William F. Buckley Jr.\n|image=William F. Buckley, Jr. 1985.jpg\n|caption=Buckley at the second inauguration of US President [[Ronald Reagan]] in 1985\n|birth_name=William Francis Buckley\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1925|11|24}}\n|birth_place=[[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|death_date={{death date and age|2008|2|27|1925|11|24}}\n|death_place=[[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]], [[Connecticut]], U.S.\n|occupation={{hlist | Editor | author | political commentator}}\n|alma_mater=[[Yale University]]\n|subject={{hlist | [[Conservatism in the United States|American conservatism]] | politics | [[anti-communism]] | [[espionage]]}}\n|spouse={{marriage|[[Patricia Buckley|Patricia Taylor Buckley]]|1950|2007|end=died}}\n|children=[[Christopher Buckley (novelist)|Christopher Buckley]]\n|relatives={{plainlist|\n*[[James L. Buckley]] (brother)\n*[[Patricia Buckley Bozell]] (sister)\n*[[Reid Buckley]] (brother)\n*[[L. Brent Bozell Jr.]] (brother-in-law)\n*[[L. Brent Bozell III]] (nephew)\n*[[William F.&nbsp;B. O'Reilly]] (nephew)}}\n<!-- Infobox writer no longer supports the fields influences and influenced. See TALK\n [[Talk:William F. Buckley Jr.#Influences/influenced]] -->\n| module = {{Infobox military person |embed=yes\n   |branch       = [[United States Army]]\n   |serviceyears = 1944\u20131946\n   |rank         = [[Second Lieutenant (United States)|Second Lieutenant]]\n   |unit         = \n   |commands     = \n   |battles      = [[World War II]]\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''William Frank Buckley Jr.''' (born '''William Francis Buckley''';<ref>\"William Francis\" in the editorial obituary \"Up From Liberalism\" ''The Wall Street Journal'' February 28, 2008, p. A16; Martin, Douglas, \"William F. Buckley Jr., 82, Dies; Sesquipedalian Spark of Right\", obituary, ''New York Times'', February 28, 2008, which reported that his parents preferred \"Frank\", which would make him a \"Jr.\", but at his christening, the priest \"insisted on a saint's name, so Francis was chosen. When the younger William Buckley was five, he asked to change his middle name to Frank, and his parents agreed. At that point, he became William F. Buckley, Jr.\"</ref> November 24, 1925&nbsp;\u2013 February 27, 2008) was an American [[public intellectual]], [[Racial segregation in the United States|racial segregationist]] and [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] author<ref>Italie, Hillel via ''Associated Press''. [https://archive.today/20121216131901/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2008/02/27/national/a082531S11.DTL&type=politics SFgate.com], ''San Francisco Chronicle'', February 27, 2008. Accessed January 18, 2009.</ref> and commentator. In 1955 Buckley founded ''[[National Review]]'', a magazine that stimulated the conservative movement in the late-20th century United States. Buckley hosted 1,429 episodes of the public affairs television show ''[[Firing Line (TV series)|Firing Line]]'' (1966\u20131999), the longest-running public affairs show in US television history with a single host, where he became known for his distinctive [[Mid-Atlantic accent|Transatlantic]] [[idiolect]] and wide vocabulary.<ref name=WSJ>''The Wall Street Journal'' February 28, 2008, p. A16</ref>\n\nBuckley wrote ''[[God and Man at Yale]]'' (1951) and more than fifty other books on diverse topics, including writing, speaking, history, politics, and sailing. His works include a series of novels featuring fictitious [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] agent [[Blackford Oakes]]. He also penned a nationally [[Print syndication|syndicated]] newspaper column.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cumulus.hillsdale.edu/buckley/Standard/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100525170517/http://cumulus.hillsdale.edu/buckley/Standard/index.html|url-status=dead|title=Cumulus.hillsdale.edu|archivedate=May 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTobit\"/>\n\nBuckley called himself either a [[Libertarianism in the United States|libertarian]] or a [[conservativism in the United States|conservative]].<ref>C-SPAN Booknotes October 23, 1993</ref><ref>Buckley, William F. Jr. ''Happy Days Were Here Again: Reflections of a Libertarian Journalist'', Random House, {{ISBN|0-679-40398-1}}, 1993.</ref> [[George H. Nash]], a historian of the modern American conservative movement, said in 2008 that Buckley was \"arguably the most important public intellectual in the United States in the past half century. For an entire generation, he was the preeminent voice of American conservatism and its first great ecumenical figure.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://article.nationalreview.com/print/?q=YmZkMTRmN2MyZjcwYWVhYWI4YjhkNjE5YTA5NmY3ODg|first=George H.|last=Nash|date=February 28, 2008|title=Simply Superlative: Words for Buckley|accessdate=February 29, 2008|publisher=National Review Online|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080303043521/http://article.nationalreview.com/print/?q=YmZkMTRmN2MyZjcwYWVhYWI4YjhkNjE5YTA5NmY3ODg|archivedate=March 3, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Buckley's primary contribution to politics was a [[fusionism (politics)|fusion]] of [[traditionalist conservatism]] and [[classical liberalism]]; it laid the groundwork for the rightward shift in the [[Republican Party United States|Republican Party]] exemplified by [[Barry Goldwater]] and [[Ronald Reagan]].\n\n==Early life==\n{{Conservatism US}}\nBuckley was born November 24, 1925, in [[New York City]], the son of Aloise Josephine Antonia (Steiner) and [[William Frank Buckley Sr.|William Frank Buckley]], a [[Texas]]-born lawyer and oil developer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wargs.com/other/buckley.html|title=Ancestry of William F. Buckley|publisher=}}</ref> His mother, from New Orleans, was of [[Swiss (people)|Swiss-German]], German, and Irish descent, while his paternal grandparents, from [[Hamilton, Ontario]], Canada, were of [[Irish American|Irish]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UBfYAAAAMAAJ|title=The National Cyclopaedia of American Biography: Being the History of the United States as Illustrated in the Lives of the Founders, Builders, and Defenders of the Republic, and of the Men and Women who are Doing the Work and Moulding the Thought of the Present Time|date=January 1, 1967|publisher=University Microfilms|via=Google Books}}</ref> The sixth of ten children, Buckley moved as a boy with his family to Mexico,<ref name=\"Judis2001\">{{cite book|last=Judis|first=John B.|title=William F. Buckley, Jr.: Patron Saint of the Conservatives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aBEpI5h9gAUC&pg=PA29|accessdate=19 June 2016|date=29 January 2001|publisher=Simon and Schuster|location=New York City, NY|isbn=978-0-7432-1797-2|page=29|quote=After leaving Mexico, Will moved his family to New York, where he was raising funds to launch a new oil venture in Venezuela. But he didn't think children should be brought up in the city, and within a year he had bought a 47-acre estate in Sharon, a rustic town of two thousand in the northwestern corner of Connecticut.}}</ref> and then to [[Sharon, Connecticut]], before beginning his formal schooling in Paris, where he attended first grade. By age seven, he received his first formal training in English at a day school in London; his first and second languages were Spanish and French.<ref name=BuckleyJr_2004>{{cite book| first = William F. Jr. | last = Buckley|title=Miles Gone By: A Literary Autobiography|publisher=Regnery Publishing|year=2004}} Early chapters recount his early education and mastery of languages.</ref> As a boy, Buckley developed a love for music, sailing, horses, hunting, and skiing, all interests reflected in his later writings. He was homeschooled through the eighth grade using the Calvert School of Baltimore's Homeschool Curriculum.<ref name=\"Calvert\">{{cite web | url=http://blog.calverteducation.com/calvert/william-f-buckley-jr-calvert-homeschooler/ | title=William F. Buckley Jr. \u2013 Calvert Homeschooler | publisher=Calvert Education | work=Calvert Blog Network \u2013 Alumni | date=January 28, 2014 | accessdate=March 18, 2015}}</ref> Just before World War II, at age 12\u201313, he attended the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] preparatory school [[St John's Beaumont]] in England.\n\nHis father [[William Frank Buckley Sr.]] (1881-1958) was an American oil developer whose wealth was based in Mexico.  He became influential in Mexican politics during the military dictatorship of Victoriano Huerta but was expelled when leftist general [[\u00c1lvaro Obreg\u00f3n]] became president in 1920.  Buckley had nine siblings, including eldest sister Aloise Buckley Heath, a writer and conservative activist;<ref name=\"Obituary\">{{cite news|date=January 21, 1967|title=Aloise Buckley Heath|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2506&dat=19670121&id=VZhJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fAwNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4262,4249647|work=The News and Courier|accessdate=11 Mar 2013}}</ref> sister Maureen Buckley-O'Reilly (1933\u20131964), who married Gerald A. O'Reilly (the CEO of [[Richardson-Vicks]] Drugs); sister Priscilla L. Buckley (author of ''Living It Up With National Review: A Memoir'', for which William wrote the foreword); sister [[Patricia Buckley Bozell]], who was Patricia Taylor's roommate at Vassar before each married; brother [[Reid Buckley]], an author, debate-master, and founder of the Buckley School of Public Speaking; and brother [[James L. Buckley]], who became a U.S. Senator from New York and was later a judge of the [[United States Court of Appeals]] for the [[D.C. Circuit]].<ref>John B. Judis, ''William F. Buckley Jr.'' (2001) pp. 312\u201316, 103</ref>\n\nDuring the war, Buckley's family took in the future British historian [[Alistair Horne]] (son of Sir Allan Horne) as a child war [[Emergency evacuation|evacuee]]. He and Buckley remained lifelong friends. They both attended the [[Millbrook School]] in [[Millbrook, New York]], graduating in 1943. Buckley was a member of the American Boys' Club for the Defense of [[Errol Flynn]] (ABCDEF) during Flynn's trial for statutory rape in 1943. At Millbrook, Buckley founded and edited the school's yearbook, ''The Tamarack''; this was his first experience in publishing. When Buckley was a young man, his father was an acquaintance of libertarian author [[Albert Jay Nock]]. William F. Buckley Sr., encouraged his son to read Nock's works.\n\nAs a youth Buckley developed many musical talents. He played the [[harpsichord]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/embed/evvWbSAZtag|title=Firing Line with William F. Buckley Jr.: William F. Buckley Jr. and the Phoenix Symphony |website=youtube.com|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref> very well, later calling it \"the instrument I love beyond all others\".<ref name=\"Bach\"/> He was an accomplished pianist and appeared once on [[Marian McPartland]]'s [[National Public Radio]] show ''[[Piano Jazz]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/news.php?id=10676 |title=Tanglewood Jazz Festival, September 1\u20133, 2006 in Lenox, Massachusetts |publisher=Allaboutjazz.com |accessdate=2015-05-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120706181429/http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/news.php?id=10676 |archivedate=July 6, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> A great admirer of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]],<ref name=\"Bach\">[https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/07/16/specials/buckley-bach.html Once Again, Buckley Takes On Bach ]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Published October 25, 1992.</ref> Buckley wanted Bach's music played at his funeral.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Charlie Rose|url=http://www.charlierose.com/shows/2006/03/24/1/an-hour-with-editor-william-f-buckleyjr|series=Charlie Rose|network=PBS|airdate=2006-03-24|minutes=50:43|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216202858/http://www.charlierose.com/shows/2006/03/24/1/an-hour-with-editor-william-f-buckleyjr|archivedate=December 16, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Military service, higher education, and the CIA==\nBuckley attended the [[National Autonomous University of Mexico]] (or [[UNAM]]) in 1943. The following year, upon his graduation from the US Army [[Officer Candidate School (U.S. Army)|Officer Candidate School]] (OCS), he was commissioned as a [[Second lieutenant#United States|second lieutenant]] in the [[United States Army]]. In his book ''Miles Gone By'', he briefly recounts being a member of [[Franklin Roosevelt]]'s honor guard upon Roosevelt's death. He served stateside throughout the war at [[Fort Benning]], Georgia; [[Fort Gordon]], Georgia; and [[Fort Sam Houston]], Texas.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Judis |first1=John B. |title=William F. Buckley, Jr.: Patron Saint of the Conservatives |date=2001 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |pages=49-50}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of World War II in 1945, Buckley enrolled at [[Yale University]], where he became a member of the secret [[Skull and Bones]] society<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Alexandra Robbins|last=Robbins|first=Alexandra|title=Secrets of the Tomb: Skull and Bones, the Ivy League, and the Hidden Paths of Power|publisher=[[Little, Brown]]|location=Boston|year=2002|isbn=0-316-72091-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/secretsoftombsku00robb/page/41 41]|url=https://archive.org/details/secretsoftombsku00robb/page/41}}</ref><ref name=biographydotcom>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/search/article.do?id=9230494&page=print|title=Buckley, William F(rank) Jr. (1925\u20132008) Biography|accessdate=February 27, 2008}}{{dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref> and was a masterful debater.<ref name=biographydotcom/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://images.library.yale.edu/madid/oneItem.aspx?id=1809005&q=osterweis&q1=&q2=&qc1=&qc2=&qf1=&qf2=&qn=&qo=&qm=15&qs=1&sid=0&qx=|title=The Manuscripts and Archives Digital Images Database (MADID)|publisher=}}</ref> He was an active member of the [[Yale Political Union#The Conservative Party|Conservative Party]] of the [[Yale Political Union]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digital.library.yale.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/yale-ydn/id/28726/rec/2|title=\"Richard Shapiro Wins PU Debate On Aid To China\", Yale Daily News no. 88 January 22 1948 :: Yale Daily News Historical Archive|last=|first=|date=|website=digital.library.yale.edu|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref> and served as Chairman of the ''[[Yale Daily News]]'' and as an informer for the [[FBI]].<ref>{{Cite book |last = Diamond |first = Sigmund |year = 1992 |title = Compromised Campus: The Collaboration of Universities with the Intelligence Community, 1945\u20131955 |location = New York, NY |publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] |isbn = 978-0-195-05382-1 }} Chapter 7 is devoted to Buckley.</ref> Buckley studied political science, history, and economics at Yale, graduating with honors in 1950.<ref name=biographydotcom/> He excelled on the [[Yale Debate Association|Yale Debate Team]]; under the tutelage of Yale professor [[Rollin G. Osterweis]], Buckley honed his acerbic style.<ref>{{cite web |title=History |website=Osterweis Debate Tournament |url=http://www.yaledebate.org/osterweis/history.html |publisher=Yale Debate Association {{!}} Osterweis Tournament |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1951, along with many other Ivy League alumni, Buckley was recruited into the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA); he served for two years, including one year in Mexico City working on political action for [[E. Howard Hunt]],<ref name=LATimes>{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/mar/04/opinion/op-buckley4|newspaper = Los Angeles Times|title = My friend, E. Howard Hunt|first = William F. |last = Buckley Jr.|date = March 4, 2007|accessdate = May 6, 2015|issn = 0458-3035}}</ref> who was later jailed for his part in the Watergate affair. The two officers remained lifelong friends.<ref>Tad Szulc, ''Compulsive Spy: The Strange Career of E. Howard Hunt'' (New York: Viking, 1974)</ref> In a November 1, 2005, column for ''[[National Review]]'', Buckley recounted that while he worked for the CIA, the only CIA employee he knew was Hunt, his immediate boss. While in Mexico, Buckley edited ''The Road to Yenan'', a book by [[Peru]]vian author Eudocio Ravines.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Marriage and family==\nIn 1950, Buckley married [[Patricia Buckley|Patricia Aldyen Austin \"Pat\" Taylor]] (1926\u20132007), daughter of Canadian industrialist [[Austin Cotterell Taylor|Austin C. Taylor]]. He met Taylor, a Protestant from [[Vancouver]], British Columbia, while she was a student at [[Vassar College]]. She later became a prominent fundraiser for such charitable organizations as the [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]], the Institute of Reconstructive [[Plastic Surgery]] at [[New York University]] Medical Center and the Hospital for Special Surgery. She also raised money for Vietnam War veterans and AIDS patients. On April 15, 2007, Pat Buckley died at age 80 of an infection after a long illness.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/02/27/buckley.obit/index.html CNN] February 27, 2008 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605201516/http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/02/27/buckley.obit/index.html |date=June 5, 2008 }}</ref> After her death, Buckley seemed \"dejected and rudderless\", according to friend [[Christopher Little]].<ref name=rbhc>{{cite web|author=Buck, Rinker|url=http://www.courant.com/news/local/hc-buckleyobit0228.artfeb28,0,6920688,print.story|title=William F. Buckley Jr. 1925\u20132008: Icon Of The Right: Entertaining, Erudite Voice Of Conservatism|work=[[The Hartford Courant]]|date=February 28, 2007|access-date=March 1, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080303161159/http://www.courant.com/news/local/hc-buckleyobit0228.artfeb28,0,6920688,print.story|archive-date=March 3, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nWilliam and Patricia Buckley had one son, author [[Christopher Buckley (novelist)|Christopher Buckley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/01/buckleys200901|title=Bob Colacello on Pat and Bill Buckley|first=Cond\u00e9|last=Nast|website=Vanity Fair}}</ref> They lived at 778 Park Avenue in [[Manhattan]].<ref name=\"Park779\">{{cite news |last1=Toy |first1=Vivian S. |title=A Liberal Price Cut |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/21/realestate/21deal1.html |accessdate=5 March 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=March 18, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Religious views==\nBuckley was raised a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] and was a member of the [[Knights of Malta]].<ref>Phelan, Matthew (2011-02-28) [http://www.salon.com/news/politics/war_room/2011/02/28/seymour_hersh_whowhatwhy/index.html Seymour Hersh and the men who want him committed] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110302123501/http://www.salon.com/news/politics/war_room/2011/02/28/seymour_hersh_whowhatwhy/index.html |date=March 2, 2011 }}, ''[[Salon.com]]''</ref> He described his faith by saying, \"I grew up, as reported, in a large family of Catholics without even a decent ration of tentativeness among the lot of us about our religious faith.\"<ref>Buckley, ''Nearer, My God''. p. 241.{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref> When he attended Millbrook School, Buckley was permitted to attend Catholic Mass at a nearby church despite the school's Protestant affiliation. As a youth, he became aware of [[Anti-Catholicism in the United States|anti-Catholic bias]] in the United States through reading ''[[American Freedom and Catholic Power]],'' a [[Paul Blanshard]] book that accused American Catholics of having \"divided loyalties\".{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe release of his first book, ''God and Man at Yale'', in 1951 was met with some specific criticism pertaining to his Catholicism. [[McGeorge Bundy]], dean of Harvard at the time, wrote in ''[[The Atlantic]]'' that \"it seems strange for any Roman Catholic to undertake to speak for the Yale religious tradition\". [[Henry Sloane Coffin]], a Yale trustee, accused Buckley's book of \"being distorted by his Roman Catholic point of view\" and stated that Buckley \"should have attended [[Fordham University|Fordham]] or some similar institution\".<ref>Buckley, ''Nearer, My God''. p. 30.{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn his 1997 book ''Nearer, My God'', Buckley condemned what he viewed as \"the Supreme Court's war against religion in the public school\" and argued that Christian faith was being replaced by \"another God&nbsp;... multiculturalism\".<ref>Buckley, ''Nearer, My God''. p. 37.{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref> As an adult, Buckley regularly attended the [[Tridentine Mass]] in Connecticut.<ref name=\"Ponte\">{{cite news|last=Ponte|first=Lowell|title=Memories of William F. Buckley Jr.|url=http://www.newsmax.com/lowell_ponte/William_Buckley_/2008/02/28/76344.html|work=[[Newsmax]]|date=February 28, 2008|accessdate=February 28, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080302223640/http://www.newsmax.com/lowell_ponte/William_Buckley_/2008/02/28/76344.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archivedate=March 2, 2008}}</ref> He disapproved of the liturgical reforms following the [[Second Vatican Council]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.remnantnewspaper.com/Archives/archive-2008-buckley.htm|title=William F. Buckley on the New Mass|accessdate=July 11, 2008}}</ref> Buckley also revealed an interest in the writings and revelations of the 20th Century Italian writer [[Maria Valtorta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ministryvalues.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1355&Itemid=125|title=William F. Buckley's Fascination with Italian Mystic Maria Valtorta|accessdate=December 25, 2010}}</ref> In his spiritual memoir, Buckley reproduced Valtorta's detailed accounts of Jesus Christ's crucifixion; these accounts were based on Valtorta's visionary experiences of Christ and the mystical revelations she recorded in her book ''[[The Poem of the Man-God]]''.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==First books==\n\n===''God and Man at Yale''===\n[[File:Bozell&Buckley,1954.jpg|thumb|Buckley (right) and [[L. Brent Bozell Jr.]] promote their book ''McCarthy and His Enemies'', 1954]]\n\nBuckley's first book, ''[[God and Man at Yale]]'', was published in 1951. A critique of [[Yale University]], Buckley argued that the school had strayed from its original mission. Critics viewed the work as miscasting the role of [[academic freedom]].<ref>Countryman, Vern (1952). Review of \"William F. Buckley, ''God and Man at Yale''.\" [https://www.jstor.org/stable/793684 ''The Yale Law Journal''], 61.2: 272-83 (\"Once upon a time there was a little boy named William Buckley. Although he was a very little boy, he was much too big for his britches.\").</ref> Buckley himself credited the attention the book received in the media to the \"Introduction\" written by [[John Chamberlain (journalist)|John Chamberlain]], saying that it \"chang[ed] the course of his life\" and that the famous ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine editorial writer had acted out of \"reckless generosity.\"<ref>[[John Chamberlain (journalist)|Chamberlain, John]], ''A Life With the Printed Word'', Chicago: [[Regnery]], 1982, p. 147</ref> William F. Buckley Jr. was referred to in the novel ''[[The Manchurian Candidate]]'' by [[Richard Condon]] in 1959 as \"that fascinating younger fellow who had written about men and God at Yale.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=McCann |first1=David R. |last2=Strauss |first2=Barry S. |title=War and Democracy: A Comparative Study of the Korean War and the Peloponnesian War |date=2015 |publisher=Routledge}}</ref>\n\n===''McCarthy and His Enemies''===\nIn 1954, Buckley and his brother-in-law [[L. Brent Bozell Jr.]] co-authored a book, ''McCarthy and His Enemies''. Bozell worked with Buckley at ''The American Mercury'' in the early 1950s when it was edited by [[William Bradford Huie]].<ref>Judis, ''William F. Buckley Jr.'' (2001) p. 103</ref> The book strongly defended Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]] as a patriotic crusader against communism. The book asserted that \"McCarthyism&nbsp;... is a movement around which men of good will and stern morality can close ranks.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Buckley|first=William F.|year=1954|title=McCarthy and His Enemies: The Record and Its Meaning|page=132|publisher=Regnery Publishing|isbn=0-89526-472-2}}</ref> Buckley edited ''[[The American Mercury]]'' in 1951 and 1952, but left after perceiving newly emerging [[Antisemitism|anti-Semitic]] tendencies in the magazine.<ref name=\"IHT-Obit\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.iht.com/bin/printfriendly.php?id=10482667|title=William F. Buckley Jr. is dead at 82|accessdate=February 27, 2008|last=Martin|first=Douglas|date=February 27, 2008|work=International Herald Tribune}}</ref>\n\n==''National Review''==\nBuckley founded ''[[National Review]]'' in 1955 at a time when there were few publications devoted to conservative commentary. He served as the magazine's editor-in-chief until 1990.<ref name=encyc>[http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1P2-1151505.html Encyclopedia.com] June 10, 1990 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090112173159/http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1P2-1151505.html |date=January 12, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=flashback>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/flashback/flashback200511170846.asp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109203640/http://www.nationalreview.com/flashback/flashback200511170846.asp|url-status=dead|title=National Review|archivedate=January 9, 2009}}</ref> During that time, ''National Review'' became the standard-bearer of [[Conservatism in the United States|American conservatism]], promoting the [[fusionism (politics)|fusion]] of traditional conservatives and [[libertarians]]. Examining postwar conservative intellectual history, Kim Phillips-Fein writes:\n\n{{quote|The most influential synthesis of the subject remains [[George H. Nash]]'s ''The Conservative Intellectual Tradition since 1945''&nbsp;... He argued that postwar conservatism brought together three powerful and partially contradictory intellectual currents that previously had largely been independent of each other: libertarianism, traditionalism, and anticommunism. Each particular strain of thought had predecessors earlier in the twentieth (and even nineteenth) centuries, but they were joined in their distinctive postwar formulation through the leadership of William F. Buckley Jr. and ''National Review.'' The fusion of these different, competing, and not easily reconciled schools of thought led to the creation, Nash argued, of a coherent modern Right.<ref>Kim Phillips-Fein, \"Conservatism: A State of the Field,\" ''Journal of American History,'' (Dec. 2011) 98#3 pp. 723\u201343, quote p. 729</ref><ref>George H. Nash, ''The Conservative Intellectual Tradition since 1945'' (1976)</ref>}}\n\nBuckley sought out intellectuals who were ex-Communists or had once worked on the far Left, including [[Whittaker Chambers]], [[Willi Schlamm|William Schlamm]], [[John Dos Passos]], [[Frank Meyer (political philosopher)|Frank Meyer]] and [[James Burnham]],<ref>John P. Diggins, \"Buckley's Comrades: The Ex-Communist as Conservative,\" ''Dissent'' July 1975, Vol. 22 Issue 4, pp. 370\u201386</ref> as editors and writers for ''National Review''. When Burnham became a senior editor, he urged the adoption of a more pragmatic editorial position that would extend the influence of the magazine toward the political center. Smant (1991) finds that Burnham overcame sometimes heated opposition from other members of the editorial board (including Meyer, Schlamm, William Rickenbacker, and the magazine's publisher, [[William A. Rusher]]), and had a significant impact on both the editorial policy of the magazine and on the thinking of Buckley himself.<ref>Kevin Smant, \"Whither Conservatism? James Burnham and 'National Review,' 1955\u20131964,\" ''Continuity,'' 1991, Issue 15, pp. 83\u201397; Smant, ''Principles and Heresies: Frank S. Meyer and the Shaping of the American Conservative Movement'' (2002) pp. 33\u201366</ref>\n\n===Defining the boundaries of conservatism===\n{{see also|Conservatism in the United States}}\nBuckley and his editors used ''National Review'' to define the boundaries of conservatism and to exclude people, ideas or groups they considered unworthy of the conservative title.<ref>Roger Chapman, ''Culture wars: an encyclopedia of issues, viewpoints, and voices'' (2009) vol. 1 p. 58</ref> For example, Buckley denounced Ayn Rand, the John Birch Society, George Wallace, racists, white supremacists, and anti-Semites.\n\nWhen he first met author Ayn Rand, according to Buckley, she greeted him with the following: \"You are much too intelligent to believe in God.\"<ref>\"Ayn Rand, R.I.P.\", ''The National Review'', April 2, 1982.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Baker|first1=Hunter|title=The Devil and Ayn Rand: Extending Christian Charity to Galt's Creator|url=http://thefederalist.com/2014/10/07/the-devil-and-ayn-rand-extending-christian-charity-to-john-galts-creator/|website=The Federalist|accessdate=July 31, 2016|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref> In turn, Buckley felt that \"Rand's style, as well as her message, clashed with the conservative ethos\".<ref>Jennifer Burns, ''Goddess of the market: Ayn Rand and the American Right, 1930\u20131980'' (2010) p. 162</ref> He decided that Rand's hostility to religion made her philosophy unacceptable to his understanding of conservatism. After 1957, he attempted to weed her out of the conservative movement by publishing [[Whittaker Chambers]]'s highly negative review of Rand's ''[[Atlas Shrugged]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chambers|first=Whittaker|authorlink=Whittaker Chambers|title=Big Sister is Watching You|url=http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=ZTFlYjgxMjgzYzkyYjI0NDI4YzM3YzAzYTcyMWQxNGU=|publisher=National Review (online reprint October 12, 2007)|date=December 28, 1957|access-date=October 13, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013171258/http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=ZTFlYjgxMjgzYzkyYjI0NDI4YzM3YzAzYTcyMWQxNGU=|archive-date=October 13, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://whittakerchambers.org/articles/nr/bigsister/|last=Chambers|first=Whittaker|authorlink=Whittaker Chambers|title=Big Sister is Watching You|publisher=WhittakerChambers.org|accessdate=March 18, 2012}}</ref> In 1964, he wrote of \"her desiccated philosophy's conclusive incompatibility with the conservative's emphasis on transcendence, intellectual and moral,\" as well as \"the incongruity of tone, that hard, schematic, implacable, unyielding, dogmatism that is in itself intrinsically objectionable, whether it comes from the mouth of [[Ilya Ehrenburg|Ehrenburg]], [[Girolamo Savonarola|Savonarola]]\u2014or Ayn Rand.\"<ref>William F. Buckley Jr., \"Notes toward an Empirical Definition of Conservatism,\" in Frank S. Meyer, ed., ''What is Conservatism?'' (1964) p. 214</ref> Other attacks on Rand were penned by [[Garry Wills]] and [[M. Stanton Evans]]. Nevertheless, Burns argues, her popularity and her influence on the Right forced Buckley and his circle into a reconsideration of how traditional notions of virtue and Christianity could be integrated with all-out support for capitalism.<ref>Jennifer Burns, \"Godless Capitalism: Ayn Rand and the Conservative Movement,\" ''Modern Intellectual History,'' (2004) 1#3 pp. 359\u201385</ref>\n\nDuring the 1950s, Buckley worked to remove [[anti-Semitism]] from the conservative movement and barred holders of those views from working for ''National Review''.<ref name=stnyt8/>\n\nIn 1962, Buckley denounced [[Robert W. Welch Jr.]] and the [[John Birch Society]] in ''National Review'' as \"far removed from common sense\" and urged the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] to purge itself of Welch's influence.<ref>William F. Buckley Jr., \"Goldwater, the John Birch Society, and Me\". [http://www.commentarymagazine.com/article/goldwater-the-john-birch-society-and-me/ ''Commentary'' (March 2008) online]</ref>\n\n===Views on race and segregation===\nIn the 1950s and early 1960s, Buckley opposed federal civil rights legislation and expressed support for continued racial segregation in the South. In ''Freedom Is Not Enough: The Opening of the American Workplace'', author Nancy MacLean states that ''National Review'' made [[James J. Kilpatrick]]\u2014a prominent supporter of segregation in the South\u2014\"its voice on the [[civil rights movement]] and the Constitution, as Buckley and Kilpatrick united North and South in a shared vision for the nation that included upholding [[white supremacy]]\".<ref>Nancy MacLean, ''Freedom Is Not Enough: The Opening of the American Workplace'' (2008) p. 46</ref> In the August 24, 1957 issue of ''National Review'', Buckley's editorial \"Why the South Must Prevail\" spoke out explicitly in favor of temporary segregation in the South until \"long term equality could be achieved\". It argued that \"the central question that emerges&nbsp;... is whether the White community in the South is entitled to take such measures as are necessary to prevail, politically and culturally, in areas where it does not predominate numerically? The sobering answer is Yes\u2014the White community is so entitled because, for the time being, it is the advanced race.\"<ref>Sean Wilentz, ''The Age of Reagan: A History, 1974\u20132008'' (HarperCollins, 2009) p. 471</ref><ref>John B. Judis, ''William F. Buckley Jr.: Patron Saint of the Conservatives'' (2001) p. 138</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://adamgomez.files.wordpress.com/2012/03/whythesouthmustprevail-1957.pdf|title=Why the South Must Prevail|last=Buckley|first=William F.|date=August 24, 1957|work=National Review|access-date=September 16, 2017|volume=4|pages=148\u201349|type=}}</ref> Buckley opined that temporary segregation in the South was a good idea at the time (in 1957) and the black population lacked the education, economic, and cultural development to make racial equality possible. Buckley claimed that the white South had \"the right to impose superior mores for whatever period it takes to effect a genuine cultural equality between the races\".<ref>Judis, ''William F. Buckley Jr.'' p. 138</ref><ref>Stephen J. Whitfield, ''A death in the Delta: the story of Emmett Till'' (Johns Hopkins U.P. p. 11</ref><ref>Jeremy Lott, ''William F. Buckley Jr.'' (2010) p. 136</ref><ref>Joseph Crespinon, ''In Search of another Country: Mississippi and the Conservative Counterrevolution'' (Princeton U.P., 2007) pp. 81\u201382</ref> Two weeks after that editorial was published, another prominent conservative writer, [[L. Brent Bozell Jr.]] (Buckley's brother-in-law), wrote in the ''National Review'': \"This magazine has expressed views on the racial question that I consider dead wrong, and capable of doing great hurt to the promotion of conservative causes. There is a law involved, and a Constitution, and the editorial gives White Southerners leave to violate them both in order to keep the Negro politically impotent.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/buckleywilliamfb0000bogu|url-access=registration|title=Buckley: William F. Buckley Jr. and the Rise of American Conservatism|first=Carl T.|last=Bogus|date=November 1, 2011|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing USA|via=Internet Archive}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bp15_FjIadgC|title=From the New Deal to the New Right: Race and the Southern Origins of Modern Conservatism|first=Joseph E.|last=Lowndes|date=October 1, 2008|publisher=Yale University Press|via=Google Books|isbn=978-0300148282}}</ref>\n\n''[[Politico]]'' indicates that during the administration of [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], Buckley's writing grew more accommodating toward the civil rights movement. In his columns, he \"ridiculed practices designed to keep African Americans off the voter registration rolls\", \"condemned proprietors of commercial establishments who declined service to African Americans in violation of the recently enacted 1964 Civil Rights Act\", and showed \"little patience\" for \"Southern politicians who incited racial violence and race-baited in their campaigns\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/05/13/william-f-buckley-civil-rights-215129|title=How William F. Buckley, Jr., Changed His Mind on Civil Rights|first=Alvin|last=Felzenberg|website=POLITICO Magazine}}</ref> However, Buckley continued to downplay structural racism and place a large amount of blame for lack of economic growth on the black community itself, most prominently during a highly publicized 1965 debate with African-American writer [[James Baldwin]] at the [[Cambridge Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oFeoS41xe7w|title=James Baldwin Debates William F. Buckley (1965)|last=The Riverbends Channel|date=October 27, 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/?id=hAqdBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT23&dq=buckley+and+mailer#v=onepage&q=baldwin&f=false|title=Buckley and Mailer: The Difficult Friendship That Shaped the Sixties|accessdate=June 7, 2015|isbn=9780393248234|last1=Schultz|first1=Kevin M.|date=June 2015}}</ref> In the late 1960s, Buckley disagreed with segregationist [[George Wallace]] and debated against his segregationist platform on ''[[Firing Line (TV series)|Firing Line]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/cognoscenti/2017/03/06/resisting-trump-the-william-f-buckley-jr-way-rich-barlow|title=Anatomy Of A Takedown: William F. Buckley Jr. Vs. George Wallace|website=[[wbur.org]]}}</ref>\n\nBuckley later said he wished ''National Review'' had been more supportive of civil rights legislation in the 1960s.<ref>{{cite book |last=Felzenberg |first=Alvin S. |date=2017 |title=A Man and His Presidents: The Political Odyssey of William F. Buckley Jr. |url= |location=New Haven & London |publisher=Yale University Press |pages=159\u201360\n|isbn=978-0-300-16384-1 |author-link=Alvin S. Felzenberg |quote=I once believed we could evolve our way up from Jim Crow. I was wrong. Federal intervention was necessary.}}</ref> He grew to admire [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] and supported the creation of a [[Martin Luther King, Jr. Day]] national holiday memorializing him.<ref name=stnyt8>Tanenhaus, Sam, [http://papercuts.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/02/27/qa-with-sam-tanenhaus-on-william-f-buckley/ on William F. Buckley], ''Paper Cuts'' blog at ''The New York Times'' website, February 27, 2008.</ref> In 2004, Buckley told ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', \"'I once believed we could evolve our way up from Jim Crow. I was wrong. Federal intervention was necessary.'\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nBuckley attempted in 2004 to clarify his earlier comments on race, saying: \"[T]he point I made about white cultural supremacy was sociological.\" Buckley also linked his usage of the word ''advancement'' to its usage in the name [[NAACP]], stating that \"[the] call for the 'advancement' of colored people presupposes they are behind. Which they were, in 1958, by any standards of measurement.\"<ref name=nytmds/>\n\n===Democracy and communism===\nBuckley's opposition to Communism extended to support for the overthrow and replacement of leftist governments by nondemocratic forces. Buckley supported Spanish [[authoritarian]] dictator General [[Francisco Franco]], who led the rightist military rebellion in its [[Spanish Civil War|military defeat]] of the [[Second Spanish Republic|Spanish Republic]]. He called Franco \"an authentic national hero,\" applauding his overthrow of Spanish Republican \"visionaries, ideologues, Marxists and nihilists.\"<ref>''National Review'', 10/26/57.{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref> He supported the military dictatorship of General [[Augusto Pinochet]], who led the [[1973 Chilean coup d'\u00e9tat|1973 coup]] that overthrew [[Chile]]an president [[Salvador Allende]]'s democratically elected [[Marxist]] government; Buckley referred to Allende as \"a president who was defiling the Chilean constitution and waving proudly the banner of his friend and idol, [[Fidel Castro]].\"<ref>''National Review'', November 23, 1998.{{fcn|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===The Buckley Rule===\n{{quotebox|''National Review'' will support the rightwardmost viable candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/340485/buckley-rule-according-bill-not-karl-neal-b-freeman/page/0/1|title=Buckley Rule \u2013 According to Bill, not Karl|author=Neal B. Freeman|work=National Review Online}}</ref>}}\n\nThe Buckley Rule states that ''National Review'' \"will support the rightwardmost viable candidate\" for a given office. Buckley first stated the Buckley Rule during the 1964 Republican primary election featuring Barry Goldwater and Nelson Rockefeller. The Rule is often misquoted and misapplied as proclaiming support for \"the rightwardmost electable candidate\", or simply the most electable candidate.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murdock |first1=Deroy |title=Follow the Buckley Standard: Vote for Trump |url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2016/11/william-f-buckley-donald-trump-republican-conservative-electable-candidate/ |website=nationalreview.com |publisher=National Review |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''National Review''{{'}}s [[Neal B. Freeman]], the Buckley Rule meant that ''National Review'' would support \"somebody who saw the world as we did. Somebody who would bring credit to our cause. Somebody who, win or lose, would conservatize the Republican party and the country. It meant somebody like Barry Goldwater.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/340485/buckley-rule-according-bill-not-karl-neal-b-freeman/page/0/1|title=Buckley Rule \u2013 According to Bill, not Karl |author=Neal B. Freeman|work=National Review Online}}</ref>\n\n==Political commentary and action==\n===Young Americans for Freedom and Barry Goldwater===\nIn 1960, Buckley helped form [[Young Americans for Freedom]] (YAF). The YAF was guided by principles Buckley called \"The [[Sharon Statement]]\". Buckley was proud of the successful campaign of his older brother, [[James L. Buckley|Jim Buckley]], on the Conservative Party ticket to capture the US Senate seat from New York State held by incumbent Republican [[Charles Goodell]] in 1970, giving very generous credit to the activist support of the New York State chapter of Y.A.F. Buckley served one term in the Senate, then was defeated by Democrat [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]] in 1976.<ref>Judis, ''William F. Buckley Jr.: Patron Saint of the Conservatives'' pp. 185\u201398, 311</ref>\n\nIn 1963\u201364, Buckley mobilized support for the candidacy of Arizona Senator [[Barry Goldwater]], first for the [[History of the Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nomination against New York Governor [[Nelson Rockefeller]] and then for the Presidency. Buckley used ''National Review'' as a forum for mobilizing support for Goldwater.<ref>Judis, ''William F. Buckley Jr.: Patron Saint of the Conservatives'' ch. 10</ref>\n\n===''On the Right''===\nBuckley's column ''On the Right'' was syndicated by [[Universal Press Syndicate]] beginning in 1962. From the early 1970s, his twice-weekly column was distributed to more than 320 newspapers across the country.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quarles |first1=Philip |title=William F. Buckley Jr., Mayoral Candidate, on Political Rhetoric and Theater,1965 |url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/219301-william-buckley/ |website=wnyc.org |publisher=New York Public Radio |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Edgar Herbert Smith Jr.===\nIn 1962, the convicted murderer [[Edgar Smith (murderer)|Edgar Smith]] began a correspondence with Buckley during which Buckley began to doubt Smith's guilt, later stating that the case was \"inherently implausible\".<ref name=\"multiple\">{{cite web|author=Manning, Lona|url=http://www.crimemagazine.com/great-prevaricator-0|title=Edgar Smith: The Great Prevaricator|work=Crime Magazine|date=October 9, 2009|accessdate=March 10, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103083010/http://crimemagazine.com/great-prevaricator-0|archive-date=January 3, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAn article by Buckley in November 1965, published in ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', drew national media attention:\n\n{{quote|Smith said he told Hommell during their brief conversation&nbsp;... on the night of the murder just where he had discarded his pants. The woman who occupies property across the road from which Smith claimed to have thrown the pants&nbsp;... swore at the trial that she had seen Hommell rummaging there the day after the murder. The pants were later found [by the police] near a well-travelled road&nbsp;... Did Hommell find them, and leave them in the other location, thinking to discredit Smith's story, and make sure they would turn up?<ref name=\"multiple\"/>}}\n\nThis brought renewed media interest in a Don Hommell, who Smith claimed was the real killer.<ref name=\"multiple\"/>\n\nIn 1971, Smith was able to have a retrial. He walked free later that year. In 1976, he attempted another murder and was sentenced to life in prison. He also admitted that he had, in fact, committed the first murder with which he had been charged.<ref>{{cite web|author=Stout, David| work=The New York Times|date=September 24, 2017|title=Edgar Smith, Killer Who Duped William F. Buckley, Dies at 83|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/24/nyregion/edgar-smith-killer-who-duped-william-f-buckley-dies-at-83.html}}</ref>\n\n===Mayoral candidacy===\nIn [[1965 New York City mayoral election|1965]], Buckley ran for [[mayor of New York City]] as the candidate for the new [[Conservative Party of New York State|Conservative Party]]. He ran to restore momentum to the conservative cause in the wake of Goldwater's defeat.<ref>Jonathan Schoenwald, ''A Time for Choosing: The Rise of Modern American Conservatism'' (2002) pp. 162\u201389</ref> He tried to take votes away from the relatively [[Rockefeller Republican|liberal Republican]] candidate and fellow Yale alumnus [[John Lindsay]], who later became a Democrat. Buckley did not expect to win; when asked what he would do if he won the race, he responded, \"Demand a recount.\"<ref name=\"tanenhaus\"/> He used an unusual campaign style. During one televised debate with Lindsay, Buckley declined to use his allotted rebuttal time and instead replied, \"I am satisfied to sit back and contemplate my own former eloquence.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.com/general-news/20080228/having-a-beer-with-william-f-buckley-jr|title=Having a beer with William F. Buckley Jr.|date=February 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nTo relieve traffic congestion, Buckley proposed charging drivers a [[congestion pricing|fee to enter the central city]] and creating a network of [[bike lane]]s. He opposed a [[Civilian Complaint Review Board|civilian review board]] for the [[New York Police Department]], which Lindsay had recently introduced to control police corruption and install community policing.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Perlstein|first=Rick|authorlink=Rick Perlstein|title=Nixonland: The Rise of a President and the Fracturing of America|year=2008|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-0-7432-4302-5|pages=144\u201346|title-link=Nixonland: The Rise of a President and the Fracturing of America}}</ref> Buckley finished third with 13.4% of the vote, possibly having inadvertently aided Lindsay's election by instead taking votes from Democratic candidate [[Abe Beame]].<ref name=\"tanenhaus\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/02/magazine/02buckley.html|title=The Buckley Effect|accessdate=November 12, 2007| last = Tanenhaus | first = Sam | work=The New York Times|date=October 2, 2005|authorlink=Sam Tanenhaus}}</ref>\n\n===Break with the Nixon administration===\nIn July 1971, Buckley assembled a group of conservatives to discuss some of Nixon's domestic and foreign policies that the group opposed. In August 1969, Nixon had proposed and later attempted to enact welfare legislation known as the Family Assistance Plan (FAP), which would establish a national income floor of $1600 per year for a family of four.<ref>Small, Melvin (1999). The Presidency of Richard Nixon. University Press of Kansas. {{ISBN|0-7006-0973-3}}.</ref> On the international front he negotiated arms talks with the Soviet Union and initiated relations with China, which Buckley, as a hawk and anti-communist, opposed. The group, known as the Manhattan Twelve, included National Review's publisher [[William A. Rusher]] and editors [[James Burnham]] and [[Frank Meyer (political philosopher)|Frank Meyer]]. Other organizations represented were the newspaper ''[[Human Events]]'', The Conservative Book Club, [[Young Americans for Freedom]], and the [[American Conservative Union]].<ref>Laurence Jurdem. October 25, 2016. ''When National Review Finally Had Enough of Richard Nixon: A Chorus of Disapproval:''  http://laurencejurdem.com/2016/10/when-national-review-finally-had-enough-of-richard-nixon-a-chorus-of-disapproval/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312144232/http://laurencejurdem.com/2016/10/when-national-review-finally-had-enough-of-richard-nixon-a-chorus-of-disapproval/ |date=March 12, 2018 }}</ref> On July 28, 1971, they published a letter announcing that they would no longer support Nixon.<ref>Tad Szulc. July 29, 1971. ''11 Conservatives criticize Nixon'' New York Times. page 7.  https://www.nytimes.com/1971/07/29/archives/11-conservatives-criticize-nixon-headed-by-william-buckley-they.html</ref> The letter said, \"In consideration of his record, the undersigned, who have heretofore generally supported the Nixon Administration, have resolved to suspend our support of the Administration.\" Buckley would later go on to join the administration as a delegate to the UN.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Redman |first1=Eric |title=William Buckley Reports on a Tour of Duty |url=https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/00/07/16/specials/buckley-un.html |website=nytimes.com |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''Firing Line''===\n[[File:William F. Buckley, Jr. with President Reagan 1986.jpg|thumb|Buckley with President [[Ronald Reagan]] at Reagan's birthday celebration, 1986]]\n[[File:Reagan with William F. Buckley, Jr 1988.jpg|thumb|right|Buckley with Reagan in the [[Oval Office]], 1988]]\n\nFor many Americans, Buckley's erudition on his weekly [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] show ''[[Firing Line (TV series)|Firing Line]]'' (1966\u20131999) was their primary exposure to him and his manner of speech, often with vocabulary common in academia but unusual on television.<ref>{{cite book|author=Charles R. Kesler and John B. Kienker|title=Life, Liberty, and the Pursuit of Happiness: Ten Years of the Claremont Review of Books|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O4g_WKk1dOoC&pg=PA86|year=2012|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|page=86|isbn=9781442213357}}</ref>\n\nThroughout his career as a media figure, Buckley had received much criticism\u2014largely from the American left, but also from certain factions on the right, such as the [[John Birch Society]] and its second president, [[Larry McDonald]], as well as from [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivists]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://capmag.com/article.asp?ID=5128|title=William F. Buckley Jr.: The Witch-Doctor is Dead|publisher=Capmag.com|accessdate=2015-05-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114130355/http://capmag.com/article.asp?ID=5128|archive-date=January 14, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953\u201354, long before he founded ''Firing Line'', Buckley was an occasional panelist on the conservative [[Public affairs (broadcasting)|public affairs]] program ''[[Answers for Americans]]'' broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] and based on material from the [[H. L. Hunt]]\u2013supported publication ''Facts Forum''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jfredmacdonald.com/macfilms/Press%20Release%202.htm |title=MacDonald & Associates: Facts Forum press release |publisher=jfredmacdonald.com |accessdate=June 13, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110112234003/http://www.jfredmacdonald.com/macfilms/Press%20Release%202.htm |archivedate=January 12, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Feud with Gore Vidal===\nWhen asked if there was one person with whom Buckley would not share a stage, Buckley's response was [[Gore Vidal]]. Likewise, Vidal's antagonism toward Buckley was well known, even before 1968.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rosen|first1=James|title=The Long, Hot Summer Of '68|journal=National Review|date=7 September 2015|volume=67|issue=16|pages=37\u201342|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/nrd/articles/422804/long-hot-summer-68|accessdate=28 September 2015}}</ref> Buckley appeared in a series of televised debates with Vidal during the [[1968 Republican National Convention]] in Miami and the [[1968 Democratic National Convention|Democratic National Convention]] in Chicago.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/26/movies/buckley-vs-vidal-when-debate-became-bloodsport.html|title=Buckley vs. Vidal: When Debate Became Bloodsport|first=Michael M.|last=Grynbaum|date=July 24, 2015|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nIn their penultimate debate on August 28 of that year, the two disagreed over the actions of the [[Chicago Police Department]] and the protesters at the ongoing convention. In reference to the response of the police involved in supposedly taking down a Viet Cong flag, moderator [[Howard K. Smith]] asked whether raising a Nazi flag during the Second World War would have elicited a similar response. Vidal responded that people were free to state their political views as they saw fit, whereupon Buckley interrupted and noted that people were free to speak their views but others were also free to ostracize them for holding those views, noting that in the US during the Second World War \"some people were pro-[[Nazi]] and they were well treated by those who ostracized them\u2014and I'm for ostracizing people who egg on other people to shoot American Marines and American soldiers. I know you [Vidal] don't care because you have no sense of identification with\u2014\". Vidal then interjected that \"the only sort of [[Crypto-Nazism|pro- or crypto-Nazi]] I can think of is yourself,\" whereupon Smith interjected, \"Now let's not call names.\" Buckley, visibly angered, rose several inches from his seat and replied, \"Now listen, you [[queer]], stop calling me a crypto-Nazi or I'll sock you in your goddamn face, and you'll stay plastered.\"<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Buckley later apologized in print for having called Vidal a \"queer\" in a burst of anger rather than in a clinical context, but also reiterated his distaste for Vidal as an \"evangelist for [[bisexuality]]\": \"The man who in his essays proclaims the normalcy of his affliction, and in his art the desirability of it, is not to be confused with the man who bears his sorrow quietly. The addict is to be pitied and even respected, not the pusher.\"<ref>''Esquire'' (August 1969), p. 132</ref> The debates are chronicled in the 2015 documentary ''[[Best of Enemies (2015 film)|Best of Enemies]]''.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nThis feud continued the following year in the pages of ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', which commissioned essays from both Buckley and Vidal on the television incident. Buckley's essay \"On Experiencing Gore Vidal\" was published in the August 1969 issue. In September, Vidal responded with his own essay, \"A Distasteful Encounter with William F. Buckley\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Gore|last=Vidal|authorlink=Gore Vidal|title=A Distasteful Encounter with William F. Buckley Jr|url=http://www.columbia.edu/~tdk3/vidalesquire69.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050216165523/http://www.columbia.edu/~tdk3/vidalesquire69.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2005-02-16|work=Esquire|pages=140\u201345, 150|date= September 1969|accessdate=February 28, 2008}}</ref> In it Vidal strongly implied that, in 1944, Buckley's unnamed siblings, and possibly Buckley himself, had vandalized a [[Protestantism|Protestant]] church in their [[Sharon, Connecticut]], hometown after the pastor's wife had sold a house to a [[Jewish]] family. He also implied that Buckley was a homosexual<ref name=\"Colacello, 2009\">{{cite news|last1=Colacello|first1=Bob|title=Mr. and Mrs. Right|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/01/buckleys200901|accessdate=22 June 2016|magazine=Vanity Fair|date=January 2009|quote=In follow-up pieces in Esquire, Buckley focused on homosexual themes in Vidal's work, and Vidal responded by implying that Buckley was a homosexual and an anti-Semite, whereupon Buckley sued and Vidal countersued.}}</ref> and a \"racist, antiblack, [[anti-Semite|anti-Semitic]] and a pro-crypto Nazi.\"<ref name=\"NYT_1972\">{{cite news|title=Buckley Drops Vidal Suit, Settles With Esquire|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/03/01/home/vidal-suit.html|accessdate=22 June 2016|newspaper=New York Times|date=September 26, 1972|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124095336/http://www.nytimes.com/books/98/03/01/home/vidal-suit.html|archivedate=January 24, 2016|quote=Mr. Gingrich confirmed that Esquire would publish a statement in its November issue disavowing 'the most vivid statements' of the Vidal article, calling Mr. Buckley 'racist, antiblack, anti-Semitic and a pro-crypto Nazi.'}}</ref> Buckley sued Vidal and ''Esquire'' for libel; Vidal counter-claimed for libel against Buckley, citing Buckley's characterization of Vidal's novel ''[[Myra Breckenridge]]'' as pornography. After Buckley received an out-of-court settlement from ''Esquire'', he also dropped the suit against Vidal. Both cases were dropped,<ref name=NR>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/document/document200412140834.asp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090826230758/http://www.nationalreview.com/document/document200412140834.asp|url-status=dead|title=National Review|archivedate=August 26, 2009}}</ref> with Buckley settling for court costs paid by ''Esquire'' magazine, which had published the piece, while Vidal, who did not sue the magazine, absorbed his own court costs, but neither had paid each other compensation. Buckley also received an editorial apology in the pages of ''Esquire'' as part of the settlement.<ref name=NR/><ref name=\"round\">{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2004/12/20/buckley-and-vidal-one-more-round/ |title=Buckley and Vidal: One More Round |last=Murphy |first=Jarrett |date=December 20, 2004| accessdate=October 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe feud was reopened in 2003 when ''Esquire'' republished the original Vidal essay as part of a collection entitled ''Esquire\u2019s Big Book of Great Writing''. After further litigation, ''Esquire'' agreed to pay $65,000 to Buckley and his attorneys, to destroy every remaining copy of the book that included the Vidal essay, to furnish Buckley's 1969 essay to anyone who asked for it, and to publish an open letter stating that the current management of ''Esquire'' was \"'not aware of the history of this litigation and greatly [regretted] the re-publication of the libels'\" in the 2003 collection.<ref name=round/>\n\nBuckley maintained a philosophical antipathy towards Vidal's other [[wikt:b\u00eate noire|''b\u00eate noire'']], [[Norman Mailer]], calling him \"almost unique in his search for notoriety and absolutely unequalled in his co-existence with it.\"<ref>[http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=YzhhYmYzNjQzM2ViYmMzZmUwNjRiZTQ4YTVmY2I1OTY= National Review]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109170548/http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=YzhhYmYzNjQzM2ViYmMzZmUwNjRiZTQ4YTVmY2I1OTY%3D |date=January 9, 2009 }}</ref> Meanwhile, Mailer summed up Buckley as having a \"second-rate intellect incapable of entertaining two serious thoughts in a row.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/27/business/media/27cnd-buckley.html?_r=1|work=The New York Times|first=Douglas|last=Martin|title=William F. Buckley Jr. Is Dead at 82|date=February 27, 2008}}</ref> After Mailer's 2007 death, however, Buckley wrote warmly about their personal acquaintance.\n\n===Associations with liberal politicians===\nBuckley became close friends with liberal Democratic activist [[Allard K. Lowenstein]]. Buckley featured Lowenstein on numerous ''[[Firing Line (TV series)|Firing Line]]'' programs, publicly endorsed his candidacies for [[United States Congress|US Congress]], and delivered a eulogy at his funeral.<ref>''Firing Line'', [http://hoohila.stanford.edu/firingline/programView2.php?programID=843 \"Allard Lowenstein: A Retrospective\", Episode #415] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104063943/http://hoohila.stanford.edu/firingline/programView2.php?programID=843 |date=November 4, 2013 }}, May 18, 1980</ref><ref>Buckley, William F. Jr., ''On The Firing Line: The Public Life of Our Public Figures'', 1988, pp. 423\u201334</ref>\n\nBuckley was also friends with economist [[John Kenneth Galbraith]]<ref>''The Sydney Morning Herald'', [https://www.smh.com.au/news/obituaries/mordant-wit-perched-atop-manhattan-society/2007/04/27/1177459974997.html?page=2 \"Mordant wit perched atop Manhattan society (Pat Buckley, 1926-2007)\"], Mark McGinness, April 28, 2007</ref><ref>''The Daily Beast'', [http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2008/10/14/sorry-dad-i-was-fired.html \"Buckley Bows Out of National Review\"], Christopher Buckley, October 14, 2008</ref> and former senator and presidential candidate [[George McGovern]],<ref>C-SPAN, [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/80308-1 \"Conservative v. Liberal Ideology\"] (Debate: William F. Buckley v. George S. McGovern), Southeast Missouri State University, April 10, 1997</ref> both of whom he frequently featured or debated on ''[[Firing Line (TV series)|Firing Line]]'' and college campuses. He and Galbraith were also popular for their occasional appearances on ''[[The Today Show]]'', where host [[Frank McGee (journalist)|Frank McGee]] would introduce them and then deftly step aside and defer to the verbal thrust and parry.<ref>Hoover Institute, Stanford University, Library and Archives, [http://hoohila.stanford.edu/firingline The ''Firing Line'' Archive] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150423135750/http://hoohila.stanford.edu/firingline/ |date=April 23, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===United Nations delegate===\nIn 1973, the [[Nixon Administration]] appointed Buckley to serve as a delegate to the United Nations, upon which Buckley would later write a book.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/00/07/16/specials/buckley-un.html|title=William Buckley Reports on a Tour of Duty|publisher=}}</ref> In 1981, Buckley informed President-elect (and personal friend) [[Ronald Reagan]] that he would decline any official position offered to him. Reagan jokingly replied that was too bad, because he had wanted to make Buckley ambassador to (then [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]-occupied) [[Afghanistan]]. Buckley replied that he was willing to take the job but only if he were to be supplied with \"10 divisions of bodyguards\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-6724737060193073610&q=william+buckley|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106215734/http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=-6724737060193073610&q=william+buckley|url-status=dead|title=Google Video|archivedate=January 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Amnesty International===\nIn the late 1960s, Buckley joined the Board of Directors of [[Amnesty International USA]].<ref name=\"newark 1970\">{{cite news|last=Buckley|first=William F.|author-link=William F. Buckley|title=Amnesty International|newspaper=Newark Advocate|page=4|date=April 13, 1970}}</ref> He resigned in January 1978 in protest over the organization's stance against [[capital punishment]] as expressed in its [[Stockholm Declaration]] of 1977, which he said would lead to the \"inevitable sectarianization of the amnesty movement\".<ref name=\"archivaria 1995\">{{cite journal|last=Montgomery|first=Bruce P.|title=Archiving Human Rights: The Records of Amnesty International USA|journal=Archivaria|issue=39|date=Spring 1995|url=http://journals.sfu.ca/archivar/index.php/archivaria/article/view/12073/13055}}</ref>\n\n===Views on HIV/AIDS===\nIn an op-ed piece in ''The New York Times'' on March 18, 1986, Buckley addressed the AIDS epidemic. Calling it \"a fact\" that AIDS is \"the special curse of the homosexual,\" Buckley argued that people infected with the disease should only marry if they agreed to [[sterilization (medicine)|sterilization]] and that universal testing\u2014led by insurance companies, not the government\u2014should be mandatory. Most controversially of all, he wrote: \"Everyone detected with AIDS should be tattooed in the upper forearm, to protect common-needle users, and on the buttocks, to prevent the victimization of other homosexuals.\"<ref>The New York Times, \"Crucial Steps in Combating the Aids Epidemic; Identify All the Carriers,\" March 18, 1986</ref> The piece led to much criticism; some gay activists advocated boycotting Patricia Buckley's fund-raising efforts for AIDS. William Buckley later back-tracked from the piece, but in 2004 he told ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'', \"If the protocol had been accepted, many who caught the infection unguardedly would be alive. Probably over a million.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Interviewed by Deborah Solomon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/11/magazine/way-we-live-now-7-11-04-questions-for-william-f-buckley-conservatively-speaking.html |title=The Way We Live Now, 7/11/04: Questions for William F. Buckley; Conservatively Speaking |publisher=The New York Times Magazine |date=2004-07-11 |accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==Spy novelist==\nIn 1975, Buckley recounted being inspired to write a spy novel by [[Frederick Forsyth]]'s ''[[The Day of the Jackal]]'': \"...&nbsp;If I were to write a book of fiction, I'd like to have a whack at something of that nature.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Interviewed by Sam Vaughan |url=http://www.theparisreview.org/viewinterview.php/prmMID/1395 |title=The Art of Fiction No. 146, William F. Buckley Jr |publisher=Paris Review |date=1925-11-24 |accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref> He went on to explain that he was determined to avoid the moral ambiguity of [[Graham Greene]] and [[John le Carr\u00e9]]. Buckley wrote the 1976 spy novel ''[[Saving the Queen]]'', featuring [[Blackford Oakes]] as a rule-bound CIA agent, based in part on his own CIA experiences. Over the next 30 years, he would write another ten novels featuring Oakes. ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' critic Charlie Rubin wrote that the series \"at its best, evokes [[John O'Hara]] in its precise sense of place amid simmering class hierarchies\".<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/17/books/review/17RUBINL.html?ex=1279339200&en=845293053a63c725&ei=5088 'Last Call for Blackford Oakes': Cocktails With Philby], Charlie Rubin, ''The New York Times'', July 17, 2005</ref> ''[[Stained Glass (novel)|Stained Glass]]'', second in the series, won a 1980 [[National Book Award]] in the [[List of winners of the National Book Award#Miscellaneous 1980 to 1985|one-year category Mystery (paperback)]].<ref name=\"nb a1980\">[https://www.nationalbook.org/awards-prizes/national-book-awards-1980 \"National Book Awards \u2013 1980\"]. [[National Book Foundation]]. Retrieved 2012-02-28. (With essay by Harold Augenbraum from the Awards' 60-year anniversary blog.)</ref><ref group=lower-alpha>From 1980 to 1983 in [[National Book Award#History|National Book Award history]] there were dual awards for hardcover and paperback books in many categories. Most of the paperback award-winners were reprints, including this one.</ref>\n\nBuckley was particularly concerned about the view that what the CIA and the KGB were doing was morally equivalent. He wrote in his memoirs, \"To say that the CIA and the KGB engage in similar practices is the equivalent of saying that the man who pushes an old lady into the path of a hurtling bus is not to be distinguished from the man who pushes an old lady out of the path of a hurtling bus: on the grounds that, after all, in both cases someone is pushing old ladies around.\"<ref>Linda Bridges and John R. Coyne, ''Strictly Right: William F. Buckley Jr. and the American Conservative Movement'' (2007) p. 182</ref>\n\nBuckley began writing on computers in 1982, starting with a [[Zenith Z-89]].<ref name=\"shea19820913\">{{cite news | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EDAEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA25&pg=PA26#v=onepage&q&f=true | title=Buckley finds word processing on Z-89 'liberating' | work=InfoWorld | date=1982-09-13 | accessdate=9 January 2015 | author=Shea, Tom | page=26}}</ref> According to his son, Buckley developed an almost fanatical loyalty to [[WordStar]], installing it on every new PC he got despite its growing obsolescence over the years. Buckley used it to write his last novel, and when asked why he continued using something so outdated, he answered \"They say there's better software, but they also say there's better alphabets.\"\n\n==Later career==\n[[File:William F. Buckley, Jr. with President Bush 2005.jpg|thumb|Buckley shakes hands with President [[George W. Bush]] on October 6, 2005]]\n\nIn 1988, Buckley helped defeat liberal Republican Senator [[Lowell Weicker]] in Connecticut. Buckley organized a committee to campaign against Weicker and endorsed his Democratic opponent, Connecticut Attorney General [[Joseph Lieberman]].<ref>[http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=NGEwNmYxYjRhZmRkZjA4MmM1YzE5MDIzMzJlYjExNmU= National Review]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109212724/http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=NGEwNmYxYjRhZmRkZjA4MmM1YzE5MDIzMzJlYjExNmU%3D |date=January 9, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, Buckley received the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] from President [[George H. W. Bush]]. Upon turning 65 in 1990, he retired from the day-to-day running of the ''National Review''.<ref name=encyc/><ref name=flashback/> He relinquished his controlling shares of ''National Review'' in June 2004 to a pre-selected board of trustees. The following month, he published the memoir ''Miles Gone By''. Buckley continued to write his syndicated newspaper column, as well as opinion pieces for ''National Review'' magazine and ''National Review Online''. He remained the ultimate source of authority at the magazine and also conducted lectures and gave interviews.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=3387080 |title=A Life on the Right: William F. Buckley |publisher=NPR |date= |accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref>\n\n===Views on modern-day conservatism===\nBuckley criticized certain aspects of policy within the modern conservative movement. Of [[George W. Bush]]'s presidency, he said, \"If you had a European prime minister who experienced what we've experienced it would be expected that he would retire or resign.\"<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/07/22/eveningnews/main1826838.shtml |title=Buckley: Bush Not A True Conservative |publisher=CBS News |date=2006-07-22 |accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref>\n\nRegarding the [[War in Iraq]], Buckley stated, \"The reality of the situation is that missions abroad to effect regime change in countries without a bill of rights or democratic tradition are terribly arduous.\" He added: \"This isn't to say that the Iraq war is wrong, or that history will judge it to be wrong. But it is absolutely to say that conservatism implies a certain submission to reality; and this war has an unrealistic frank and is being conscripted by events.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://acuf.org/issues/issue49/051204news.asp|title=Season of Conservative Sloth|accessdate=July 27, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607122729/http://acuf.org/issues/issue49/051204news.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archivedate=June 7, 2007}}</ref> In a February 2006 column published at ''National Review Online'' and distributed by [[Universal Press Syndicate]], Buckley stated unequivocally that, \"One cannot doubt that the American objective in Iraq has failed.\" Buckley has also stated that \"...&nbsp;it's important that we acknowledge in the inner councils of state that it (the war) has failed, so that we should look for opportunities to cope with that failure.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/buckley/buckley200602241451.asp |title=It Didn't Work |accessdate=July 27, 2007 |work=National Review |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702035617/http://www.nationalreview.com/buckley/buckley200602241451.asp |archivedate=July 2, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Jeffrey Hart]], writing in ''[[The American Conservative]]'', Buckley had a \"tragic\" view of the Iraq war: he \"saw it as a disaster and thought that the conservative movement he had created had in effect committed intellectual suicide by failing to maintain critical distance from the Bush administration&nbsp;... At the end of his life, Buckley believed the movement he made had destroyed itself by supporting the war in Iraq.\"<ref>Right at the end, ''[[The American Conservative]], March 24, 2008</ref> Regarding the [[Iraq War troop surge of 2007]], however, it is noted by the editors of ''National Review'' that: \"Buckley initially opposed the surge, but after seeing its early success believed it deserved more time to work.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nrd.nationalreview.com/article/?q=YzllM2IwOGRmODM5YzFhZDEyYjk5MDEwNzBmMTk3MmE=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717033709/http://nrd.nationalreview.com/article/?q=YzllM2IwOGRmODM5YzFhZDEyYjk5MDEwNzBmMTk3MmE%3D|url-status=dead|title=National Review|archivedate=July 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBuckley was an advocate for the legalization of [[marijuana]] and some drug legalization as early as his 1965 candidacy for mayor of New York City.<ref>{{cite journal|date= March 1983|title=Reason Interview: William F. Buckley|journal=Reason |pages=40\u201344|url=http://reason.com/assets/db/159ef03791b35c5bf8537c9cdfd33484.pdf|accessdate=May 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/openmind_ep181|title=The Openmind: Buckley on Drug Legalization|accessdate=July 27, 2007}}</ref> He wrote a pointed pro-marijuana legalization piece for ''National Review'' in 2004 where he calls for conservatives to change their views on legalization, stating, \"We're not going to find someone running for president who advocates reform of those laws. What is required is a genuine republican groundswell. It is happening, but ever so gradually. Two of every five Americans&nbsp;... believe 'the government should treat marijuana more or less the same way it treats alcohol: It should regulate it, control it, tax it, and make it illegal only for children.'\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://old.nationalreview.com/buckley/buckley200406291207.asp|first=William F. Jr.|last=Buckley|title=Free weed. The marijuana debate|accessdate=October 26, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808091214/http://old.nationalreview.com/buckley/buckley200406291207.asp|archivedate=August 8, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In his December 3, 2007 column, shortly after his wife's death, which he attributed, at least in part, to her smoking, Buckley seemed to advocate banning tobacco use in America.<ref name=\"smokingban\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nysun.com/article/67349|title=My Smoking Confessional| last = Buckley | first = William F. Jr. |date=December 3, 2007|accessdate=February 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAbout [[neoconservative]]s, he said in 2004: \"I think those I know, which is most of them, are bright, informed and idealistic, but that they simply overrate the reach of U.S. power and influence.\"<ref name=nytmds>Sanger, Deborah, [https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/11/magazine/11QUESTIONS.html?ei=5070&en=a78be4479c624bcf&ex=1204952400 \"Questions for William F. Buckley: Conservatively Speaking\"], interview in ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'', July 11, 2004. Retrieved March 6, 2008</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sunsite.berkeley.edu/videodir/asx2/2299.asx|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101212011402/http://sunsite.berkeley.edu/videodir/asx2/2299.asx|url-status=dead|title=Video of Buckley debating James Baldwin, October 26, 1965, Cambridge University; digitized by UC Berkeley|archivedate=December 12, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.10zenmonkeys.com/2008/02/28/the-collected-controversies-of-william-f-buckley/ \"The Collected Controversies of William F. Buckley\"], February 28, 2008.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=OWQ4Y2VmNjNmZjhiZTEwOThmNTA3NGY1Y2UwNTE4ZDM= |title=Where does one Start? A Guide to Reading WFB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305130558/http://article.nationalreview.com/?q=OWQ4Y2VmNjNmZjhiZTEwOThmNTA3NGY1Y2UwNTE4ZDM=|archive-date=March 5, 2008|work=National Review|date=February 29, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Johns |first=Michael |url=http://michaeljohnsonfreedomandprosperity.blogspot.com/2008/03/walking-road-that-buckley-built.html |title=Michael Johns: Walking the Road that Buckley Built |publisher=Michaeljohnsonfreedomandprosperity.blogspot.com |date=2008-03-07 |accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref> \n\nVarious organizations have awards and honors named after Buckley.<ref>{{cite web |title=The William F. Buckley Prize Is an Award I\u2019m Unable to Reject |url=https://www.rushlimbaugh.com/daily/2019/10/10/the-william-f-buckley-prize-is-an-award-im-unable-to-reject/ |website=rushlimbaugh.com |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The 8th Annual Buckley Awards |url=https://cei.org/content/8th-annual-buckley-awards |website=cei.org |publisher=Competitive Enterprise Institute |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Intercollegiate Studies Institute]] awards the William F. Buckley Award for Outstanding Campus Journalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legalinsurrection.com/2013/11/oorah-for-the-cornell-review/ |title=Cornell Review &#124; Buckley Award &#124; Collegiate Network |publisher=Legalinsurrection.com |date=2013-11-19 |accessdate=2015-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nBuckley died at his home in [[Stamford, Connecticut]], on February 27, 2008 at the age of 82. Initially, it was reported that he was found dead at his desk in his study, a converted garage. \"He died with his boots on\", his son [[Christopher Buckley (novelist)|Christopher Buckley]] said, \"after a lifetime of riding pretty tall in the saddle.\"<ref name=rbhc/> Subsequently, however, in his 2009 book ''Losing Mum and Pup: A Memoir'', Christopher Buckley admitted that this account was an embellishment on his part: his father had actually been found lying on the floor of his study after suffering a fatal heart attack. At the time of his death, he had been suffering from [[emphysema]] and [[diabetes]].<ref name=\"NYTobit\">{{cite news| first = Douglas | last = Martin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/27/business/media/27cnd-buckley.html?hp|title=William F. Buckley Jr. Is Dead at 82|work=The New York Times|date=February 27, 2008|accessdate=February 27, 2008}}</ref> In a December 3, 2007, column, Buckley commented on the cause of his emphysema, citing his lifelong habit of smoking tobacco, despite endorsing a legal ban of it.<ref name=\"smokingban\"/> Buckley's body was buried at the Saint Bernard Cemetery in [[Sharon, Connecticut]], next to his wife Patricia's.<ref>{{findagrave|24915565|William Frank Buckley, Jr}}</ref>\n\nNotable members of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] political establishment paying tribute to Buckley included President [[George W. Bush]],<ref>{{cite press release|title=Statement by the President on Death of William F. Buckley| last = Bush | first = George W. |publisher=Office of the Press Secretary, the White House|date=February 27, 2008|accessdate=February 28, 2008|url= https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2008/02/20080227-4.html}}</ref> former [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]] [[Newt Gingrich]], and former [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Nancy Reagan]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=Nancy Reagan Reacts To Death Of William F. Buckley| last = Reagan | first = Nancy|publisher=The Office of Nancy Reagan|date=February 27, 2008|accessdate=February 28, 2008|url=http://orangecounty.cox.net/cci/newslocal/local?_mode=view&view=LocalNewsArticleView&articleId=3238791&_action=validatearticle}}</ref> Bush said of Buckley, \"[h]e influenced a lot of people, including me. He captured the imagination of a lot of people.\"<ref name=\"AP Buckley dies\">{{cite news|title=Conservative author Buckley dies at 82|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20080227/ap_on_re_us/obit_buckley|date=February 27, 2008|accessdate=February 28, 2008 | agency = Associated Press | publisher = Yahoo! News | last = Italie | first = Hillele | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080301212442/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20080227/ap_on_re_us/obit_buckley <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> | archivedate = March 1, 2008 }}</ref> Gingrich added, \"Bill Buckley became the indispensable intellectual advocate from whose energy, intelligence, wit, and enthusiasm the best of modern conservatism drew its inspiration and encouragement&nbsp;... Buckley began what led to Senator [[Barry Goldwater]] and his ''[[The Conscience of a Conservative|Conscience of a Conservative]]'' that led to the seizing of power by the conservatives from the moderate establishment within the Republican Party. From that emerged [[Ronald Reagan]].\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://newt.org/tabid/102/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/3207/Default.aspx|title=Before there was Goldwater or Reagan, there was Bill Buckley | accessdate = March 4, 2008|publisher=Newt.org| last = Gingrich | first = Newt | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080306012440/http://newt.org/tabid/102/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/3207/Default.aspx <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->| archivedate = March 6, 2008 }}</ref> Reagan's widow, Nancy, commented, \"Ronnie valued Bill's counsel throughout his political life, and after Ronnie died, Bill and Pat were there for me in so many ways.\"<ref name=\"AP Buckley dies\"/>\n\n==Linguistic expertise==\nBuckley was well known for his command of language.<ref>See Schmidt, Julian. (June 6, 2005) ''[[National Review]]'' Notes & asides. (Letter to the Editor) Volume 53; Issue 2. p. 17. (\"Dear Mr. Buckley: You can call off the hunt for the elusive \"encephalophonic\". I have it cornered in ''Webster's Third New International Dictionary'', where the noun \"encephalophone\" is defined as \"an apparatus that emits a continuous hum whose pitch is changed by interference of brain waves transmitted through oscillators from electrodes attached to the scalp and that is used to diagnose abnormal brain functioning.\" I knew right where to look, because you provoked my search for that word a generation ago, when I first (and not last) encountered it in one of your books. If it was used derisively about you, I can only infer that the reviewer's brain was set a-humming by a) his failure to follow your illaqueating (ensnaring) logic, b) his dizzied awe at your manifold talents, and/or c) his inability to distinguish lexiphanicism (the use of pretentious words) from lectio divina. I say, keep it up. We could all do with more brain vibrations.\")</ref> He came late to formal instruction in English, not learning it until he was seven years old and having earlier learned Spanish and French.<ref name=BuckleyJr_2004 /> Michelle Tsai in ''[[Slate.com|Slate]]'' says that he spoke English with an [[idiosyncrasy|idiosyncratic]] accent: something between an old-fashioned, upper class [[Mid-Atlantic English|Mid-Atlantic accent]], and British [[Received Pronunciation]], with a Southern drawl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2185368/|title=Why Did William F. Buckley Jr. talk like that?|last=Tsai|first=Michelle|work=[[Slate.com|Slate]]|date=February 28, 2008|accessdate=February 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Rhetoric===\nEpstein (1972) argues that liberals were especially fascinated by Buckley, and often wanted to debate him, in part because his ideas resembled their own, for Buckley typically formulated his arguments in reaction to left-liberal opinion, rather than being founded on conservative principles that were alien to the liberals.<ref>Joseph Epstein, \"The Politics of William Buckley: Conservative Ideologue as Liberal Celebrity\", ''Dissent'', Oct 1972, Vol. 19 Issue 4, pp. 602\u201361</ref>\n\nAppel (1992) argues from rhetorical theory that Buckley's essays are often written in \"low\" burlesque in the manner of [[Samuel Butler (poet)|Samuel Butler's]] satirical poem \"[[Hudibras]]\". Considered as drama, such discourse features black-and-white disorder, a guilt-mongering logician, distorted clownish opponents, limited scapegoating, and a self-serving redemption.<ref>Edward C. Appel, \"Burlesque drama as a rhetorical genre: The hudibrastic ridicule of William F. Buckley Jr.,\" Western Journal of Communication, Summer 1996, Vol. 60 Issue 3, pp. 269\u201384</ref>\n\nLee (2008) argues that Buckley introduced a new rhetorical style that conservatives often tried to emulate. The \"gladiatorial style\", as Lee calls it, is flashy and combative, filled with sound bites, and leads to an inflammatory drama. As conservatives encountered Buckley's arguments about government, liberalism and markets, the theatrical appeal of Buckley's gladiatorial style inspired conservative imitators, becoming one of the principal templates for conservative rhetoric.<ref>Michael J. Lee, \"WFB: The Gladiatorial Style and the Politics of Provocation,\" ''Rhetoric and Public Affairs,'' Summer 2010, Vol. 13 Issue 2, pp. 43\u201376</ref>\n\n\"Charm, wit, eye-twinkling and rapid deployment of stray [[factoid]]s were among Buckley\u2019s chief rhetorical assets,\" wrote Thomas Meany in the ''New York Times''. \"His main form of reasoning consisted of forced analogies.\"\n\n==Works==\n{{main|William F. Buckley Jr. bibliography}}\n{{see also|List of Blackford Oakes novels}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External references==\n<!---or maybe additional reading--->\n* Appel, Edward C. \"Burlesque drama as a rhetorical genre: The hudibrastic ridicule of William F. Buckley Jr.\", ''Western Journal of Communication,'' Summer 1996, Vol. 60 Issue 3, pp.&nbsp;269\u201384.\n* {{Cite book|first1=Linda|last1=Bridges|first2=John R. Jr.|last2=Coyne|title=Strictly Right: William F. Buckley Jr. and the American Conservative Movement|year=2007|publisher=Wiley|location=Hoboken|isbn=978-0-471-75817-4|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/strictlyrightwil0000brid}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Reid|last=Buckley|year=1999|title=Strictly Speaking|publisher=McGraw-Hill|location=New York|isbn=0-07-134610-4|url=https://archive.org/details/strictlyspeaking0000buck}}\n* Farber, David. ''The Rise and Fall of Modern American Conservatism: A Short History'' (2010) pp.&nbsp;39\u201376\n* Gottfried, Paul (1993). ''The Conservative Movement''. {{ISBN|0-8057-9749-1}}\n* {{Cite book|first= John B.|last=Judis|authorlink=John Judis|year=1990|title=William F. Buckley Jr.: Patron Saint of the Conservatives|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=978-0-671-45494-4}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Brian|last=Lamb|year=2001|title=Booknotes: Stories from American History|publisher=Penguin|location=New York|isbn=1-58648-083-9|url=https://archive.org/details/booknotesstories00lamb}}\n* Lee, Michael J. \"WFB: The Gladiatorial Style and the Politics of Provocation,\" ''Rhetoric and Public Affairs,'' Summer 2010, Vol. 13 Issue 2, pp.&nbsp;43\u201376\n* [[David Miller (author)|Miller, David]] (1990). ''Chairman Bill: A Biography of William F. Buckley Jr.''. New York\n* Nash, George H. ''The Conservative Intellectual Movement in America Since 1945'' (2006)\n* {{Cite book|first=Mark Royden|last=Winchel